<FIRST>r a AM-ActorsNegotiations     03-09 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Actors Negotiations,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Actors Guilds, Seeking to Avert Strike, Release Contract Demands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an unusual move to avoid another
entertainment industry strike, the two largest actors unions
published their contract demands on Wednesday, two months before
negotiations with producers are set to open.
   The joint statement from the local board of the Screen Actors
Guild and the American Federation of Television and Radio Artists
was conciliatory in tone, asking for many of the same contract terms
given to the Writers Guild of America following its six-month strike
last year.
   ``We are attempting to greatly accelerate the bargaining process
in order to keep production going at full steam,'' SAG negotiator
Ken Orsatti said in a statement. ``After last year's painful
writers' strike, we don't believe the industry can withstand another
major work stoppage.''
   The SAG-AFTRA release said the two guilds hoped to avert ``the
long, contentious bargaining process'' when their joint contract
with producers expires June 30.
   SAG-AFTRA negotiations with the Alliance of Motion Picture and
Television Producers are scheduled to begin on May 15. Herb
Steinberg, a spokesman for the producers group, said that it would
have no comment on the SAG-AFTRA proposals.
   In their release, the actors unions said they would accept new
rules for overtime work and a new formula for rerun payments for
one-hour television programs. The guilds also asked that producers
raise minimum wages 4 percent each year in the three-year contract,
improve pension and health plans and revise the payment structure
for foreign television syndication.
   SAG, with roughly 70,000 members, is the nation's largest
performers union. The 68,000-member AFTRA is the second largest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
