<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 0036EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-PanAm-Landing     03-09 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pan Am-Landing,0183</SECOND>
<HEAD>New York-Boston Pan Am Shuttle Forced To Land In Norwood</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORWOOD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Pan American shuttle flight from New York
was forced to make an emergency landing Wednesday night at Norwood
Airport after pilots detected a vibration, a Federal Aviation
Administration official said.
   Pan Am Flight 794 from Kennedy International Airport landed in
Norwood at about 10:10 p.m. He said pilots heard a vibration and
requested a priority landing when the airplane was five miles south
of Norwood, said Michael Ciccarelli of the FAA.
   ``There were 48 people on board and Pan Am is now arranging to
put people in buses to bring them up to Boston,'' Ciccarelli said.
He said the plane has a capacity of 50 people.
   The FAA did not immediately know the cause of the vibration, but
Ciccarelli said the Dehavilland-7 four-engine aircraft landed safely
and was still at Norwood Airport when the control tower closed at 11
p.m.
   The plane will remain at Norwood until Pan Am and the FAA have a
chance to go over it, he said.
</TEXT>
