<DOCNO> AP890309-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 0039EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-Names     03-09 0718</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Names,0744</SECOND>
<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Novelist E.L. Doctorow wondered what he did
wrong to deserve a state writing honor, and fellow award winner
Robert Creeley said he was glad he decided to become a poet instead
of a veterinarian.
   Doctorow got the Edith Wharton Citation of Merit and Creeley
received the Walt Whitman Citation of Merit at a ceremony Wednesday.
   The New York State Writers Institute presented the awards, which
are given every two years and carry a $10,000 stipend. Doctorow and
Creeley also will give two annual readings in the next two years in
the state.
   Doctorow said he was gratified to be declared a new state
resource, but wondered ``what I have done wrong to deserve it.''
   Such honors from official sources don't sit well with writers,
who prefer to be ``somewhere between the state bird and the
blasphemer with a price on his head,'' Doctorow said.
   Creeley said he once wanted to be a veterinarian ``because I
thought animals wouldn't mind my ineptitude as would people.'' But a
``tune in my head'' from which words later flowed drew him to
writing, said Creeley.
   Doctorow's books include the just published ``Billy Bathgate''
and ``World's Fair,'' winner of the 1986 National Book Award. His
novel ``Ragtime,'' winner of the 1976 National Book Critics Circle
Award, was acclaimed for its blending of real people, such as Harry
Houdini and Sigmund Freud, with Doctorow's own characters.
   Creeley's awards include two Guggenheim fellowships and the
Robert Frost Medal given by the Poetry Society of America. Creeley
is one of the founders of the Black Mountain school of poetry, which
uses sparse language and natural speech rhythms.
   The awards, instituted two years ago, are named for early 20th
century novelist Wharton, whose fiction revealed the hypocrisies of
New York City society, and the 19th century poet Whitman, a Long
Island native.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angela Lansbury, who recently agreed to stay
for another year on CBS' highest rated show, ``Murder, She Wrote,''
has been named Woman of the Year by the Hollywood Radio &amp; Television
Society.
   She will be honored at the society's 29th International
Broadcasting Awards presentation dinner. An estimated 1,500
advertising and broadcasting executives are expected at the March 22
dinner to name the best television and radio commercials of 1988.
   Miss Lansbury won an Oscar nomination as best supporting actress
in her film in ``Gaslight'' in 1944. She won Tony awards for
Broadway productions of ``Mame,'' ``Dear World,'' ``Gypsy'' and
``Sweeney Todd.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BRIDGETOWN, Barbados (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's Queen Elizabeth II and
Prince Philip have arrived in Barbados for a four-day visit to mark
the 350th anniversary of the Caribbean nation's Parliament.
   Under a tropical sun and warm temperatures, Prime Minister
Erskine Sandiford and Governor General Hugh Springer greeted the
royal couple Wednesday. About 300 other dignitaries, a red carpet
and 21-gun salute welcomed the visiting couple, traveling with a
20-member party. The queen last visited this Caribbean island in
1985.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PENTICTON, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Reagan is due
for a visit this weekend to address employees of Vancouver
millionaire Jim Pattison.
   The former president's spokesman, Mark Weinberg, said Reagan will
come to Penticton, about 150 miles east of Vancouver, to address the
Pattison Group convention. He declined to give further details.
   Two years ago, former U.S. Vice President Walter Mondale
addressed the convention. In 1985, comedian Bob Hope appeared.
   The Pattison Group, a private company with interests in
supermarkets, car dealerships, radio stations and neon lighting, has
annual sales of about $1.89 billion (in Canadian money).
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Princess Diana marked National No Smoking Day by
visiting lung cancer patients at a London hospital and wishing good
luck to smokers trying to kick the habit.
   The princess, who has banned smoking at her Kensington Palace
home and is a patron of the British Lung Foundation, handed out fake
cigarettes containing lists of helpful hints on how to quit.
   Up to a third of Britain's 14.7 million smokers were expected to
try to give up cigarettes Wednesday. On National No Smoking Day last
year, 2.7 million did their best not to light up.
   ``Good luck to all the people who are giving up smoking today,''
the princess told patients at St. Bartholomew's Hospital.
