<FIRST>r i PM-LiberatedPakistan     03-09 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Liberated Pakistan,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bhutto Brings Culture and Color To Pakistan</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED AFTAB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto's first
months in office have brought a splash of color and a dose of
culture to a Pakistan that had grown grim and gray under her
predecessor, President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq.
   But this newfound sense of social freedom has created some deep
conflicts in this Moslem nation of 107 million people.
   A group of Islamic clergy have designated Friday, Bhutto's 99th
day in power, as a day of protest against her allegedly secular
policies. They claim religious law bars a woman from governing an
Islamic country.
   Others disagree, and have welcomed the swift social changes her
young reign has wrought.
   ``We had become a joyless society before she hit the scene,''
said a senior Pakistani diplomat who requested anonymity.
   Zia, who died in a plane crash in August, ruled 11 years under a
combination of martial law and strict Islamic practice.
   But Ms. Bhutto, a 35-year-old Oxford and Harvard graduate,
believes Islam should be a religion and not a form of government.
   Her attitude seemed to catch on quickly after she emerged
victorious from the November elections.
   A young, brother-and-sister duo of singers and dancers known as
Nazia and Zohaib were the first act of their kind to to hit the
state-owned television soon after Ms. Bhutto's inauguration on Dec.
2. The one-hour gala left millions of bored Pakistanis humming the
tunes for days.
   Several rightist groups were quick to dub the TV show un-Islamic
and filed lawsuits to seek to have the producers and performers
punished. The courts dismissed the cases.
   Now, a new wave of theatrical satire is rising in the cities of
Rawalpindi, Lahore, and Karachi. The acts are full of barbs aimed at
government bureaucrats.
   One play called ``Divorce Me, My Wife,'' takes a swipe at women's
rule. Several females have begun appearing on the screen without
covering their heads with the traditional ``dopatta,'' or head
scarf, worn even by Bhutto herself in deference to the still
politically strong religious lobby.
   While Ms. Bhutto's cultural openness takes hold, she remains
careful not to unecessarily offend Islamic sensitivity. She has
directed women in government to refrain from shaking hands with men,
Pakistani or foreign.
   Meanwhile, left-leaning Pakistanis such as Ms. Bhutto have
stopped accusing state-run media of being monopolized by the clergy.
   Pakistani newspapers and magazines are enjoying their newfound
liberty with ads and fashion photos featuring shapely female models.
   At a dinner for newspaper editors shortly before his death, Zia
waved copies of newspapers and magazines that displayed fashion
pictures of women.
   ``Are these the publications of an Islamic country?'' Zia
demanded. ``I leave the future decision to you.'' Most of the
editors were blushing.
   While Pakistani women are enjoying newfound liberties, men are
not far behind.
   One of the first masculine items to disappear from government
offices under the new Bhutto era was the traditional, pajama-like
baggy trousers and long shirts which Pakistanis call ``shalwar
kameez.''
   Now, most bureaucrats wear Western business suits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
