<FIRST>r w PM-S&amp;Ls     03-09 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;Ls,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Questions Dual FDIC Role</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of Congress are expressing doubt about
the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.'s ability to supervise the
nation's sickest savings and loans and simultaneously regulate
commercial banks.
   As an interim step in President Bush's plan for the savings and
loan crisis, the FDIC _ a bank regulator _ is taking control of more
than 200 insolvent S&amp;Ls.
   ``I am deeply concerned about the ability of the FDIC to handle
its current workload and to also take on the additional burden
assigned by the Bush plan,'' Rep. Frank Annunzio, D-Ill., chairman
of the House Banking subcommittee on financial institutions, said
Wednesday.
   ``We should not blindly transfer a whole burden of
responsibilities to an agency that clearly has problems of its
own,'' he said, citing reports that seven banks in Texas had not
been examined for the past four years.
   However, FDIC Chairman L. William Seidman said, ``We believe we
are up to the task.''
   Seidman said the FDIC is diverting about 500 bank examiners from
its force of 2,029 to work on S&amp;Ls. He conceded the agency would be
strained for two to three months, but said only 200 to 250 FDIC
examiners would be needed after the initial takeovers.
   In the meantime, the FDIC's list of problem banks has been
declining, he said, and the agency will hire about another 150
examiners by the end of the year. It also is raising salaries to
retain experienced employees, he said.
   White House budget director Richard Darman has agreed to testify
before Annunzio's subcommittee later this month. Initially, Darman
had refused, saying he would testify only before the full banking
committee.
   However, he reversed his position after Annunzio sent a letter to
President Bush complaining that Darman's ``ego problems'' threatened
to delay congressional action on the S&amp;L crisis.
   At another hearing, before the Senate Banking Committee,
commercial bank groups endorsed the Bush plan, which would maintain
separate deposit insurance funds for banks and S&amp;Ls.
   Executives of the U.S. League of Savings Institutions said
earlier this week that the funds should be merged as a way of
forcing banks to help pay for the S&amp;L crisis.
   Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez, D-Texas, chairman of the House Banking
Committee, told reporters he opposes any plan to mingle the S&amp;L and
bank insurance funds.
   ``I believe one drowning man is enough,'' he said.
   Gonzalez said time pressures mean Congress likely will pass the
administration's off-budget borrowing plan for resolving the crisis,
even though he personally favors direct Treasury spending.
   He also said he favors giving S&amp;Ls that concentrate on home
mortgage lending a break in meeting stricter capital standards.
   In related action, Sen. David Durenberger, R-Minn., introduced a
bill Wednesday to repeal tax breaks benefiting buyers of failed
banks and S&amp;Ls. He said tax rules may be encouraging the new owners
to operate the institutions less efficiently. Seidman has asked that
the tax benefits continue beyond their scheduled expiration at the
end of this year.
</TEXT>
