<FIRST>r w PM-SenateTravel     03-09 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Senate Travel,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Official Says He Will Reimburse Any Improper Payments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Sergeant-at-Arms Henry K. Giugni says he
will reimburse the Senate for any improper expenses he submitted
during a dozen taxpayer-financed trips in 1987-88, but insists he
did nothing wrong.
   Giugni said Wednesday he submitted his trip records to the Senate
Rules Committee, and will make the repayments if panel Chairman
Wendell H. Ford, D-Ky., finds ``anything improper.''
   The Senate's second-ranking staff official said in an interview
that he conducted official business on all of the trips, including
the six to the former Honolulu policeman's native Hawaii.
   Giugni said trips that included non-Senate business were only
partially billed to taxpayers.
   Giugni said he traveled to inspect security at senators' state
offices, to check on a computer network he ordered installed, to
provide security at last year's two national political conventions,
and to meet senators' state office staff members.
   ``I've got to be a people person,'' he said. ``They get to know
who the sergeant-at-arms is when they pick up the phone.''
   Serving as the Senate's chief purchasing officer with a $115
million budget, Giugni said, ``I have telecommunications, I have a
computer system to discuss with (Senate) offices. I could have gone
to more places. Hawaii is my own state. I'm more tempted to go to my
state than Texas.''
   Giugni's travels were reported in Wednesday's Washington Post,
which said that he took eight trips to Hawaii from December 1987 to
August 1988. The official disputed that number, saying there were
six trips including one in 1987 for which he was unable to find his
records.
   Another trip to Hawaii in 1987 began in New Orleans, the official
said.
   Giugni said the purpose of an 11-day trip to Hawaii, on which he
was accompanied by two aides, was to familiarize the Capitol police
chief with security problems.
   ``The chief of police had never been to Honolulu, and I wanted
him to look at the security at the federal building,'' Giugni said.
``They have major security problems.''
   Giugni, who has authority over the Capitol police, also set up
meetings between Congress' police chief, Frank A. Kerrigan, and
Hawaii police officials to discuss security.
   On two trips where taxpayers financed only part of the cost,
Giugni said, he went to Hawaii to be master of ceremonies at a Boy
Scout fund-raising function, and to attend a meeting of a hospital
rehabilitation board on which he serves.
   The Post cited figures indicating that Giugni's Dec. 27-30, 1987,
trip to Hawaii, for which he couldn't locate records, cost $2,274.
Giugni billed the Senate $436 for a Feb. 4-8 trip to Honolulu for
the rehabilitation board meeting, after which, the official said, he
visited Senate offices.
   A seven-day trip over the July 4 weekend last year was taken at
the invitation of American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co., which paid for
Giugni's air fare. Giugni charged the Senate for $522.77 in personal
expenses.
   The Capitol Police Board paid for the travel of Giugni and
Kerrigan on their trip to Hawaii, but Giugni's budget paid $1,195
for his per diem expenses. The $5,779 travel and per diem expenses
of Giugni's two aides were charged to the sergeant-at-arms budget.
   Giugni's other trips during the past two years included visits to
Miami, Atlanta, New Orleans, Las Vegas and Reno in Nevada, El Paso,
Texas, and New Mexico, he said.
</TEXT>
