<FIRST>r p PM-Atwater-Blacks     03-09 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Atwater-Blacks,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Resentment Over Bush Campaign Ads Lingers Among Blacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Republican Party's attempts to attract more
blacks will be hampered by the same resentment over the 1988
presidential campaign that drove GOP Chairman Lee Atwater from the
board of Howard University, black leaders and analysts say.
   ``Using Willie Horton the way he was used was deeply felt within
the black community,'' Rep. John Lewis, D-Ga., said Wednesday,
referring to the black Massachusetts murderer and rapist highlighted
in President Bush's campaign ads.
   For now, however, more of that resentment is aimed at Atwater,
who ran the Bush campaign, than at Bush himself, said Linda Williams
of the Joint Center for Political Studies, an independent group that
focuses on issues of concern to blacks.
   ``A lot of younger blacks and older blacks, too, are willing to
give George Bush a chance, and yet Atwater is in a kind of separate
category right now,'' she said.
   The president was flying to New York late today to be the keynote
speaker at a United Negro College Fund banquet.
   Michelle Stent, director of the fund's Washington legislative
office, said, ``The college fund has a very close and good
relationship with the president and his family.''
   Atwater resigned from the board of overseers at Howard, a
predominantly black school, after protesting students occupied the
administration building and demanded his removal.
   The students cited the Bush campaign ads that featured Horton, a
convicted murderer who escaped while on furlough from a
Massachusetts prison and later raped a Maryland woman. The ads
alleged that Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis
supported allowing convicted murderers weekend furloughs from prison.
   The ads prominently featured a picture of Horton. Democrats,
including Jesse Jackson, contended that they played on racial fears.
   ``The signals that were sent in the Willie Horton ad were not so
much about furloughs, but about race-inciting fears in white people
and creating very painful feelings among African-Americans,''
Jackson said Wednesday.
   ``Unfortunately, Lee Atwater symbolizes the worst of that
situation.''
   Atwater, who was the president's choice to take over as party
leader after the election, has said one of his goals is to attract
more black voters to the GOP.
   He attended a commemorative service in Atlanta for the late
Martin Luther King Jr. An accomplished rhythm and blues guitar
player, Atwater also has made highly publicized appearances with
black musicians including B.B. King.
   ``I think it was a good thing he attended the (King) service,''
said Lewis, a former civil rights activist. But, he went on, ``It's
going to take more than attending a service in honor of Martin
Luther King Jr. It's going to take much more than that.''
   Coming to the defense of Atwater was Alan Keyes, a black who was
the GOP's candidate for Senate in Maryland in 1988.
   Keyes disputed that the Willie Horton ads were racist.
   ``When I look at Willie Horton, I see a criminal, I don't see a
black person,'' he said.
   But Ms. Williams said simply playing the guitar with black
musicians won't be enough to change Atwater's image with blacks.
   ``People are waiting to see from Atwater something more than
symbolism,'' she said. ``He's talked about winning 20 percent or
more of the black vote. He's been on stage with B.B. King and so
forth.
   ``Blacks are beginning to say there's no other group in America
that people think liking their music affects their voter choice.''
</TEXT>
