<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 0251EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-ArcticDrilling     03-09 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arctic Drilling,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Report Ignores Advances in Clean Technology, Senator Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Environmental Protection Agency draft report
detailing damage to the Alaskan tundra from oil drilling was ``very
preliminary'' and gives no reason to stop further oil exploration in
the area, says a Senate backer of drilling.
   The report, leaked to The New York Times, has not had adequate
review by EPA managers and requires ``substantial work before it is
finished,'' Sen. Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, said Wednesday.
   ``The EPA was apparently doing some on-site work to establish
information for guidelines they are going to issue in the future,''
he said. ``This is all very preliminary.''
   The draft was a summary of a ``trip report'' after a visit to the
North Slope, said Tom Williams, a member of the Senate Energy and
Natural Resources Committee staff.
   According to a story Sunday in the Times, the draft relates
improper and careless management of chemical oil wastes by companies
in the Prudhoe Bay oilfields.
   Legislation before the committee would allow oil exploration in
the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge, just east of Prudhoe Bay.
   The refuge is considered a promising area for a strike that could
produce as much as 3.2 billion barrels of oil, but it also is the
breeding ground for North America's largest remaining herd of
migratory caribou and the habitat for polar bears, musk oxen,
wolves, arctic foxes, waterfowl and fish.
   The EPA draft report said acres of tundra have been blackened by
chemical spills, oil wastes seeping from drilling pads, stacks of
leaking chemical drums, a mine flooded by a diverted river,
overflowing waste disposal pits and failure to comply with federal
regulations governing the handling of hazardous materials.
   Murkowski said that since the drilling in Prudhoe Bay began,
there have been advancements in technology that minimize damage to
the environment.
   Furthermore, he said, if no oil is found, the area will revert
completely to its natural state.
   But Sen. Timothy Wirth, D-Colo., who opposes the bill, said the
government should establish an overall energy policy before it
starts looking for more oil.
   ``Our policies toward energy conservation are so bad we can't
even get the architect of the Capitol to agree to more efficient
lighting,'' he said. ``We ought to be very aggressively looking at
ways to lessen our dependence on fossil fuel.''
   In reference to the effects of Arctic drilling, Wirth said,
``Anybody who would suggest that what has gone on up there has not
been damaging to the environment is just blowing smoke.''
   Sen. Dale Bumpers, D-Ark., characterized the government's energy
policy as ``go out and find it, dig it up and use it up as fast as
possible.''
   ``I want to hold this bill hostage in exchange for a national
energy policy,'' he said. ``We don't have an energy policy and we
need one.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
