<FIRST>u a AM-Eastern-Interference     03-09 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Interference,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Pilot Says Someone Broke Onto Air Channels With Taunts Of
`Scab'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pilot at strike-crippled Eastern Airlines said
Thursday shouts of ``scab'' and static interfered with his
communications to air traffic controllers as he took off from
Hartsfield-Atlanta International Airport.
   ``The word `scab' was used on the radio,'' said Capt. Roger P.
Pipkin, who was flying Flight 5679 to Miami on Monday with a crew of
six and three passengers aboard the Boeing 757.
   ``I haven't said that any danger was posed. But if frequencies
are going to be used for reasons other than air traffic control then
we have a problem,'' said Pipkin, who has flown for Eastern for 27
years. ``I have no idea who the voices were. I have no idea who
caused the interference.''
   Pipkin said the interference, which lasted seven minutes, was on
four separate frequencies and occurred during ``taxi out, take off
and climb out.''
   Voices were heard on three of the frequencies and static was on
the fourth, said Pipkin, who claimed the interference blocked a call
clearing him to a new heading.
   Jack Barker, spokesman for the Federal Aviation Administration in
Atlanta, said the incident was reported to the FBI.
   ``There was some interference on the frequencies from some
unknown person on the air,'' Barker said. ``The pilot was able to
communicate. There just was other spurious transmissions on the
frequency.''
   ``We were of course involved,'' Barker added. ``We had an
inspector meet the plane in Miami ... the FBI has it now.''
   Air Line Pilots Association members contacted in Miami said it
was the first they had heard of the incident, and doubted that any
of their members were responsible.
   ``I find it highly unlikely that an ALPA pilot would do it. It
could have been anybody,'' said Jack Gordon, an Eastern pilot at the
ALPA communications center in Miami.
   Pipkin, 52, is one of the few Eastern pilots who crossed picket
lines. Nearly 3,600 APLA pilots at Eastern have honored a strike by
the Miami-based carrier's 8,500 Machinists, who walked off the job
Saturday.
</TEXT>
