<DOCNO> AP890309-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 0239EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-MedicareLapse     03-09 0619</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Medicare Lapse,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Many Elderly Paying Unnecessary Medicare Premiums, Survey Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Only nine states began paying Medicare premiums
for the elderly poor under a law that took effect Jan. 1, and less
than half have begun taking steps to inform would-be beneficiaries
they are eligible, a new survey says.
   As a result, many of the elderly still have $31.90 a month
deducted from their Social Security checks although the
state-federal Medicaid program is supposed to pay the Medicare
premium for those who live significantly below the poverty line.
   The $31.90 covers the optional portion of Medicare that pays
doctor bills.
   ``This is completely unacceptable,'' Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Calif.,
said Wednesday. ``The purpose of this `Medicare buy-in' requirement
was to protect the poorest of the elderly and disabled from what at
their income levels is an extreme financial burden.''
   Waxman's remarks and the Villers Foundation survey dealt with a
requirement in legislation to expand the Medicare program, including
coverage of catastrophic illness, starting Jan. 1.
   The requirement says states must use their Medicaid programs to
pay Medicare premiums and other costs for beneficiaries with incomes
below 85 percent of the poverty line.
   Waxman, a main force behind the new legislation, said widespread
failure of states to comply ``may well be an ominous sign for other
mandates coming down the line.''
   He referred to such things as expanded Medicaid coverage for
pregnant women and newborn infants that also have been switched from
optional to mandatory, but have not taken effect yet.
   Under the Medicare expansion, all but five states are required to
pay Medicare premiums for recipients with incomes below 85 percent
of the official poverty line _ $5,980 for an individual or $8,020
for a couple.
   Moreover, Medicaid is supposed to pay any hospital deductibles or
other co-payments that otherwise would be required of Medicare
beneficiaries.
   The five with exceptions _ Hawaii, Illinois, North Carolina, Ohio
and Utah _ are supposed to cover Medicare recipients up to 80
percent of the poverty line in the first year.
   Within five years, all states and the District of Columbia are
supposed to be paying the premiums for Medicare recipients up to 100
percent of the poverty line.
   Medicaid is the state-federal health program for the poor and
Medicare, the federal health program for the elderly and disabled.
   There are an estimated 3.5 million elderly Americans living below
the poverty line, but roughly 1 million are so poor they already
have their Medicare costs picked up by Medicaid.
   The Congressional Budget Office estimates that of the remaining
2.5 million or so who would be eligible, 590,000 will actually sign
up for the $31.90 benefit program.
   Ronald F. Pollack, executive director of the Villers Foundation,
said only nine states started providing coverage Jan. 1 as required:
Florida, Iowa, Maine, Nevada, New Jersey, North Dakota, Ohio,
Pennsylvania and South Dakota.
   Waxman said he did not know whether the fault for the others'
failure was at the local level or failure of federal officials to
get guidelines out in time.
   At any rate, he said: ``Where the fault lies ... is really not
the issue. We need to assure, as quickly as possible, that
low-income Medicare beneficiaries in all states are protected from
catastrophic Medicare cost-sharing.''
   Pollack said the most disturbing finding of the survey, conducted
for Villers by Sarah Shuptrine &amp; Associates of Columbia, S.C., was
that only 24 states and the District of Columbia have taken concrete
steps toward notifying poor Medicare beneficaries in their
jurisdictions that they may be eligible to have Medicaid pay their
Medicare premiums.
   Villers is a private foundation that concentrates on issues
affecting the poor, particularly the elderly poor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890309-0025 </DOCNO>
