<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     03-09 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents of 5th graf.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SHREVEPORT, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Call it the crawfish war.
   When Texas Agriculture Commissioner Jim Hightower said Louisiana
crawfish are smaller, smellier, dirtier, dumber and less tasty than
those in the Lone Star State, his counterpart in Louisiana was quick
to respond.
   ``Jim Hightower will have to back out and crawl,'' Commissioner
Bob Odom said Wednesday, referring to the way a startled crawfish
runs from danger.
   ``The one market we've gone head to head with Texas crawfish has
been in the Swedish market,'' Odom said.
   ``Louisiana beat the hell out of them.''
   But Hightower crowed about his state's crawfish, saying the Texas
variety were cleaner because packers put them through a brief fast
to clean out intestinal impurities.
   ``At long last we have a pure Texas crawfish that is going to
save us Texans from the shame and humiliation that we have
experienced over the last many, many generations of having to eat
those smelly, mud-coated, itty-bitty, slow-witted crawfish from
Louisiana,'' Hightower said.
   The crawfish skirmish is of no little consequence. Hightower
estimated that the crawfish industry could mean $120 million in
direct sales for Texas farmers and about 1,000 jobs.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BROKEN ARROW, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jennifer Brown isn't looking for a
little Michelangelo, but she did teach her middle school art
students something about the difficulties of painting the ceiling of
the Sistine Chapel.
   Ms. Brown's students at the Childers Middle School were required
recently to draw on paper taped to the bottom of their desks.
   ``There were a lot of moans and groans,'' she said. ``Some
thought it was cruel. Some thought it was cool. But once they got
started I think most of the students enjoyed it.''
   The youngsters spent parts of three days on their backs, drawing
a likeness of their hands.
   ``Michelangelo painted figures on the ceiling of the Sistine
Chapel, so we painted hands instead, which is a part of the body, at
least,'' she said.
   The teacher said some students who had trouble with other
assignments excelled on this project. ``I joked with some of them
that they would have to draw on their backs all the time,'' Ms.
Brown said.
</TEXT>
