<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines     03-09 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coup Leader Nabbed By Soldiers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government troops today arrested a
renegade military officer sought in a series of coup plots allegedly
financed by ousted President Ferdinand Marcos, military officials
said.
   President Corazon Aquino congratulated the armed forces and said
the capture of former Lt. Col. Reynaldo Cabauatan after a two-year
manhunt ``will lead to greater stability in this country.''
   Brig. Gen. Pantaleon Dumlao said Cabauatan, who was wearing
civilian clothes and disguised with eyeglasses and a goatee, was
arrested by soldiers as he left a suburban Manila restaurant after
midnight.
   Dumlao said soldiers, tipped off earlier that Cabauatan would be
at the restaurant, initially did not recognize the renegade officer
when they arrived at the restaurant.
   But Dumlao said one soldier saluted a bearded man who resembled
Cabauatan, and Cabauatan instinctively returned it, leading to his
arrest.
   Cabauatan was taken to the Philippine Constabulary's Camp Crame,
where authorities presented him briefly at a news conference. No
interviews were allowed. Cabauatan shook his head no when reporters
asked him to make a statement.
   Cabauatan, 42, was the most prominent anti-Aquino military figure
captured since the December 1987 arrest of former Lt. Col. Gregorio
``Gringo'' Honasan, leader of the Aug. 28, 1987 coup attempt in
which 53 people were killed and hundreds wounded.
   Honasan escaped in April and remains at large.
   Cabauatan was sought after a January 1987 coup attempt, when
renegade soldiers stormed military and news media facilities in the
capital. The government called it an attempt to restore Marcos to
power.
   He also took part in an abortive coup at The Manila Hotel in July
1986 and was linked to an attack on the stockade at Manila's Fort
Bonifacio the following April.
   Maj. Gen. Ramon Montano, head of the Philippines Constabulary,
said the military had ``very strong indications that the money being
used by this group came from ex-President Marcos,'' who fled to
exile in Hawaii after being ousted in a February 1986
military-civilian uprising.
   Cabauatan went underground after the January 1987 coup attempt.
   He gave frequent clandestine news conferences to announce the
organization of the Nationalist Army of the Philippines to continue
his struggle against Mrs. Aquino.
   Military officials said they were preparing several rebellion
charges against him in addition to the two existing mutiny cases.
</TEXT>
