<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     03-09 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Plunge, Dollar Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices plunged on the Tokyo Stock Exchange
Thursday, while the dollar edged up against the Japanese yen.
   The dollar closed at 129.23 yen, up 0.50 yen from Wednesday's
128.73-yen finish. The currency, which opened at 129.32 yen, moved
in a range of 129.10-129.40 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 100.28-point
loser the previous day, shed another 181.21 points, or 0.57 percent,
to end trading at 31,656.45.
   Dealers said the stock index fell as investors stepped to the
sidelines because of the weakening yen.
   Buying interest was also discouraged by news reports Thursday
saying that U.S. sources suspected some Japanese companies,
including Mitsubishi Heavy Industry, were involved in a chemical
weapons plant in Libya, said a trader with Daiwa Securities in Tokyo.
   Affected by the news, Mitsubishi-related issues lost ground, he
added, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   ``Trading was inactive and lacking incentives due to a
wait-and-see attitude among participants who are also waiting for
the U.S. employment figure due out Friday,'' the dealer added.
   The U.S. Commerce Department is to announce the nation's jobless
rate for February on Friday.
   In currency dealings, the dollar opened higher in Tokyo following
overnight gains in New York in response to comments by Michael
Boskin, chairman of President Bush's Council of Economic Adivsers,
said an analyst with a commercial bank in Tokyo.
   Speaking before a congressional committee, Boskin said the
administration has ``not ruled out a discussion'' of taxes as part
of budget negotiations with Congress. Some analysts said the
comments were good news for the dollar.
   But the dollar-yen rate in Tokyo moved in a tight range in the
absence of major market-affecting news, said the analyst. ``Trading
was inactive except for some position adjustments and profit-taking
by speculative investors,'' he said, speaking anonymously.
</TEXT>
