<FIRST>r i PM-Salvador     03-09 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador,0411</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Call Off Talks with Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist rebels say time has run
out on their offer to hold peace talks with the government and they
are now calling for a boycott of the March 19 presidential elections.
   But the guerrillas, in a communique, said they may resume
discussions with political leaders after the vote and that they
favor participation in the election by the leftist political front
with which they maintain links.
   The rebel announcement Wednesday put at least a temporary end to
the peace process they initiated Jan. 24 by offering to take part in
the vote and respect its outcome if it were postponed to September
and their security and anti-fraud concerns addressed.
   The Christian Democratic government of President Jose Napoleon
Duarte had failed to arrange talks with the rebel Farabundo Marti
National Liberation Front to consider the plan.
   The opposition rightist Nationalist Republican Alliance, which
controls the legislature and is favored to win the presidency,
vigorously objected to any election delay.
   Noting that the government took more than a month to respond to
the proposal, the rebel communique said that time had run out.
   ``In these conditions of so much delay and deceit ... the
Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front declares that it maintains
its offer of peace and will continue to struggle for it. But it
considers that holding a meeting now with the government .. . would
be to lend ourselves to further deceit of our people and of world
opinion,'' the communique said.
   ``Only after the election, which will be fraudulent, could there
be another attempt to negotiate peace among the (rebels), the
government, the Legislative Assembly and the political parties,''
said the communique, which was called in to a local radio station.
   ``The (front) calls on the masses to combatively repudiate this
fraudulent election,'' it said. The guerrillas have repudiated the
five previous national elections held this decade.
   The rebel communique approved participation in the election by
the Democratic Convergence, the political front that maintains links
with the guerrillas. It said guerrilla combatants ``consider that
the Convergence's participation in the elections, at a disadvantage
and against fraud, is intended to help clear the path toward peace.''
   An estimated 70,000 people, most of them civilians, have died in
the 9-year-old civil war between the Marxist-led guerrillas and the
U.S.-supported government.
</TEXT>
