<FIRST>r w PM-ThirdWorldDebt     03-09 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Third World Debt,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration on Verge of Unveiling New Third World Debt Approach</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration may announce a new
approach to the Third World debt problem by the end of the week,
officials say.
   The Treasury Department has completed its review of the debt
topic, officials said, although the president has not yet approved
the recommended changes.
   Officials said Wednesday if that approval is gained, Treasury
Secretary Nicholas Brady could outline the new administration's
approach to the debt issue when he addresses a conference on Third
World debt at the State Department on Friday.
   Officials would not comment on a published report that the Bush
administration planned several initiatives to encourage banks to
voluntarily forgive a portion of the debt.
   Such an approach would mark a major change from the Baker plan,
which has guided U.S. policy on debt issues since it was first
unveiled by then-Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III in 1985.
   Baker's approach emphasized new lending rather than broadbased
efforts to reduce the debt burden.
   The Wall Street Journal reported in Wednesday's editions that the
Bush administration has been considering proposals that would
involve reduction in interest rates and principal on a portion of
the $1.3 trillion in debt held by developing countries.
   The newspaper reported that the administration plan rules out any
new direct U.S. government spending to support the debt reduction
efforts. Instead, the administration proposal would call for
diverting a portion of existing resources at the World Bank and the
International Monetary Fund to debt reduction and away from making
new loans.
   The new administration is receiving pressure from major U.S.
allies to go beyond the Baker plan and support some sort of
debt-relief program.
   That pressure intensified last week after riots in Venezuela
which were touched off after the newly elected government of Carlos
Andres Perez announced austerity measures as part of an agreement
with the IMF to get more loans for Venezuela, one of Latin America's
biggest debtors.
</TEXT>
