<FIRST>r a PM-Sununu-Deficit     03-09 0634</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sununu-Deficit,0658</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats Say Sununu Masked New Hampshire's Looming Cash Crunch</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMA LOVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. John Sununu made a second career
of pooh-poohing Michael Dukakis' claims about the Massachusetts
economy during the presidential race. Now, Democrats say, the White
House chief of staff is sporting his own black eye.
   Just five days after Sununu announced a state surplus as he left
to serve President Bush, his successor, Judd Gregg, said New
Hampshire was saddled with a deficit. Today, the governor and
legislators are still struggling to keep the state's books in
balance.
   ``Where did Governor Sununu's $10 million surplus go, or was it
never there?'' Democratic state Sen. James St. Jean asked recently
in calling on Sununu and Gregg, both Republicans, to explain.
   House Democratic Leader Mary Chambers proposed that if she were
Gregg, ``I'd punch John Sununu in the nose.''
   Some critics suggest Sununu did to Gregg what he accused his
Democratic predecessor of doing in 1982 _ telling ``the big lie'' by
intentionally masking a deficit.
   Sununu did indeed project a $10 million surplus in the current
$571 million general-spending budget when he bade farewell to
legislators Jan. 4. And Gregg, less than a week later, warned of a
potential $13 million deficit when he cut most state spending by 3
percent for the remainder of the fiscal year.
   What galls critics is that Sununu, in projecting a surplus,
didn't deduct anything for bills he knew were coming due; Gregg did
in predicting a deficit.
   Gregg, however, a former congressman who soundly defeated a
Democratic lawyer in an election to succeed Sununu, defended the
former governor.
   ``You always want to put the best spin on things,'' Gregg said
recently. ``He did what most politicians in his position would have
done.''
   Critics say that in not mentioning the bills Sununu painted too
rosy a picture. Sununu said they weren't listening closely to what
he's been saying for two years.
   ``For folks to say I didn't say revenues were tight is just not
true,'' he said. ``I was the one who said it was going to be a
tough, tough biennium.''
   Sununu was well aware of the bills for programs including lawyers
for poor defendants and court-ordered placements of troubled
juveniles, but he said the amount had not been established.
   Sununu and Gregg also differed on two other critical elements in
the surplus-deficit calculation: how much revenue the state will
take in during the year ending June 30, and how much money will be
left over _ appropriated but not spent _ in various state accounts.
   Together, those differences alone made Sununu about $13 million
more optimistic than Gregg.
   Some Democrats suggest Sununu padded figures to make himself look
good, even as he was criticizing Dukakis, last year's Democratic
presidential candidate, for boasting about the economy in
neighboring Massachusetts.
   But Gregg himself agrees that the deteriorating fiscal picture
wasn't predictable. He does not challenge Sununu's assertion that
when he left, the forecast was for a small surplus even after the
bills were paid.
   ``You could still have been optimistic into December,'' Gregg
said, ``and if I were a departing governor, I suspect I would have
been.''
   Sununu added, ``I felt we still would have been able to manage
it.''
   Even now, Gregg and legislators don't agree on how much money the
state will take in this year. Projecting revenues, Gregg said,
``remains very much a crystal-ball game.''
   Gregg said the main reason is the unpredictability of the state's
business profits tax, its top moneymaker.
   Gregg warned against exaggerating the state's difficulties.
Spending cuts, not tapping the state's rainy day fund or raising
taxes, will take care of the projected deficit, he said.
   ``My sense is we are still in a very manageable problem,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
