<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 0600EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Seabrook     03-09 0599</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Seabrook,0621</SECOND>
<HEAD>In Reversal, New Hampshire Wants To Block Seabrook Tests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MOKRZYCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a break with 15 years of state support
for the Seabrook nuclear power plant, Gov. Judd Gregg announced he
will ask a federal bankruptcy judge to block low-power testing of
the reactor.
   Gregg, who two months ago succeeded staunch Seabrook supporter
John Sununu, said Wednesday the testing shouldn't start until
commercial operation is assured.
   ``If Seabrook never goes on-line (commercially), then low-power
testing will have been a wasted exercise, the resultant
contamination will have been avoidable and the expense will have
been unnecessary,'' the Republican governor said in a statement.
   Seabrook officials hope to start the tests within weeks and begin
commercial operation within a year.
   Spokesman Nicholas Ashooh said Public Service Co. of New
Hampshire officials ``have concerns that this may lead to additional
unnecessary delays and cost increases for Seabrook and may further
delay our getting Seabrook's power, which we need.''
   But Seabrook spokesman Rob Williams sought to play down the
development and said Gregg ``must be misinformed'' about the effects
of low-power testing on the plant.
   Seabrook opponents greeted Gregg's announcement as a major
setback for the long-delayed project.
   ``The one thing the owners could always say was that they had the
state on their side. We're delighted to have company in this
fight,'' said Mary Breslauer, spokeswoman for Massachusetts Attorney
General James Shannon, who has fought Seabrook licensing on the
grounds that Massachusetts residents near the plant could not be
safely evacuated if there were an accident.
   Anti-Seabrook lawyer Robert Backus called Gregg's announcement
``monumentally good news.''
   The $5.9 billion project was completed in July 1986 but remains
idle because of evacuation-planning and financial obstacles.
   Seabrook's main owner, Public Service, sought bankruptcy
protection in January 1988. Other Seabrook owners have been
faltering.
   Gregg said the state will argue to Bankruptcy Judge James Yacos
that letting Seabrook conduct atomic tests is not sound business
judgment ``unless it has first obtained the clearances necessary to
begin full-power operation, including final evacuation plans.''
   Public Service, one of five members of the Seabrook owners'
executive committee, has maintained it does not need Yacos' approval
to start the tests. The judge has not ruled on the issue.
   In December, the U.S. Nuclear Regulatory Commission said
Seabrook's troubled finances do not pose a safety concern for
low-power tests as long as the owners prove they can come up with
$72.1 million to decommission the reactor if the tests are conducted
but the plant never operates commercially.
   Seabrook owners initially hoped to give that assurance in
January, but they have yet to do so.
   Public Service owns 36 percent of Seabrook, and Gregg said the
state opposes letting the company take on what he estimated as $25
million more liability for low-power decommissioning.
   Gregg said that contaminating Seabrook with atomic testing ``will
needlessly render the facility useless for alternate applications.''
   Williams, the Seabrook spokesman, countered: ``There's nothing to
suggest that the plant would be rendered useless. Any contamination
would be negligible.''
   Public Service began the project in 1972, initially planning two
1,150-megawatt reactors at a cost of less than $1 billion, the first
to operate commercially in 1979 and the second in 1981. Seabrook's
owners abandoned the second reactor in 1986.
   The project suffered years of delays over environmental issues,
and in the late 1970s became the site of mass protests, resulting in
more than 2,000 arrests.
   Sununu, who in 1984 helped Public Service sell bonds that paid
for the plant's completion, now is President Bush's chief of staff.
</TEXT>
