<SECOND>PM-SAfrica-Remark,0159</SECOND>
<HEAD>Host of Television Talk Show Under Fire For Racist Remark</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A host of the state-run
television network's morning talk show has taken temporarily leave
after making a racist remark off-camera that was broadcast
nationwide.
   During Wednesday's telecast of ``Good Morning South Africa,''
there was an interview with a black housemaid in which she talked
about problems finding someone to look after her children while she
worked.
   After the interview, a voice was heard to say: ``I'll bet you
she's got 14 children, and each from a different father.''
   The South African Broadcasting Corp. confirmed today that David
Hall-Green, one of the program's four hosts, had made the remark.
The company said the incident was under investigation and Hall-Green
had taken a temporary leave for health reasons ``because he was
under stress.''
   The Labor Party, which controls the mixed-race house of the
three-chambered Parliament, today called for Hall-Green's suspension.
</TEXT>
