<FIRST>r a PM-TeamstersSuit     03-09 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Teamsters Suit,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Agrees To Drop Claims Against Senior Union Official</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has agreed to drop its claims
against the second-ranking Teamsters official in return for his
efforts to increase democracy and fight corruption in the union,
lawyers said.
   The settlement with Weldon Mathis, the union's
secretary-treasurer, was announced in U.S. District Court Wednesday
just days before the government's case against the International
Brotherhood of Teamsters was scheduled to go to trial.
   It remained unclear whether Mathis would go through with the pact
should the union oppose it and demand his resignation.
   In January, after three other officers settled, the Teamsters
board passed a resolution requiring any member of the leadership who
settles with the government to resign from the board. Mathis and his
allies want to remain on the board.
   The government has been negotiating with the union and some of
its leaders in recent weeks. But talks with leaders loyal to union
President William J. McCarthy have ended, said James T. Grady, the
union's general counsel.
   Mathis challenged McCarthy for leadership of the 1.7
million-member union after the death of Jackie Presser in July.
   The government's civil suit seeks to use federal racketeering
laws to oust the union's senior leadership and impose reforms.
Originally named as defendants were the union, 18 members of its
executive board and 26 alleged leaders of organized crime. The trial
is scheduled to begin Monday.
   Also Wednesday, Judge David N. Edelstein separated from the case
all of the government's claims against five reputed organized crime
figures, saying those claims would be tried separately.
   The government previously dropped from the case the 21 other
people it identified as Mafia leaders after some were ordered and
others agreed to refrain from involvement with the union.
 
</TEXT>
