<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 0543EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Soviets-WorldCourt 1stLd-Writethru   03-09 0687</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviets-World Court, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0445,0708</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Accept World Court Authority In Human Rights Treaties</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES thruout with reaction from World Court official, Soviet
envoy's comment. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union says it will accept World
Court rulings in cases involving human rights treaties, a gesture
that signals an end to Soviet resistance to being judged by other
nations.
   State Department officials hailed the move as ``a major step''
and said they hoped the Soviets would now join the United States in
accepting the court's rulings in all but the most sensitive national
security cases.
   The United Nations' legal office on Wednesday released a letter
Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze wrote to
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar withdrawing Soviet
reservations on six human rights treaties.
   His letter suggested, however, that the Soviet Union would agree
to the court's arbitration in all human rights cases. The 15-judge
officially neutral court deals with cases brought by states and has
no authority to deal with complaints filed by private individuals or
organizations.
   Shevardnadze noted that Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev
proposed in his December address to the General Assembly that all
countries recognize World Court jurisdiction ``with respect to the
interpretation and application of human rights agreements.''
   In Geneva, Soviet Deputy Foreign Minister Anatoly L. Adamyshin
said the changes Gorbachev is pursuing are aimed at ``the
development of a state based on the rule of law.''
   ``We want to build it by drawing on the general democratic
achievements of human civilization,'' he said.
   A senior State Department official called the announcement ``a
major step.'' The official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
noted that the Soviets previously contended the court ``was
dominated by Western influences.''
   The Netherlands-based tribunal, formally known as the
International Court of Justice at The Hague, was established in 1945
and is the main judicial arm of the United Nations. While it has no
powers of enforcement, its rulings weigh heavily on world opinion.
   Three years ago, the United States rejected the court's authority
when Nicaragua brought a case charging Washington with trying to
subvert the leftist Sandinista government.
   Washington and Moscow have been holding talks, however, in an
effort to get an agreement with Britain, France and China to
recognize the court's authority in most treaties.
   A World Court official in The Hague today called the Soviet move
a declaration of Moscow's intention to give the court a more
prominent role in international affairs.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said that only
once had the court handled a case involving one of the six treaties
in which Shevardnadze said the Soviets would recognize the court's
binding jurisdiction
   They are:
   _The 1984 Convention Against Torture and Other Cruel, Inhuman or
Degrading Treatment or Punishment.
   _The 1979 Convention on the Elimination All Forms of
Discrimination Against Women;
   _The 1965 International Convention on the Elimination of All
Forms of Racial Discrimination;
   _The 1952 Convention on the Political Rights of Women;
   _The 1949 Convention for the Suppression of the Traffic in
Persons and of the Exploitation of the Prostitutions of Others;
   _The 1948 Convention on the Prevention and Punishment of the
Crime of Genocide.
   Moscow had signed the treaties, but said it did not accept World
Court authority in disputes.
   U.S. and Soviet legal experts have held two rounds of talks since
July aimed at strengthening the court's authority in all but the
most sensitive political cases.
   Washington also suggests that the United States, Soviet Union,
China, Britain and France declare certain cases inappropriate for
the court's jurisdiction, such as national security issues or the
use of force.
   That would avoid cases such as the 1986 Nicaraguan-U.S. dispute,
in which Nicaragua charged the United States was illegally mining
its harbors. After the World Court ruled it had jurisdiction in the
case, the United States refused to appear before the tribunal or
honor its verdict, which favored the Sandinistas.
   In 1946, the United States had accepted the compulsory
jurisdiction of the World Court in all cases except those within the
jurisdiction of U.S. courts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
