<FIRST>r a PM-PersistentDefendant     03-09 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Persistent Defendant,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Persistence Pays For Man Wrongly Accused In Theft Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If you don't believe that it pays to be
persistent, just ask Michael Ray Tanner. But be sure you ask the
right Michael Ray Tanner.
   The Michael Ray Tanner who knows that persistence pays is the
same man who finally convinced a Harris County prosecutor that the
wrong man had been arrested on a felony theft charge.
   But it wasn't easy. Tanner said even the woman who was with him
when he was arrested won't talk to him.
   A Harris County deputy arrested Tanner on Feb. 12 on a 1986
warrant accusing him of stealing $6,000 worth of computer discs.
Tanner, a 31-year-old electronics technician from suburban Katy,
took an unusual step to prove he was the wrong man.
   He began calling prosecutor Ruben Perez.
   Perez said: ``I told him I shouldn't be talking to him and that
anything he said could be used against him, but he just kept telling
me we had the wrong man. ... Finally I started to sense a ring of
credibility. He literally convinced me on the phone.''
   The matter was resolved Wednesday during a confrontation between
Tanner and Joseph H. Wofford Jr., whose tapes had been stolen three
years ago.
   Wofford took one look at the technician in the courtroom and told
Perez that Tanner was not the Michael Ray Tanner who had stolen the
tapes.
   The judge then signed a dismissal order that exonerated the
innocent Tanner.
   The other Tanner, 35, who is accused of taking 20 discs from
Wofford's business and attempting to ransom them back for $1,500, is
still at large, authorities say.
   The younger Tanner said his problems began when his Jeep got
stuck in the mud. A deputy who came out to help ran a check on the
man's driver's license and arrested him on the old warrant.
   ``I was on a date with a girl I'd just met, and now she won't
even talk to me,'' Tanner lamented. ``The deputy wouldn't even let
me go back to the Jeep to tell her. He said, `I'll take care of
it.'''
   Tanner spent most of a day in jail before paying a bondsman $300
to post a $2,000 bond.
   Tanner said he never hired a lawyer, choosing instead to take his
case directly to Perez.
   ``If I'd been guilty, I sure wouldn't have called him, but I had
nothing to lose,'' Tanner said. ``I had to do something.''
</TEXT>
