<FIRST>r a PM-PlaneCrash     03-09 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Plane Crash,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Dead In Collision Of 2 Planes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WATKINS, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small plane and a home-built aircraft
apparently collided in the air, killing four men, including three
members of one family, authorities said.
   Witnesses said they watched one of the planes, a single-engine
Cessna, plummet into a muddy field Wednesday afternoon near
Interstate 70 about 15 miles east of Denver.
   ``I just heard a snap, like a collision. When I looked up, I saw
the right wing of an aircraft had been torn off and it was spiraling
to the ground,'' said Rorie Barta of Basalt, who was at the Watkins
truck stop at the time.
   Another witness, truck stop attendant Gene Newman, also saw the
wing come off and then watched the Cessna drop ``like a wet potato.''
   ``It looked like a wing came off _ that one (the Cessna) just
looked like it dropped,'' said Newman. ``I never did see the other
plane.''
   Greg Feith, an investigator for the National Transportation
Safety Board in Denver, said three men were found dead in the
wreckage of the four-seat Cessna 172K in a muddy field about a mile
southeast of Watkins.
   Another man was found dead amid the debris of the home-built,
single-seat fiberglass and wood aircraft 300 yards away, said Arnold
Scott of the NTSB.
   Frederick Lee Wright, 37, of Akron was identified as the pilot of
the Cessna, which also carried his brother-in-law, Craig Andrew
Willeke, 34, of Otis, and father, Harold Lee Wright, 67, of Akron,
according to Arapahoe County chief deputy coroner Jim Stork.
   The pilot of the home-built plane, a Quickie Q-2 model, was
identified as Robert M. Bucy, 41, of Aurora.
   Scott said he would attempt to confirm today whether there was an
in-flight collision, although witnesses said pieces from the
home-built craft were found close to the crashed Cessna.
   Feith and Lt. John Maki of the County Sheriff's Department said
it was possible one or both of the planes' pilots may have been
watching area fire departments battle a brush fire two miles south
of the crash scene when they collided.
   The Cessna was believed to have taken off from Akron, 90 miles
northeast of Watkins, while the home-built plane had taken off
minutes before the crash from the Aurora airport, about three miles
from the crash site, airport officials said.
   Scott said home-built planes are certified by the Federal
Aviation Administration and are not necessarily more dangerous than
conventional aircraft.
</TEXT>
