<SECOND>PM-Abortion-Coma, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0484,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Seen Progressing After Abortion, To Move To Rehab Center</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 10th graf pvs, `She can ...' to UPDATE
with hospital saying condition unchanged</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANHASSET, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A comatose woman who received an abortion
last month after a bitter legal battle has made enough progress to
transfer to a rehabilitation center, relatives say.
   Nancy Klein, who remains in a coma at North Shore University
Hospital in Manhasset, just east of New York City, was to be moved
today to a rehabilitation center in Edison, N.J.
   ``Nancy is moving onto a whole new world,'' her mother, Anne
Zusselman of Delray Beach, Fla., said Wednesday in an interview with
The Associated Press from the Klein home in Upper Brookville.
   ``We think she is ready, and we're going for it.''
   Mrs. Klein, 32, suffered severe brain damage in a Dec. 13 car
accident.
   Her husband, Martin, 34, went to court to be appointed her legal
guardian so he could authorize an abortion that doctors said could
improve her chances of survival.
   Anti-abortionists fought a three-week court battle to block the
abortion, appealing all the way to the U.S. Supreme Court before the
case was thrown out.
   The abortion was performed Feb. 11 when Mrs. Klein was 18 weeks
pregnant.
   Although hospital physicians believe Mrs. Klein only has a slim
chance of recovery, family members say they have seen an improvement
since the abortion.
   She can move her head to both sides, open her mouth and lift her
left arm on command. ``She can even give us the thumbs up sign,''
Mrs. Zusselman said.
   But Carol Hauptman, a spokeswoman for North Shore, said Mrs.
Klein's condition remained unchanged.
   The Klein's 3-year-old daughter has visited her mother twice in
the hospital.
   ``We don't know how much Nancy knows but she seems to be happy
when the baby visits,'' said Mrs. Zusselman.
   The family believes Mrs. Klein now requires intensive daily
therapy that the hospital isn't equipped to provide.
   The Robert Wood Johnson Rehabilitation Institute of John F.
Kennedy Hospital has a renowned brain trauma unit. It provides eye
and speech therapy and equipment that includes a chair that will
help Mrs. Klein hold her head up.
   ``They will give her an intensive workout, as much as she can
take,'' Mrs. Zusselman said.
</TEXT>
