<DOCNO> AP890309-0055 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 0717EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SouthAfrica     03-09 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hunger Strikers Will Go Free Or Face Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities have agreed to
release or file formal charges against 35 black inmates who have
been hospitalized because of their hunger strikes, their lawyers
said today.
   Lawyer Mahmood Cajee said Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok
agreed on Tuesday to make a decision on the status of each of the 35
prisoners, who are among hundreds of black inmates being held
without charge.
   The 35 prisoners, some of whom have been on hunger strikes for 19
days, are inmates at a prison in the southeastern city of
Pietermaritzburg.
   Cajee said the detainees resumed eating Wednesday evening. ``The
detainees are ecstatic,'' he said.
   The attorney declined to say how many of the 35 would be freed
and how many would be charged, but said he expected the Law and
Order Ministry to announce its decisions within a matter of days.
   Lawyer Rishi Thakurdin, who also represents some of the inmates,
said some of those released would be placed under restrictions
limiting their movements and prohibiting involvement in political
activities.
   A Law and Order Ministry spokesman, Brig. Leon Mellet, said Vlok
was ``examining the status of each and every detainee (nationwide)
but we don't want to comment on individual cases.''
   Detainees in Johannesburg began fasting Jan. 23, demanding to be
freed or put on trial. The hunger strikes quickly spread to other
cities, and Vlok said Feb. 16 he would release a ``substantial
number'' of detainees.
   The government says it since has freed 279 detainees and more
than 500 people remain held without charge. Anti-apartheid groups
say 202 people have been released while about 700 remain in
detention.
   The groups say Vlok has reneged on his promise, that he had given
the impression that more than half the detainees would be released
by the beginning of March. There have been widespread calls for an
end to all detentions without trial.
   About 20 detainees in Durban and a smaller number at Modderbee
Prison east of Johannesburg reportedly remain on hunger strikes.
   Vlok said Wednesday that 23 detainees hospitalized due to their
hunger strikes have been returned to prison.
   An estimated 30,000 people have been detained without charge for
varying lengths of time under the nearly 3-year-old state of
emergency.
   Emergency regulations give security forces wide powers and ban or
restrict many forms of peaceful protest.
   In a separate development today, two black men convicted of
murder were hanged in Pretoria, raising the number of executions
this year to four.
   Human rights organizations recently praised the government for
the sharp decline in the rate of executions. A total of 117 people
were executed last year and 164 were hanged in 1987.
</TEXT>
