<FIRST>r a PM-MoneyLaundering     03-09 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Money Laundering,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grand Jury Indicts 33 In Money Laundering Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drug agents were alerted to look out for
possible retaliation from cocaine dealers after the indictment of 33
wholesale jewelers on charges of participating in a $1 billion money
laundering ring.
   ``We are getting feedback now which indicates we will get some
major retaliation against law enforcement,'' said John Zienter, head
of the Drug Enforcement Administration office in Los Angeles.
   Zienter and other law enforcement officials announced the
indictments at a news conference Wednesday. Four others were
indicted last week in San Jose. The officials also made their first
public comments on the money laundering probe code-named Operation
Polar Cap.
   The indictments on charges of money laundering and conspiracy to
aid and abet narcotics trafficking struck a major blow to the
Colombian drug cartels, officials said.
   ``The amount of money laundered is staggering,'' U.S. attorney
Robert Bonner said of the $1 billion alleged to have been moved out
of the country in two years. ``The amount represents proceeds of
approximately 70 tons of cocaine sold in the United States in two
years.''
   The jewelers are alleged to have operated the money laundering
business in the heart of the Los Angeles jewelry district. They were
arrested Feb. 22.
   Bonner said the 15-month probe netted more than $80 million in
real estate, gold and cash seized from the defendants. It included a
$17 million, 10-story building in the center of the jewelry district
that allegedly was purchased with cocaine profits.
   The grand jury indictments focused on operations run by Nazareth
and Vahe Andonian and Wanis ``Joseph'' Koyomejian, who operated
jewelry and gold bullion companies in Los Angeles.
   In addition to defendants of Armenian, Turkish and Syrian
descent, the indictments also named several Latin Americans, one of
whom was said to oversee the entire money laundering operation from
his post in Uruguay. That defendant, Raul Vivas, is in custody in
Uruguay, Bonner said.
   The conspiracy charge carries a maximum sentence of life
imprisonment. The maximum sentence for money laundering is 20 years
and fines up to $25 million.
</TEXT>
