<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 0813EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Sweden-VanAllen     03-09 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sweden-Van Allen,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Space Explorer Wins Prestigious Swedish Prize</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Royal Academy of Sciences today
named U.S. space researcher James A. Van Allen winner of the 1989
Crafoord Prize for his discovery of the radiation belts surrounding
the Earth.
   Van Allen, professor emeritus at the University of Iowa, also was
cited for providing the first instruments ever carried to another
planet, those taken on the 1963 mission to Venus by Mariner II.
   The prize, which includes a $252,000 cash award, is given
annually by the same institution that awards the Nobel Prizes. The
award was founded in 1980 for excellence in physical sciences
outside those stipulated by the 1896 will of Alfred Nobel:
chemistry, physics, and medicine.
   Van Allen began experimenting in nuclear physics by developing
instruments for counting charged particles, the academy said. After
World War II, when he served in the Navy, he applied his methods to
the study of cosmic rays and the earth's geomagnetic field, using
rockets he helped develop.
   His experience in rocketry and instrumentation put him at the
forefront of space research at a time when the United States and the
Soviet Union had begun their race to put satellites and men in space.
   His work with the Explorer I satellite led to the discovery in
1958 of the earth's radiation belts, now called the Van Allen belts.
   As head of the astronomy and physics department of the University
of Iowa, Van Allen developed new satellites in the early 1960s and
trained some of the leaders in space research, the academy said.
   He has published close to 250 scientific papers on studies
ranging from solar wind to the magnetospheres of the various planets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
