<FIRST>r i PM-Tibet-DalaiLama     03-09 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tibet-Dalai Lama,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dalai Lama Commends Tibetan Struggle For Independence</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Tibet, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Dalai Lama today praised the Tibetan
nationalist struggle and condemned Chinese repression in the
disputed region, the scene of bloody riots this week.
   Tibetan demonstrations for independence have left at least 16
people dead and forced the imposition of martial law in Lhasa, the
Tibetan capital.
   ``No amount of repression, however brutal and violent, can
silence the voice of freedom and justice,'' the Tibetan spiritual
leader said in a statement marking the 30th anniversary of the
Tibetan uprising against China.
   ``Unfortunately, the Chinese leadership still fails to understand
... the extent of dissatisfaction among the Tibetan people,'' said
the statement, issued by the office of the Dali Lama's
representative in New Delhi.
   The Dalai Lama, spiritual leaders of Tibetans, fled to India
after the failed March 10, 1959, uprising against the Chinese in
Lhasa.
   China claims Tibet has been an integral part of Chinese territory
for seven centuries. But most Tibetans maintain it was an
independent nation before the communists moved into Tibet in 1949.
   ``We honor ... more than 1 million Tibetans who have died as the
result of four decades of Chinese occupation,'' the Dali Lama said.
   His government-in-exile, headquartered in the town of Dharmsala,
260 miles north of New Delhi, offered on Wednesday to hold talks on
the future of Tibet with the Chinese government.
   ``Despite the current tragic events, we are still ready to hold
talks with the Chinese so that a peaceful solution can be found,''
said Tashi Wangdi, the Tibetan leader's chief representative.
   China offered in September to hold talks with the Dalai Lama on
the future of Tibet if he dropped demands for Tibetan independence.
   The Dalai Lama's adminstration accepted the offer but said the
only reasonable basis for resolving the issue was ``a self-govering
democratic entity'' in Tibet ``in association with the People's
Republic of China.''
   The talks were to start in January, but snags developed in
December when the Chinese said they preferred to meet in Beijing,
not Geneva.
   The Tibetans rejected Beijing, saying a meeting in the Chinese
capital would portray the Tibetan issue as an internal Chinese
problem.
</TEXT>
