<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 0837EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-East-West     03-09 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-East-West,0321</SECOND>
<HEAD>Talks Open On Closer East-West Relations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND PRINZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty-five nations, including the Soviet
Union and the United States, today began talks aimed at closer
East-West relations.
   Separate talks on reductions in NATO and Warsaw Pact conventional
armed forces were to begin later today.
   The negotiations on ``confidence- and security-building
measures'' involve all the countries that signed the 1975 Helsinki
accords on human rights and include all European countries except
self-isolated Albania.
   In January, the nations adopted the concluding document of the
Helsinki review Conference on Security and Cooperation in Europe,
which spells out far-reaching human rights and provisions for
economic cooperation in Europe.
   Foreign ministers of the 35 nations Wednesday ended a three-day
conference that set the stage for today's talks, which may last for
several years before practical agreements are reached.
   The arms control negotiations replace and expand the Mutual and
Balanced Force Reduction talks, which ended without agreement after
15 years.
   But the new talks _ called the Negotiations on Conventional Armed
Forces in Europe _ come during a time of improved relations between
the superpowers and are expected to produce results. They will
involve the 16 members of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization and
the seven Warsaw Pact members.
   NATO wants the East to make deep cuts in tanks and troops. NATO
has proposed overall limits of 20,000 tanks for each side, 16,500
artillery pieces for each side and 28,000 armored troop carriers for
each alliance.
   The British foreign secretary, Sir Geoffrey Howe, said NATO's
proposals would reduce Soviet tanks and artillery in Europe by
two-thirds and armored troop carriers by more than 50 percent.
   The Warsaw Pact has proposed reductions in troop numbers and all
weapons, including battlefield nuclear weapons. But the United
States and most of its allies insist that nuclear weapons must be
dealt with separately.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
