<HEAD>Arguments in Missouri Abortion Case Set for April 26</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oral arguments it will conducted April 26 in a
case the Supreme Court is being asked to use to overturn or greatly
alter its 1973 legalizing abortion.
   A 60-minute session in the Missouri case, the most closely
watched controversy at the high court this year, will take place on
the 1988-89 term's last scheduled day of arguments.
   The justices are expected to announce their decision by July.
   At issue are Missouri abortion regulations struck down by a
federal appeals court.
   Although the case could be resolved without altering the court's
1973 landmark decision, Missouri authorities and the Bush
administration are urging the court to reconsider its 16-year-old
ruling in a case called Roe vs. Wade.
   Justice Department lawyers have asked the court to let state
legislatures decide what legal protections, if any, should be given
to women seeking abortions.
   The court's 1973 decision said women have a constitutional right
to seek abortions, and greatly limited governmental authority to
interfere with that right.
