<FIRST>r i PM-Rushdie-Commandos     03-09 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rushdie-Commandos,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Anti-Rushdie Commando Spotted in Spain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A news agency today quoted intelligence
sources as saying an Iranian commando unit was in Spain recently,
apparently trying to obtain weapons to kill author Salman Rushdie.
   According to the EFE news agency, the sources said the Iranians
dispersed and infiltrated Britain, France and West Germany and that
authorities in those countries were notified. It said the Iranians
were trailed in Spain more than 10 days ago.
   The sources, who were identified only as being close to the
investigation, were quoted as saying information obtained through
telephone taps revealed the group was unable to obtain weapons in
Spain and that no arrests were made due to lack of evidence.
   Iran's Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini on Feb. 14 sentenced Rushdie
to death for his new novel, ``The Satanic Verses,'' which some say
blasphemes Islam. Iranian clerics have offered $5.2 million for
Rushdie's death.
   The writer lives in Britain and has been in hiding since the
death order.
   The commando group consisted of five men and two women, said the
sources. The agency said five members entered Spain from Morocco,
using Moroccan passports and posing as migrant workers.
   The other two arrived in Madrid from Beirut aboard a Middle East
Airlines flight and met up with the five in an apartment in northern
Madrid, the sources told EFE.
   Interior Ministry spokesman Luis Peiro said the ministry could
neither confirm nor deny the report. ``This information didn't come
from us, and we're still checking on its veracity,'' he said.
   The commandos remained under surveillance during the week they
spent in Spain, apparently trying to make contacts to get arms and
explosives to kill Rushdie, according to EFE.
   When they were unable to secure weapons, two of the Iranians
drove to the port of Santander and caught a ferry to England, EFE
said. Three other Iranians drove to France, EFE said. The two who
had arrived from Beirut took a flight to Munich, West Germany, the
agency said.
</TEXT>
