<HEAD>Saudi Arabia Recognizes Afghan Guerrilla Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saudi Arabia today became the first
country to officially recognize the Afghan guerrilla
government-in-exile.
   Saudi Arabia did so because the members of the
government-in-exile were chosen freely by the Moslem guerrilla
leaders, the official Saudi Press Agency quoted a Foreign Ministry
statement as saying.
   Saudi Arabia, home of Islam's holiest shrines, carries
considerable weight in the Moslem world. The oil-rich kingdom has
given the Moslem guerrillas considerable support in their struggle
against the Afghan government and the Soviet army, which withdrew
last month after nine years of fighting.
   The United States and Pakistan also supplied the anti-communist
forces with weapons and funding during the Soviet intervention.
   Saudi Arabia will host a meeting of foreign ministers from the
46-member Islamic Conference organization later this month. Among
other issues the conference will discuss recognizing the Afghan
guerrilla's government-in-exile, which was proclaimed in Pakistan on
Feb. 24.
   The president of the guerrilla government, Sibghatullah Mojaddidi
on Wednesday called on the United Nations and the Islamic Conference
organization to recognize the new leaderhsip of the insurgency.
