<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 0930EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i China-Tibet 2ndLd-writethru   03-09 0805</FIRST>
<SECOND>China-Tibet, 2nd Ld-writethru,a0466,0831</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tibetan: Foreigners Depart, Troops Round Up Tibetans</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with troops reportedly rounding up Tibetans,
comment from Chinese government. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHENGDU, CHINA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All foreigners were removed from Lhasa
today, and Chinese troops began rounding up Tibetans, said a Tibetan
woman.
   ``Soldiers are all over the place, and they're grabbing
everyone,'' she said. The woman, who runs a small hotel in Lhasa,
was interviewed by telephone from Beijing. Foreign reporters were
barred from the city.
   China on Tuesday declared martial law in the city of 70,000
following three days of rioting by Tibetans demanding independence
from China and the return of their spiritual leader, the Dalai Lama.
   China today added four people to the number killed during
protests in Lhasa on Sunday, bringing the official toll to 16 dead
and about 100 wounded.
   Western travelers say many more have died, and most Tibetans
reportedly put the toll at between 20 and 30.
   The government also denied that it had abused Tibetans' human
rights.
   The Tibetan woman said most of the city's foreigners, estimated
at 140, left in buses. About 40 flew into to Chengdu, the capital of
neighboring Sichuan province.
   The woman said soldiers then began detaining large numbers of
Tibetans. She said she could not estimate how many people were being
taking away. ``Many people. It is many more than when the foreigners
were here,'' she said.
   Upon arriving in Chengdu, tourists said Tibetans had become
increasingly scared after the imposition of martial law.
   ``People begged us repeatedly over the last few days _ `Tell the
world, help us please,''' said one American from New Orleans, who
spoke on condition of anonymity for fear of Chinese reprisals.
   ``They grab your hand and say `Help us,' and they cry,'' said a
West German woman.
   A group of tourists that flew to Chengdu issued a statement they
said would be sent to the United Nations and to the Dalai Lama, who
lives in exile in India.
   ``It is our urgent and heartfelt wish that the world community
should carefully and critically examine the causes of this conflict
and the methods and motives of the authorities,'' said the statement.
   ``While the Tibetan demonstrators became violent and destructive
in expressing their anger and frustration, we feel the magnitude and
bloodiness of the crisis has been caused by the incompetence of the
authorities.
   ``Shootings by the authorities have been excessive,
unpredictable, indiscriminate and there have on occasion been
atrocities,'' it said.
   State-run radio reported the four additional deaths and said the
people died in the hospital ``during emergency life-saving
procedures.'' The report did not say whether the dead were Tibetans.
   Foreigners say some Tibetans claim as many as 100 people were
killed by police, although those claims could not be confirmed.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Li Zhaoxing, in a weekly briefing,
denied Chinese authorities were violating the human rights of
Tibetans.
   ``Recently a handful of separatists committed beating, smashing,
looting and burning in a deliberate attempt to start a riot,'' Li
said. ``These violent incidents aimed at splitting the motherland
were a serious breach of law. It is not a question of human rights,
religion or nationality.''
   Li also blamed the disturbances on the ``clique'' of the Dalai
Lama.
   During the riots, thousands of Tibetans rampaged through the
streets and ransacked Chinese-owned shops. On Wednesday, travelers
reported seeing police dragging Tibetans out of their homes and
hauling them away in trucks.
   The official Chinese media has given no figures on arrests, but
the Communist Party's official People's Daily reported from Lhasa
how police raided one home and dragged a screaming man outside. They
then went next door and found a man hiding under a blanket.
   The man's wife was quoted as saying, ``Hurry up and dress and go
with them. I told you not to take part (in the riots) but you just
had to do it.''
   China's official Xinhua News Agency, meanwhile, accused Tibetan
separatists living abroad of smuggling weapons into Tibet and
instigating the riots.
   Foreign travelers said they saw no signs of Tibetans firing on
police.
   Xinhua said, ``The Tibetan separatist clique based abroad has
recently sent its men into Tibet under the guise of tourists to
incite riots, and they have also smuggled weapons into the region.''
   It was an apparent reference to the followers of the Dalai Lama,
who fled Tibet following a failed uprising against China's army in
March 1959.
   Friday is the 30th anniversary of that rebellion, and martial law
was imposed in part to prevent further anti-Chinese demonstrations
on that day.
   The Dalai Lama, in a statement marking the anniversary, praised
the Tibetan struggle and condemned Chinese oppression.
   ``No amount of repression, however brutal and violent, can
silence the voice of freedom and justice,'' he said.
</TEXT>
