<HEAD>Nine Former Iranian Embassy Employees Told to Leave in 10 Days</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine former employees of the Iranian Embassy will
be deported if they do not leave Britain voluntarily within 10 days,
a government spokesman said today.
   Also today, Spain's national news agency EFE quoted intelligence
sources as saying an Iranian commando team was recently in that
country trying to obtain weapons, apparently to kill British author
Salman Rushdie.
   President Saddam Hussein of Iraq said Iran's death sentence
against Rushdie has damaged Islam more than the controversial novel,
which some say blasphemes Islam.
   Kuwait today joined other Moslem nations in condemning the book,
and it banned all works by the author, who was born into a Moslem
family.
   ``The Satanic Verses'' led Iran to break relations with Britain
on Tuesday. Britain, in turn, announced Wednesday it plans to expel
``a number'' of Iranians because of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's
refusal to revoke his death sentence against Rushdie.
   Government sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
expulsion order applied to up to 30 Iranians ``who are held to be
close to the regime.'' There are about 25,000 Iranians in Britain,
including 2,400 students.
   ``I can confirm to you that the names of nine Iranian individuals
have been sent over to the FCO (Foreign and Commonwealth Office),''
a spokesman for the Home Office, the department responsible for
immigration, said today.
   ``This would be to initiate the proceedings to secure their
removal,'' he said, speaking anonymously in keeping with British
custom. When asked if they were former embassy employees who no
longer have diplomatic status, he said, ``I can confirm that.''
   Home Secretary Douglas Hurd said his officials were checking all
people stationed in Britain by Iran to decide ``which of them we can
no longer safely receive here.''
   ``I think we are dealing here with a regime which is different
from the others, a regime which in recent weeks has gone back to
preaching violence,'' Hurd told British Broadcasting Corp. radio.
   Rushdie, a British citizen, has been in hiding, reportedly under
police guard, since Feb. 14, when Khomeini ordered Moslems to kill
him. Iranian clerics have offered $5.2 million for Rushdie's death.
   According to the Spanish news report, seven Iranians were tracked
in Spain more than 10 days ago but have since dispersed and
infiltrated Britain, West Germany and France. The news agency quoted
sources as saying authorities in those countries were warned.
   EFE quoted the sources as saying the group was apparently tried
but failed to obtain weapons in Spain to kill Rushdie. No charges
were filed because of lack of evidence, it quoted the sources as
saying.
   The Iraqi president was quoted today as telling the Saudi
newspaper Al-Sharq Al-Awsat that Rushdie is ``bad and ill-disposed.''
   But he was also quoted as saying, ``This (death threat) does more
damage to Islam than Salman Rushdie's book.'' It was the first
public statement from the Iraqi president on the Rushdie affair.
   Kuwait's government urged Moslems across the world to boycott all
books published by The Penguin Group, which published ``The Satanic
Verses.''
   In a separate decision, the Information Ministry banned all books
written by Rushdie.
   The novel has been banned in almost all Moslem countries, and
riots against it have killed 19 people.
</TEXT>
