<FIRST>r a PM-NewOrleansSymphony     03-09 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-New Orleans Symphony,0501</SECOND>
<HEAD>After Long Absence, Symphony Performs, Parties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New Orleans Symphony took the stage for
the first time since it ran out of money 14 months ago and feted a
rare sell-out crowd with balloons, jazz bands and Cajun buffet.
   ``This is a great victory for the city,'' Mayor Sidney Barthelemy
told the crowd Wednesday. ``This is a great victory for the people.
... We can't go anywhere but up.''
   The long absence generated a crush for tickets. In addition to
the opening night sellout, officials said all seats for Saturday
night were sold and only 200 remained for the next Thursday's
performance in the 1,750-seat Orpheum Theater.
   Symphony officials said they could remember only one previous
sell-out in the Orpheum _ a benefit with violinist Itzhak Perlman.
   Ron Jones, president of the board, said 70 percent of season
tickets have been sold and officials expect to sell 90 percent of
seats in advance.
   Organizers turned the opening into a celebration. There were
flowers for women in the audience, a welcome line of local
television anchors and a high school jazz band playing in the lobby.
   During the closing bows, balloons rained from the ceiling as in a
political convention. Afterward, the whole crowd was invited to a
hotel across the street where some of the city's finest restaurants
catered a buffet that included jambalaya, red beans and rice, shrimp
pasta and oyster soup.
   The crowd loved it.
   ``I can remember the night they closed,'' said Eean McNaughton,
an architect who has been attending the symphony here for 30 years.
``It really makes this an exuberant night.''
   A massive fund-raising and the sale of the Orpheum erased a $4
million debt. The theater's buyers, whose names haven't been
disclosed, are letting the symphony play rent-free for five years.
   In addition, the board of directors and staff were restructured.
   The symphony has scheduled a short 12-week spring season. Full
34-week seasons are being prepared for the next two years.
   The opening program, with music director Maxim Shostakovich
conducting, included ``Fanfare For A New Beginning,'' composed by
orchestra flutist Richard Harrison.
   Alexander Slobodyanik was guest pianist for Chopin's Concerto No.
1 in E Minor.
   ``The orchestra sounds better than it has for a long time,
because the people are in a better mood,'' said Greg Miller, a
trombonist who is the musicians' personnel manager. ``It is hard to
concentrate on Beethoven when you are worrying about paying the
rent.''
   The shutdown took its toll on the musicians, however. Thirteen of
the 89 orchestra members were listed in the program as ``on leave.''
Many have new jobs, including concert master Joseph Kim who is now
concert master of the Seoul Symphony in South Korea.
   Kim flew back to New Orleans for the opening and will be featured
next week in Rimsky-Korsakov's Scheherazade. It is uncertain whether
he will return next year.
</TEXT>
