<FIRST>u a PM-Eastern-Chapter11     03-09 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Chapter 11,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>What Chapter 11 Means For Eastern</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Eastern Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airline's decision to seek Chapter 11 federal bankruptcy
protection from creditors today means the strike-crippled carrier
could continue to operate, although it may have difficulty imposing
wage cuts on union employees.
   Under Chapter 11 of the Federal Bankruptcy Act, companies are
shielded from creditors while they continue to operate and
reorganize their finances. Any reorganization plan is subject to
approval by the bankruptcy court and creditors.
   Eastern could continue flying, as other carriers have after
seeking bankruptcy court protection.
   But Frank Lorenzo, chairman of Eastern parent Texas Air Corp.,
would have a tougher time imposing lower wages on striking employees
than he did when he reorganized Continental Airlines under federal
bankruptcy law in 1983.
   Congress amended federal laws in 1984 to require bankrupt
companies to negotiate with unions and prove economic necessity
before abrogating their contracts.
   The Eastern strike began Saturday with a walkout by 8,500 members
of Eastern's Machinists union in a dispute over Lorenzo's proposed
$125 million in wage cuts.
   The Miami-based airline reduced its operations to about 4 percent
of its scheduled flights and sent thousands of employees home after
Eastern pilots and flight attendants joined the Machinists walkout.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
