<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 1020EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-East-West 1stLd-Writethru   03-09 0725</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-East-West, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0511,0746</SECOND>
<HEAD>Warsaw Pact Proposes Sweeping Cuts But Warns Against Modernization
Program</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Warsaw Pact proposals. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND PRINZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Warsaw Pact today proposed sweeping
reductions in troops and conventional weapons but gave a stern
warning to NATO that its plans to modernize nuclear weapons could
disrupt arms control efforts.
   A Warsaw Pact position paper given to reporters sets a goal of
making both military alliances ``strictly defensive'' by the year
2000 after gradual reductions in troops and weapons.
   Oleg A. Grinevski, the Soviet ambassador to the new talks on
reducing conventional weapons, outlined the Warsaw Pact proposals at
the start of the negotiations involving the 23 NATO and Warsaw Pact
nations.
   Separate talks on closer East-West relations also began today in
Vienna. Those talks involve the 35 nations, including the Soviet
Union and United States, that signed the 1975 Helsinki accords on
human rights.
   Grinevski stressed the Warsaw Pact's opposition to a Western
proposal to upgrade 700 Lance nuclear missiles to double their range
to about 150 miles. The missiles are mostly in West Germany.
   Reading a prepared statement, Grinevski declared: ``It should be
clearly understood that good will has its limits. We have made quite
a few major unilateral steps.''
   He referred to Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
announcement to pull out about 50,000 men and their weaponry from
East Germany, Czechoslovakia and Hungary during the next two years
and pledges by other Soviet bloc countries to scale down their
armies and defense budgets.
   ``Let no one cherish the hope that our profound internal changes
will be making us more malleable and agreeable to unreasonable
demands or inflated bids,'' Grinevski said.
   Judging by the Warsaw Pact presentation and prior NATO proposals,
the two alliances differ substantially on how and what reduce, and
to what extent.
   The 16-member North Atlantic Treaty Organization proposes deep
cuts in battle tanks, artillery pieces and armored personnel
carriers. It says the seven-member Warsaw Pact has a 2-to-1 edge in
such equipment.
   The Warsaw Pact paper proposes three stages of reducing personnel
and arms up to the year 2000.
   From 1991 to 1994, participants would eliminate ``imbalances and
asymmetries'' between the alliances and ``would take steps to
eliminate the capability to launch a surprise attack or initiate a
large-scale offensive action.'' The amount of arms the alliances are
allowed to maintain would be reduced by about 15 percent, according
to the Warsaw Pact.
   From 1994 to 1997, the bloc proposed reductions of armed forces
by 25 percent, or 500,000 men.
   In the last stage, the armed forces of the NATO and Warsaw Pact
nations should be given ``a strictly defensive character,''
according to the paper.
   It included combat aircraft among the weapons to be cut. But NATO
is unwilling to discuss the inclusion of combat aircraft at this
point.
   NATO has proposed overall limits of 40,000 tanks on both sides,
33,000 artillery peices overall and 56,000 troop carriers. It also
proposed a limit of 12,000 tanks, 10,000 artillery pieces and 16,800
armored troop carriers for any one nation.
   Weaponry stationed outside one's home country would be limited to
32,000 tanks, 1,700 artillery pieces and 6,000 armored troop
carriers in each bloc, according to NATO proposals.
   Britain's foreign secretary, Sir Geoffrey Howe, said this would
cut Soviet tanks and artillery in Europe by two-thirds and armored
troop carriers by more than 50 percent.
   The United States and most other NATO countries have ruled out
negotiations on nuclear or even dual-capable weapons system, stating
that they are not included in the mandate for the new arms talks.
   But Grinevski said, ``The more agreement we shall have on the
conventional side, the more (are) necessary steps, measures or
negotiations concerning other types of security _ tactical nuclear
weapons, and their modernization, and the naval situation.''
   Nuclear weapons ``are not on the agenda, but they exist around
us. It's impossible to close our eyes to that. I'm just warning
about that, nothing more,'' he said.
   The arms control negotiations replace and expand the Mutual and
Balanced Force Reduction talks, which ended without agreement after
15 years.
   The new talks _ called the Negotiations on Conventional Armed
Forces in Europe _ come during a time of improved relations between
the superpowers and are expected to produce results.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
