<FIRST>r i PM-India-Bhopal 1stLd-Writethru   03-09 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Bhopal, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0498,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Arrest 2,000 During Protest In Carbide Settlement</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with protesters released. Pickup
6th graf pvs, ``On Feb...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY BHARAT DESAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BHOPAL, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police today arrested and briefly held 2,000
people who tried to march on the state legislature to protest Union
Carbide Co.'s $470 million settlement in the Bhopal gas disaster,
officials said.
   About 5,000 demonstrators, many carrying small children and
waving banners saying ``We Want Justice,'' marched from the
shantytowns affected by the 1984 gas leak to the Madhya Pradesh
state legislature, said a police spokesman who insisted on anonymity.
   About 2,000 marchers, including 500 women, tried to cross a
police barricade half a mile from the building and were arrested,
the spokesman said.
   A few demonstrators wrestled briefly with police before being
taken by buses to jail, where they were charged with violating an
order prohibiting the assembly of more than five people on the
legislature grounds, he said.
   The spokesman said all were released this evening.
   On Feb. 14, the Supreme Court in New Delhi ordered Union Carbide
to pay $470 million as the final settlement of all claims stemming
from the world's worst industrial disaster.
   More than 3,400 people died when toxic methyl isocyanate leaked
from a pesticide plant run by Union Carbide's subsidiary, Union
Carbide of India Ltd. More than 20,000 others were injured.
   Many shops and business throughout this central Indian city
closed today in a daylong strike to protest the settlement, which
also absolved the U.S.-based multinational of any criminal or civil
liability for the gas leak.
   The protests came on the opening day of the legislature's budget
session.
   Opposition politicians wore black arm bands bearing skulls and
crossbones and shouted ``Down with Union Carbide.'' Some carried
placades saying, ``The settlement smells of kickbacks.''
   ``The result of the settlement has been that Union Carbide shares
have gone sky high and the prestige and honor of India has been
ground to dust,'' said Atal Bihari Bajpayi, a leader of the
opposition Bharatiya Janata Party. ``India has let the Third World
down.''
   About 570,000 victims, many of whom lived in shantytowns around
the factory, filed compensation claims. Parliament passed the Bhopal
Gas Leak Disater Act 1985 giving the government the authority to act
on behalf of the victims.
   A panel of five Supreme Court justices is hearing arguments this
week on a petition challenging the government's authority to act as
the sole representative of the victims.
   The federal government originally sued Union Carbide for $3
billion, claiming the gas leak was caused by negligence.
   Union Carbide, headquartered in Danbury, Conn., said the gas leak
was the result of sabotage by a disgruntled employee.
</TEXT>
