<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 1025EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ArtsFunds     03-09 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arts Funds,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Artists Draw Legislators A Picture: Arts Spending is an Investment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 1,000 musicians, actors and other artists
gathered to lobby the legislature to restore $19 million in arts
funding to the state budget, saying culture returns more than that
to the state.
   They argued that jobs, ticket sales, tourism and enrichment of
schools and communities justify full state funding for the
Massachusetts Council on the Arts and Humanities.
   In a rally outside the Statehouse on Wednesday, they brandished
signs that said ``Don't stop the music'' and ``Keep the arts alive.''
   The state House of Representatives is debating a $12.3 billion
budget proposal for next year that eliminates $19 million proposed
by Gov. Michael S. Dukakis for the council, which makes grants to
dozens of cultural institutions and individual artists.
   The legislature is considering a no-frills budget because the
current fiscal year is expected to end up at least $600 million in
the red since anticipated corporate tax revenue has not materialized.
   Democratic House leaders, retreating from the zero funding
recommended by the House Ways and Means committee two weeks ago,
have decided to support a plan that would tap the state Lottery
Commission's prize money to restore $9.5 million to the council.
   But arts advocates want restoration of full funding, arguing that
the money spent on the arts more than pays for itself. Last year,
arts funding yielded $23 million in state taxes, they said.
   ``Culture is good business, and the economic impact is
substantial,'' said Nancy Finkelstein, executive director of the
Massachusetts Cultural Alliance.
   Holly Sidford, executive director of the New England Foundation
for the Arts, said her group has compiled statistics that show
non-profit arts groups contributed $1.2 billion to the state's
economy. She said arts organizations employed 20,000 people and
served 20 million ticket buyers, five times the number who attended
professional sports events.
</TEXT>
