<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 1047EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Pope-Bishops 1stLd-Writethru a0410 03-09 0757</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pope-Bishops, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0410,0776</SECOND>
<HEAD>Top Vatican Official Says U.S. Bishops Yield To Academicians</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Ratzinger criticism of U.S. bishops,
American comments. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top Vatican cardinal, addressing American
Catholic leaders, accused bishops of allowing their authority to be
usurped by academic experts, officials said today.
   Cardinal Joseph Ratzinger, head of the powerful Congregation for
the Doctrine of the Faith, appealed to the Americans attending a
special Vatican meeting to assert their authority and be ``martyrs''
for church teaching.
   Some U.S. bishops countered that compromising on some church
issues ``should not be seen as weakness,'' as long as matters of
faith are not sacrificed.
   The issue of the U.S. bishops' role was at the center of an
extraordinary meeting involving 35 American Catholic leaders
summoned by Pope John Paul II to discuss the independent-minded
American flock.
   The Vatican has criticized American Catholics' dissent from Rome
on matters such as artificial birth control and divorce.
   At the meeting's opening session, Ratzinger charged that in many
places theological experts have expressed their own ideas through
the mass media. He said they ``have taken the place of bishops as
teachers, causing a growing insecurity and disorientation'' among
the faithful.
   Bishops, he said, were pressured to be administrators rather than
strong champions of church doctrine.
   ``Bishops have fully adapted themselves to this regulative model,
little defending their magisterial authority'' over that of
theological experts, the West German cardinal said, according to a
summary of his speech.
   ``Those who announce the Gospel must also be martyrs, in the most
profound sense of the word,'' he said.
   Ratzinger's speech Wednesday evening was to set the Vatican's
tone for this week's four-day meeting, according to church
officials. Vatican spokesman Joaquin Navarro and the Rev. John
Lynch, secretary of the U.S. National Conference of Bishops, briefed
reporters today on the closed session.
   In opening remarks at the meeting, Archbishop John L. May,
president of the U.S. bishops' conference, said Americans would not
put up with an authoritarian approach from the church.
   Other bishops, led by Archbishop John Roach of Minneapolis-St.
Paul, responded to Ratzinger's speech by saying that give-and-take
in the American church did not endanger Catholicism.
   ``Several bishops said that in the United States, compromise _ as
long as you're not giving away the store ... is not in and of itself
a bad word or a bad process,'' said Lynch.
   The bishops, he said, declared ``that to keep the dialogue open,
which can sometimes be read as weakness, but which in our American
experience often leads to a good end, should not be seen as
weakness.''
   ``While it can be risky, it does sometimes lead to the successful
conclusion of problems'' between bishops and theological experts, or
between the church hierarchy and the faithful, the bishops said,
according to Lynch.
   The Vatican has billed this week's encounter as a series of open
discussions of issues raised during the pope's 1987 U.S. visit and
periodic bishops' trips to Rome.
   On Wednesday evening, Cardinal John O'Connor of New York said
``there were no expressed disagreements'' to the speech by Ratzinger
or one he gave on the bishops' role.
   However, several of the bishops' statements drove home the
contention of some Americans that Vatican criticism stems in part
from a lack of understanding of the U.S. church.
   Speaking of U.S. society at Wednesday's meeting, May said:
``Authoritarianism is suspect in any area of learning or culture.
Individual freedom is prized supremely. Religious doctrine and moral
teaching are widely judged by these criteria.
   ``Therefore to assert that there is a church teaching with
authority binding and loosing for eternity is truly a sign of
contradiction to many Americans who consider the divine right of
bishops as outmoded as the divine right of kings,'' said May, of St.
Louis.
   In his speech, O'Connor said U.S. bishops had been fulfilling
their teaching role.
   ``I explained my personal conviction that for 200 years, the
bishops of the United States have demonstrated their commitment as
teachers. Too often they are dismissed simply as fund-raisers or
school-builders,'' he said in an interview Wednesday night. He said,
however, that it was not the Vatican but U.S. critics who made those
charges.
   A conflict appeared to develop between the Vatican and the U.S.
bishops over releasing texts of speeches from the closed sessions.
The Vatican released May's opening remarks but not the speeches by
O'Connor or Ratzinger.
   Vatican officials prevailed today, issuing summaries of the
speeches.
</TEXT>
