<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 1102EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TorturedArtist     03-09 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tortured Artist,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tormented Artist's Work Remembered In Exhibit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WAUKEGAN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An artist's haunting, surrealist paintings
went on view today as a tribute from his friends who won't let his
art die despite his tragic life and death.
   Colleagues liken John Wicklund's work to early efforts by
Salvador Dali and compare his tragic life and premature death to
Vincent Van Gogh's.
   They arranged for the monthlong exhibit of Wicklund's works at a
gallery here, about 40 miles north of Chicago.
   ``His art showed very lonely, always abandoned houses,'' his best
friend, Francis Smolinski, said Wednesday. ``To him they were
buildings that had a lot of love at one time. Now they were empty,
ready to be torn down.''
   Wicklund's art imitated his life up to the day he died sometime
between Dec. 20 and Dec. 30, Smolinski said.
   Although he had just been released from an alcohol detoxification
center, Wicklund was depressed and dejected when he stopped by
Smolinski's house in Gurnee on Dec. 20, the friend said. He suffered
from a lack of inspiration and grieved over his sister in
California, who was comatose and near death, Smolinski said.
   After Wicklund left, Smolinski became alarmed and spent 10 days
searching for his friend. Smolinski finally found Wicklund's frozen
body beneath a tree in a nearby stand of woods with vodka bottles
scattered around.
   Lynn Schornick, director of the Jack Benny Center for the Arts,
called the exhibit of Wicklund's watercolors and drawings haunting
and disturbing.
   ``I think there's no denying he had a real genius,'' Schornick
said. ``Almost none of (the works) have any people in them, and the
windows ... You can't see in them at all. There's simply no one
home.''
   Wicklund won a number of art contests and was an active member of
the Lake County Art League.
   ``He had this facade of humor ... and his work was just the
antithesis of that _ solemn, serious,'' said Ed Kanwischer, an art
professor who said Wicklund often sat in on his classes at the
College of Lake County.
   ``I knew he was doomed to die, you know, like Van Gogh,''
Kanwischer said.
   He said he and other league members organized the exhibit and
plan to auction off some works to raise money for a grave marker.
   ``We just felt his death shouldn't be the end,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
