<DOCNO> AP890309-0085 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 1130EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Salvador-Colonel     03-09 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador-Colonel,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colonel Relieved of Command in Massacre Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The commander of the 5th Brigade
has been relieved of his post as a result of an investigation into
the massacre of 10 peasants, military and government sources said
today.
   The sources, who declined to be identified pending announcement
of the probe's conclusions, said the removal is not final. But they
said it was unlikely Col. Jose Chavez Caceres would be reinstated as
commander of the 5th Brigade based in San Vicente, 40 miles east of
San Salvador.
   Chavez is not suspected of direct involvement in the slayings,
the sources said. His whereabouts were unknown.
   ``His responsibility appears to be limited to believing his
subordinates'' when they tried to cover up the army's role, said one
source.
   According to relatives, neighbors and witnesses, the massacre
took place on Sept. 21, when soldiers from the 5th Brigade's Jiboa
battalion marched into San Francisco, a hamlet of about 15 families
in San Vicente province.
   The soldiers detained most of the residents in a one-room school
and accused them of collaborating with leftist guerrillas.
   Working from a list, the troopers separated seven men and three
women and took them to a nearby ravine. They tied them up with
strips of green fabric and killed them with explosives _ either
grenades or captured guerrilla mines _ and rifle fire, according to
the witnesses.
   The army at first said the 10 corpses discovered in the ravine
were guerrillas killed in an army ambush. Then it said they were
detainees who, while being marched away from San Francisco, were
killed in a guerrilla ambush.
   Three officers who were in San Francisco the day of the killings
have been detained and at least one will be indicted on murder
charges this month by San Sebastian Judge Alcides Guandique,
according to sources close to the case.
   If such an indictment takes place, it would be the first time an
army officer has ever been indicted for politically motivated
killing of non-combatants in El Salvador's 9-year-old civil war.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
