<FIRST>r a PM-LawyerCaught     03-09 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lawyer Caught,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Client Goes Free, `Lawyer' Is Jailed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The client got off with a suspended
sentence, but the fellow who said he was the attorney was booked and
jailed.
   Fancy legal talk may have contributed to Clifford John's arrest
Wednesday in Jefferson County Court after he claimed to be a lawyer.
   ``Although not all attorneys are terribly articulate, this one
was worse than the average,'' said Judge Robert Morris. ``He used
big words that had no meaning within the sentences they were used
... Even our worst attorneys don't do that.''
   Authorities say they still aren't sure just what legal
credentials John has, but they said they do know he's not a licensed
attorney in Colorado.
   John, 37, appeared in court with his client Feb. 24 but asked for
a continuance. Morris then checked state records and found that
John's attorney number actually belonged to a woman who is an
assistant Colorado attorney general.
   When John came to the sentencing, ``He started talking, and he
still didn't sound very much like an attorney,'' Morris said.
   John's client, who faced a drunken driving charge, was ordered to
pay $320 in court costs and was given a suspended $500 fine and a
suspended 180-day jail sentence.
   The 20-year-old defendant, Monte Castaneda, received the minimum
sentence, which Morris said was not affected by John. Castaneda did
not pay attorney's fees, said Mark Pautler, chief deputy district
attorney.
   John, formerly a salesman for The Denver department stores,
apparently had an office in Denver. ``It does appear from looking at
his appointment books that he has additional clients,'' Pautler said.
   John, booked in Jefferson County Jail on $5,000 bond, was
scheduled to make his next court appearance today, facing possible
charges of criminal impersonation and forgery.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
