<DOCNO> AP890309-0089 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 1200EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-NorthernIreland 1stLd-Writethru a0470 03-09 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northern Ireland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0470,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Explosion Kills Two Soldiers, Wounds Six</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to ADD arrests, UPDATE with two victims identified,
estimate of bomb size. TRIMS to tighten. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two British soldiers were killed
and six wounded near Londonderry when their jeeps were blown apart
by a land mine that shattered windows half a mile away, police said
today.
   No group immediately claimed responsibility for the attack
shortly before midnight Wednesday, but suspicion fell on the Irish
Republican Army, which is fighting British rule in Northern Ireland.
   Police said today they had arrested two men but did not identify
them.
   Home Secretary Douglas Hurd, the British Cabinet member
responsible for law and order, said Wednesday an IRA unit was at
large on the British mainland.
   His announcement followed the discovery of an arms and explosives
cache near Scarborough, in northeast England, where Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher will address a conference of the national council
of her governing Conservative Party next week. The discovery of the
weapons prompted news media speculation that the IRA might be
planning a second bid to kill her.
   Sgt. John Brown, a spokesman at police headquarters in Belfast,
said the attack on the soldiers occurred just outside Londonderry,
Northern Ireland's second largest city, two miles from the border
with the Republic of Ireland.
   He said an army patrol in two armored jeeps was traveling north
on a main road leading from Londonderry when the land mine buried in
an embankment beside the road was detonated. The second of the two
jeeps caught the full blast.
   Police estimated 400 pounds of explosive were used.
   The blast blew in windows up to half a mile away and was
reportedly heard up to 30 miles away.
   The army identified the dead soldiers Thursday as Miles Daniel
Amos, 18, and Stephen Geoffrey Cummins, 24.
   The command wire was found leading to a nearby industrial estate
from where the bomber would have had a clear view of the road, Brown
said.
   Mrs. Thatcher survived an IRA bomb attack on Oct. 12, 1984 in
which five people died during the Conservatives' annual convention
at the south coast resort of Brighton. The blast partly demolished
the hotel where she, many of her Cabinet and many other prominent
Conservatives were staying.
   The mainly Roman Catholic IRA wants to unite the predominantly
Protestant province with the 95 percent Catholic Republic of Ireland
under socialist rule.
</TEXT>
