<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 1202EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Nicaragua     03-09 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nicaragua,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sandinista Newspaper Claims U.S. Re-arming Contras</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The official Sandinista newspaper
claimed today that U.S. helicopters and pilots are ferrying weapons
to the Nicaraguan rebel forces in Honduras.
   Barricada, mouthpiece of the leftist government party, based its
report on unidentified sources ``in national political circles'' in
Honduras.
   The U.S. Congress cut off military aid to the Contras, as the
guerrillas are known, in February 1988 but continued humanitarian
aid, which runs out at the end of this month.
   President Bush has said he will ask Congress to extend the
non-lethal assistance to the Contras, about 11,000 of which are
living in jungle camps in Honduras near the Nicaraguan border with
thousands of relatives.
   ``U.S. helicopters and pilots taking part in the `Ahuas Tara 89'
joint military maneuvers in Honduran territory are supplying arms
and ammunition to the Contra forces,'' Barricada said in a
front-page article.
   It said weapons shipments leave from the Tocontin, Palmerola and
Isla del Cisne (Swan Island) air force bases to Contra camps in
Yamales and Mokoron.
   According to Barricada, the operations involving five U.S.
helicopters started in mid-February. It said the helicopters are
UH-1H and Bell-212 models.
   Barricada said shipments have been made also using DC-6 cargo
planes from private company whose stockholders, the paper said, are
Honduran military officers.
   The Honduran-U.S. maneuvers began in late January and are
scheduled through July and involve about 3,000 U.S. and Honduran
military personnel. They are largely command and construction
exercises.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
