<FIRST>u a PM-WaterMainBreak 2ndLd-Writethru a0556 03-09 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Water Main Break, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0556,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Jersey Water Main Break Hits Several Million People, Closes Schools</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `In the ...' to CORRECT that water should be
boiled a few minutes, sted two hours.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORADELL, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A water main break cut off water to millions
of people in northern New Jersey this morning, forcing officials to
close schools and seek help from the National Guard.
   The break in the 52-inch main occurred at 5 a.m. between the two
main plants of the Hackensack Water Co., according to company
spokeswoman Martha Green. Water began flowing again to most of the
company's customers about 9:30 a.m., but it was at very low pressure
and residents were being urged to boil drinking water.
   Ken Madden, of the Bergen County emergency management office,
said National Guard tankers were brought to the armory in Teaneck,
where water would be distributed to those who need it.
   The company supplies water to 750,000 customers, or several
million people, in most of Bergen County and in the northern part of
Hudson County, officials said.
   The flow of water from the huge main, which washed out part of
New Milford Avenue here, was shut off by about 7:25 a.m., officials
said. Most of the water flowed back into the nearby Hackensack River
and did not threaten homes.
   Bob Weiner, a water company spokesman, said work crews isolated
the damaged pipe by about 9 a.m., closing valves near it and routing
water through other pipes. About a half-hour later, the water began
flowing, but it would take several hours to build enough pressure to
return service to normal, he said.
   In the meantime, he recommended that residents boil tap water for
at least a few minutes before using it, since some contaminants may
have gotten into the pipelines during the break.
   While most customers were beginning to get low-pressure water,
Weiner said, an unknown number still had service cut off entirely.
   Gov. Thomas Kean toured the site of the break this morning.
   Bergen County Superintendent of Schools Ray Kelly canceled
classes at all county public schools except for three districts not
served by Hackensack Water Co.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
