<FIRST>r a PM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0526 03-09 0925</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deaths, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0526,494,0956</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES 1st item with details on Rumbaugh. A separate moved
for PMs as a0462 on Rumbaugh; includes sub moved on Powers.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>James Rumbaugh</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Army Maj. Gen. James H. Rumbaugh, commander of
Walter Reed Army Medical Center in Washington, died of injuries
suffered during a parachute accident in Honduras, the Pentagon said
today.
   Rumbaugh died while being flown to the Brooke Army Medical Center
in San Antonio, Texas, said Defense Department spokesman Maj. John
Smith.
   Rumbaugh, 49, was participating in the annual Ahuas Tara 89
exercise with a forward surgical deployment team.
   According to Pentagon sources, who insisted on anonymity,
Rumbaugh suffered abdominal injuries during a jump Tuesday. They
said Rumbaugh did not seek medical attention until Wednesday morning
and died that evening.
   Army and Pentagon officials declined to say why a two-star
general was participating in a jump and how extensive Rumbaugh's
parachute experience was.
   Rumbaugh took command of Walter Reed last August. A native of
Washington, Pa., Rumbaugh earned his medical degree from the Thomas
Jefferson University School of Medicine in Philadelphia.
   He joined the Army in 1963 while completing his studies and then
served his internship and a residency in psychiatry at Walter Reed.
   Rumbaugh earned his first star as a brigadier general in
September 1986 and his second last October. His decorations included
the Legion of Merit, the Bronze Star, the Meritorious Service Medal
with Oak Leaf Cluster, the Army Commendation Medal and the Expert
Field Medical Badge.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Edward Powers</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edward Powers, the FBI agent who helped
solve the $2.2 million Brinks armored car robbery in 1950 and was
picked to manage the first modern U.S. lottery, died Tuesday in Fort
Myers, Fla., at age 75.
   Powers, as FBI agent in charge of the Boston office, spent six
years trying to solve the Brinks case. The break came when one of
the holdup men informed on the others because he felt he didn't get
his fair share of the loot.
   In 1963, he was hired to manage the New Hampshire lottery because
its sponsors wanted to prove it could be run without organized crime
influence. He retired in 1978 and moved to Florida.
   A 400-page reference manual, ``Handbook of U.S. Lottery
Fundamentals,'' recognizes Powers as the ``father of U.S.
lotteries.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Stuart Hamblen</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stuart Hamblen, a country music
yodeler, died Wednesday at age 80.
   After winning a yodeling contest, Hamblen, made his first
recording at the Victor Talking Machine Co., now RCA. Hamblen moved
to Los Angeles and worked at radio station KFI, where he was known
on a country program as Cowboy Joe.
   During the 1950s, Hamblen wrote several songs that cemented his
place in gospel and country music history. Hamblen's records
included ``It Is No Secret What God Can Do,'' ``This Old House,''
``Open Up Your Heart (And Let the Sun Shine In),'' ``Remember Me,
I'm the One Who Loves You'' and ``Texas Plains.''
   Many of his religious and inspirational songs have been recorded
by artists like Jo Stafford, Kate Smith, Ray Price, Jimmy Dean and
Mahalia Jackson. Rosemary Clooney's version of ``This Ole House''
became a million-seller.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Leo Plofker</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leo Plofker, a structural engineer responsible
for the skeletal design of several skycrapers including the Pan Am
tower over Grand Central Terminal in New York, died of a heart
attack Monday at his home. He was 67.
   Plofker, a native of Brooklyn, worked on several other New York
buildings, including the Olympic Tower on Fifth Avenue, and on
structures in Philadelphia, Pittsburgh, Chicago and other cities.
   At his death, he was a partner in The Office of James Ruderman,
structural engineers in Manhattan. He joined the company in 1950.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Judson Philips</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CANAAN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Judson Philips, an author of dozens of
mystery novels, died Tuesday at age 85.
   Philips was the recipient of an Edgar Award. He was also the
first president of the Mystery Writers of America.
   Philips was president for many years of the Sharon Playhouse, a
summer stock theater which he helped found in 1950.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Jay Spry</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jay Spry, a former newsman for The Sun, retired
public relations executive for Exxon Oil Co. and noted creator of
crossword puzzles, died Tuesday at age 72.
   Spry worked as a reporter at The Sun after graduating from
college in 1937. He left the newspaper in 1952 for Esso Standard Oil
Co., now Exxon, and became head of corporate press relations at the
company's New York headquarters. Spry took early retirement from
Exxon in 1968 and returned to The Sun in 1976, retiring in 1982.
   He and his wife, Carolyn Crane Spry, who died in 1973, created
puzzles that were printed and reprinted in dozens of popular
collections. Spry's more challenging works appeared regularly in The
New York Times Sunday Magazine, the National Observer and other
publications.
   Spry is survived by his son, Jay F., of Annapolis; a stepson,
Charles C. Hartman Jr. of Severna Park; his mother, Nellie Majors
Spry of Dover, Del.; and three sisters, Margaret Cadell of
Catonsville, Ruth Garretson of Severna Park, and Genevieve McGee of
Laurel, Del.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Helen Grace Coates</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Helen Grace Coates, who was Leonard Bernstein's
piano teacher and later his personal secretary, died Feb. 27 at her
home. She was 89.
   Miss Coates, who was born in Rockford, Ill., studied and taught
in Boston. She became Bernstein's secretary in 1943, and worked
until a few days before her death.
</TEXT>
