<HEAD>35 Vietnamese Refugees Rescued By Japanese Ship</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Asia-Refugees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty-five Vietnamese refugees
were rescued by a Japanese tanker after their boat sank during bad
weather in the South China Sea off Malaysia, authorities said
Thursday.
   The incident occurred on Wednesday, the second day of a three-day
meeting on Indochinese refugees.
   The group of 30 men, two women and three children were picked up
by the tanker Nessei Maru, said Capt. Jaffar Lamri, head of the
Maritime Rescue Coordination Center.
   He told the National News Agency Bernama the incident occurred
when the apparently overloaded boat broke when it was hit by strong
waves and capsized about 220 miles off Malaysia's Trengganu coast.
   The boat was said to be heading for Malaysia after leaving
Vietnam, Jaffar said.
   The rescue center was put on standby after being alerted by a
ship in the area that a boat had sunk and several people were
floating in the sea, he said. The center contacted all ships in the
area and received a message from the 238,517-ton Nissei Maru saying
it had rescued the passengers.
   The Vietnamese refugees were taken to Singapore for treatment,
Jaffar said.
