<SECOND>PM-Bingo Licenses,0150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tennessee Suspends Bingo Licenses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Alcoholic Beverage Commission ordered
the state's nearly 200 bingo operators to cease operations today
because of a Tennessee Supreme Court ruling that the game is an
unconstitutional lottery.
   The ABC voted unanimously to inform license holders of the
suspension and of a March 30 hearing on the issue.
   The action was based on a memorandum from Attorney General
Charles Burson, who advised the agency to suspend the licenses ``and
thereby immediately terminate bingo operations in this state.''
   Commissioner Carl Jones said he sympathized with charities and
elderly bingo players who would miss the game.
   ``I've seen them come in and cry,'' he said.
   Commissioner Dale Woodall said he did not think there was any
chance that bingo licenses could be issued again unless a
Constitutional Convention were held to remove the lottery
prohibition.
