<FIRST>u i PM-SpySentenced     03-09 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spy Sentenced,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canadian Sentenced For Spying For Soviet Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. JOHN'S, Newfoundland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of trying to obtain
secrets from a U.S. Navy base was sentenced today to nine years in
prison for spying for the Soviet Union.
   Stephen Ratkai, 26, had pleaded guilty in Newfoundland Supreme
Court to one count of espionage and another count of attempted
espionage. He faced a maximum prison sentence of 14 years on each
count. Ratkai was sentenced to nine years on each count, to be
served concurrently.
   ``Your conduct and the paraphernalia with which you worked showed
that you were more than just a courier,'' said Judge Fintan Aylward.
``You were a well-trained and intelligent individual. You knew what
to do and how to do it.''
   ``I cannot say what harm was done to national security, but the
potential was substantial, and you were well aware of it,'' the
judge said.
   Ratkai, a Canadian citizen who grew up in Nova Scotia and
Hungary, was arrested in St. John's during a sting operation set up
by Canadian and U.S. intelligence officers in June.
   Prosecutors say that over 13 months, beginning in May 1987,
Ratkai made three trips aimed at obtaining secret documents from the
U.S. Navy base in Argentia, in eastern Newfoundland.
   During the sting operation, Ratkai met with a U.S. undercover
agent, Lt. Donna Geiger. Canadian and U.S. officials videotaped one
of the meetings, during which Ratkai gave Ms. Geiger money and
pressed her for more information about the U.S. base.
   When Ratkai was arrested, he was carrying more than $4,700 and a
portable kit for developing film.
</TEXT>
