<SECOND>PM-Japan-Libya, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0503,a0507,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan Denies Reported Links to Alleged Libyan Chemical Plant</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs after 5th graf pvs, ``Mitsubishi, in...'' to
UPDATE with White House Reaction. Pickup 6th graf pvs, ``The reports...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE KURTENBACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today denied reports that a Japanese
manufacturer in line to make a new version of the F-16 fighter jet
was involved in construction of what Washington says is a Libyan
chemical weapons plant.
   ``I have said in this forum again and again that we have made a
thorough study on this problem. ... We found that there was no
evidence that Japanese companies have been involved in this
project,'' said Foreign Ministry spokesman Taizo Watanabe.
   ``I can now confirm that Mitsubishi Heavy Industries has never
been engaged in the export of equipment or dispatch of engineers as
reported in The Detroit News,'' Watanabe added.
   The Detroit News on Wednesday quoted unidentified U.S.
congressional and Defense Department sources as saying they had been
told of Mitsubishi's alleged participation in the Libyan project by
intelligence sources in Washington. Kyodo News Service carried a
similar report today.
   Mitsubishi, in a news conference today, also denied the reports.
   In Washington, Marlin Fitzwater, a spokesman for President Bush,
said: ``We continue to investigate this matter.''
   At the same time, he said, ``The Japanese government has given us
assurances that there is no intention of any Japanese involvement
with the Libyan project and has denied emphatically any involvement
by Mitsubishi Heavy Industries' technicians or engineers in the
Libyan chemical project.''
   The reports said intelligence sources had told a closed-door
session of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee that 50 Japanese
technicians and engineers were at a chemical complex in the desert
south of the Libyan capital of Tripoli to install metal-machining
equipment used to make bomb canisters for poison gas.
   Libya denies the plant is for making chemical weapons, saying
that it is a pharmaceuticals factory.
   On Wednesday, State Department spokesman Charles Redman said the
department had no evidence Mitsubishi had helped to install
equipment at the plant.
   Watanabe said Japan had conveyed its findings to Washington
through regular communications channels.
   ``From the statement made by Mr. Redman, I take it they have
accepted our information,'' he said.
   He then read a statement that said:
   ``Through the exchange of information between the U.S. government
and Japan, the following views are fully shared by the two
governments:
   ``According to the investigation of the government of Japan so
far, there is no information indicating that Japanese firms were
involved in Libya's production of chemical weapons agents and its
facilities.''
   The Kyodo report said the allegations against Mitsubishi were
``expected to spur congressional moves to persuade the U.S.
government to scrap a plan for General Dynamics to provide
(Mitsubishi) with high technology'' to build Japan's new fighter
jet, called the FSX, a version of the U.S. F-16.
   Mitsubishi is involved in a proposed joint venture with the
United States to build the plane. The venture was negotiated during
the Reagan administration and is now under review by the Bush
administration.
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater on Wednesday
declined to comment directly on the reports about Mitsubishi and
said President Bush had not yet made a final decision on the FSX
project.
</TEXT>
