<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 1307EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     03-09 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0434</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>POMONA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman whose son was given detention for
missing high school believed it wasn't his fault _ so she served the
punishment for him.
   Vickey Esquivel said she turned off her three boys' alarm clocks
after she heard from a friend that school had been canceled because
of a winter storm Jan. 30.
   It wasn't.
   The Esquivels realized that school was in session after the
snowstorm stopped and one of the boys ran into two of his teachers
at a store in this farming community 60 miles from Kansas City. The
teachers were getting lunch.
   That story was good enough to get the youngest and middle son off
the hook, but the Pomona High School principal wanted Sam, 16, to
serve a detention.
   Instead, Ms. Esquivel spent an hour and 45 minutes vacuuming and
cleaning at school March 3 and again Tuesday.
   The idea of having Ms. Esquivel serve the sentence came from
Superintendent James Cain, who said he ``made the comment more in
jest than in meaning.''
   After taking him up on the idea, Ms. Esquivel said she is
satisfied. So is Sam, though he wonders why his mother stopped at
serving detention.
   ``She could have done my homework,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state's tourism slogan, ``Wander
Indiana,'' may get the boot after seven years on T-shirts, tote
bags, coffee mugs and license plates.
   It just isn't working, market research shows, so the state
Department of Commerce is considering dropping it.
   People in Chicago and Cincinnati were asked recently what they
thought about the ``Wander Indiana'' television and print ads.
   ``They didn't know what it meant,'' Denise L. Miller, the state's
new tourism director, said Wednesday. ``It was aimless, not really
exciting. It made us sound hick.''
   A similar survey of Indianapolis residents reinforced the
findings. ``They were even nastier about `Wander Indiana,''' said
Miller.
   Miller said the state's tourism contract with an advertising
agency is up for review in June. The stakes are high. The state
estimates tourism pumps $6.2 billion into Indiana's economy each
year.
   To attract even more revenue, Miller has asked the Legislature to
boost tourism appropriations to $4 million by 1991, from the present
$2.1 million.
   Miller said that is much less than what the state's neighbors
spend when they invite Hoosiers to ``Say Yes to Michigan,'' ``Escape
to Wisconsin,'' travel to ``Ohio, the heart of it all,'' or let
Illinois ``put you in a happy state.''
</TEXT>
