<FIRST>r w AM-Japanese-Americans     03-09 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japanese-Americans,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vets Group Sues in Fight Against Japanese-American Compensation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A veterans group said Thursday it had filed a
federal lawsuit challenging a law to compensate Japanese-Americans
who were interned during World War II.
   Under the law, the U.S. government is to provide $20,000 in
compensation to each of some 60,000 surviving Japanese-Americans who
were interned by the government. A total of about 120,000
Japanese-Americans were put in camps after Pearl Harbor.
   John P. Coale, a Washington attorney handling the lawsuit filed
in U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia, said the court
action was based on the fact that the legislation does not provide
compensation for 2,000 to 3,000 German- and Italian-Americans who
were also interned during the war.
   ``The Japanese-Americans are singled out to be compensated,''
Coale told a news conference.
   Regarding their internment, Coale said, ``We're not saying it was
a fair action, but there were many, many unfair actions during World
War II.''
   The suit was filed on behalf of the American War Veterans Relief
Association, a 30,000-member group based in Anaheim, Calif. The
organization provides emergency financial assistance and shelter to
needy veterans.
   John Kirby, the group's administrator, said, ``Millions of
veterans over the age of 60 who served faithfully in World War II
live in fear that Congress will cut their Social Security and
Medicaid benefits.''
   ``This suit is being filed for those veterans who are outraged
that the same Congress which has pledged to handle the federal
deficit problem has passed a law handing out $1.25 billion'' in
compensation, he said.
</TEXT>
