<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 1316EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-America Bjt   03-09 0875</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-America, Bjt,0894</SECOND>
<HEAD>Glasnost Doesn't Bar Anti-American Booklets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Warmer superpower relations have not stopped a
Soviet agency from spreading timeworn charges that the FBI murdered
the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. and that the CIA massacred Jim Jones
and 900 of his People's Temple followers in Guyana.
   It's all part of ``glasnost,'' President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
policy of greater openness, according to a top editor at the Soviet
press agency Novosti. But U.S. officials call it blatant lying and
say it's designed to harm the reputation of the United States.
   The anti-American charges, and literally hundreds more like them,
are contained in booklets published recently by Novosti, whose motto
is ``Information for Peace and International Friendship.''
   The deputy editor-in-chief of Novosti's North American
department, Yevgeny A. Posdnyakov, says the slick publications are
not just recycled Cold War-type propaganda. He claims they are part
of the campaign for greater frankness and wider debate launched by
Gorbachev.
   ``There is a need to write about everything so people will make
up their own mind and understand things,'' Posdnyakov said in an
interview. ``The demand that some zones be free from inquiry by
journalists would be an attack on glasnost.''
   The view from Washington is far different: at least one of the
Novosti books, ``Once Again About the CIA,'' is full of untruths and
innuendo designed to smear the reputation of the United States, U.S.
officials charge.
   ``We have discussed this book with the Soviets as a particularly
egregious example of what we call disinformation,'' said U.S.
Embassy spokesman Richard Gilbert. ``It contains outright
falsehoods, and we've told them we don't think the continued
distribution of this book is in keeping with the increasing positive
tone of our relationship.''
   Nevertheless, ``Once Again About the CIA,'' whose cover shows
bloody corpses imposed on the Central Intelligence Agency's seal, is
being distributed in special waiting rooms of Moscow airports
reserved for foreigners. According to Posdnyakov, 10,000 copies were
printed in English.
   Novosti publications also are available in Intourist hotels,
whose clientele is largely foreign; from Aeroflot, the Soviet
airline; and from Soviet embassies and other institutions abroad.
   Paradoxically, the publication of the books, largely intended for
foreign markets, comes as official media whose audience is mostly
Soviet are finding much about the United States to praise. Ogonyok
magazine recently asked whether a U.S.-style jury system could be
instituted, and on Thursday the Communist Party daily Pravda lauded
the taste of McDonald's hamburgers.
   The Novosti books strike a far different note. Among recent
releases:
   _ ``Silent Terror,'' billed as ``the book U.S. censors don't want
Americans to read.'' Written by former U.S. cancer researcher Arnold
Lockshin and his wife, Lauren, who obtained political asylum in the
Soviet Union in 1986, the book recounts ``the silent campaign of
harassment and terror which the FBI (the U.S. political police)
organized to force them to conform politically _ or be sorry.''
   The former Houston couple _ members of the Communist Party U.S.A.
who came to Moscow with their three children _ accuse the FBI of
waging an intimidation campaign that included the bugging of their
home, false entries on their telephone bills, harassment of their
daughter, Jennifer, by her high school Russian teacher and the
killing of mice that Lockshin was using in experiments at Houston's
Stehlin Foundation for Cancer Research.
   The Lockshins also say it was an ``inescapable conclusion ...
that the FBI murdered King,'' the late civil rights leader.
   Their book was printed in 10,000 copies in English, Posdnyakov
said. ``When Lockshin proposed having the book published, it was a
scoop the agency couldn't pass up,'' he said.
   _ ``American Cultural Invasion in Europe'' by Yuri Kagramanov,
with a 12,000-copy press run in English, has a cover showing a satyr
wearing a cowboy hat seemingly about to rape a naked woman
symbolizing Europe. Its author quotes writers ranging from Norwegian
novelist Knut Hamsun to jazz pioneer Dave Brubeck to buttress his
thesis that U.S. ``bourgeois ideology and culture'' are overrunning
the Old World.
   _ ``Once Again About the CIA,'' in 117 pages, accuses the U.S.
intelligence service of committing the ``monstrous crime'' of
killing the Rev. Jim Jones and over 900 of his followers at
Jonestown, Guyana in 1978 and of assassinating foreign leaders like
Panama's Omar Torrijos and the Congo's Patrice Lumumba.
   The booklet all but openly charges the CIA with the unsuccessful
attempt on the pope's life in 1981, which an Italian state
prosecutor linked instead to the secret service of Bulgaria, a
Soviet ally.
   ``There is some evidence indicating the CIA had a finger in the
attempted assaasination of Pope John Paul II,'' the book says.
``John Paul II made enemies in the West by his statements in defense
of peace ... and against the capitalist exploitation of the working
people.''
   Posdnyakov said he had no knowledge of the official U.S. protests
over ``Once Again About the CIA,'' but said that thanks to glasnost,
the agency could now take up its case with Novosti.
   ``The chief editor has said that he'll publish the CIA
disclaimers if we put out a second edition, and provided, of course,
that the CIA can prove that its version of events is true,''
Posdnyakov said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
