<FIRST>r a PM-People-KittyDukakis     03-09 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Kitty Dukakis,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governor's Wife Discusses Drinking</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kitty Dukakis, wife of Gov. Michael Dukakis, said
today that she continues to fight her alcoholism but plans to resume
her busy public life and schedule.
   ``I am an alcoholic,'' she said, adding that she hoped the public
nature of her visit to a treatment center would encourage others to
follow her route.
   ``I would have preferred to deal with my private trouble in
private,'' she said, acknowledging that was not possible as the wife
of Massachusetts' governor.
   ``One of the mysteries of this disease is that you can have a
loving family, a network of caring friends and still face recovery
every day,'' she said, asking that she be afforded some privacy
during the fight.
   Mrs. Dukakis, 52, responded to an outpouring of more than 2,000
letters from well wishers with a letter of her own published today
on the front page of USA Today.
   The letter said, in part, ``I have always believed that every
experience we have in life provides an opportunity for growth and
learning. The thousands of letters I received from you contributed
to my growth and I have drawn strength from all that you have shared
with me.''
   Mrs. Dukakis returned home Tuesday after spending 31 days at
Edgehill Newport, a private short-term treatment facility in Rhode
Island. It offers an intensive treatment program following a
detoxification period.
   In the three months following her husband's defeat in November's
presidential election, Mrs. Dukakis' drinking became a serious
problem, the governor said. He described it as her chemical
dependency resurfacing. He blamed exhaustion, stress and ``the
post-election let-down.''
</TEXT>
