<DOCNO> AP890309-0114 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 1357EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a BC-Eastern-BakesStatement 2Takes   03-09 0853</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Eastern-Bakes Statement, 2 Takes,0872</SECOND>
<HEAD>Statement of Eastern Airlines President Phil Bakes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Eastern</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the statement of Eastern Airlines
President Phil Bakes at a news conference Thursday announcing that
the strikebound airline had filed for Chapter 11 protection under
the U.S. Bankruptcy Code.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   We have petitioned the Federal Court in New York for protection
under the bankruptcy laws.
   Turning to what we have always viewed as the last resort of
bankruptcy has been brought about by the airline pilots union
grounding, or virtual grounding, of our airline. It has not only
paralyzed our operation and severely inconvenienced customers, but
has precipitated a potential cash crisis at the company that can
only be averted and stabilized by seeking protection under the
bankruptcy laws.
   I want to emphasize and re-emphasize what Frank said. We intend
to operate our airline. And make no mistake about that. We intend to
continue our immediate emphasis on the shuttle and South America,
and then prudently, but unmistakeably, put back into the sky more
airplanes and go back into service in many of the markets that we
have served up until last week. And we'll do that as pilots become
available, and the bankruptcy process itself will substantially
assist our ability to build back the airline.
   The steps we've been forced to take because of the virtual
shutdown of the company will also require that we entertain
transactions that, like the proposed sale of the Eastern Airlines
shuttle to Donald Trump, will provide liquidity and cash resources _
the lifeblood, if you will _ to allow us to resuscitate a smaller,
but certainly a revitalized, and certainly viable Eastern Airlines.
   We fully intend to meet _ and we intend to ... and we have
confidence in saying that _ all of our obligations to our creditors
and we are confident there will be substantial value for our
shareholders.
   Despite the fact that the reorganization should be a successful
one, I have to echo Frank's comment that the last five days have
been the saddest five days of my life. This is the last course of...
the last resort that we ever thought we'd have to pursue. To see the
tens of thousands of men and women who have been inconvenienced is
tough. To go from last week 30,000 employees of Eastern Airlines to
1,500 employees today is something that will be with me for the rest
of my life. But we're going to go on and we're going to build.
   Although the immediate precipitating crisis has been the pilot
union decision to shut down most of our airplanes, the larger story
of Eastern Airlines is a story that goes back many years. Most of
the problems at Eastern have preceded the acquisiton by Texas Air.
   In the post decade of deregulation in the 1980s, Eastern has lost
$1.5 billion on airline operations. During that same period of time
the competition had earned $2 billion. And much of that $2 billion
was reinvested in airplanes that ended up in our market. In the last
five years we have seen approximately 1,600 new daily competitive
flights by our competitors in the market areas that we serve east of
the Mississippi.
   The causes of Eastern's losses go back many many years. They
start, acutally, in the late 1950s and early 1960s. Eastern was slow
to convert and stayed with props a little too long.
   The problems date to the 1970s when Eastern's labor costs were
among the highest _ if not the highest _ in the entire airline
industry. And they continue through the 1980s when Easterns unions,
most particularly the International Association of Machinists,
resisted agreeing to productive and affordable labor settlements
that could have provided the company the strength to not only meet
the competition but to grow substantially as many other airlines did.
   And labor strife, not just high labor costs, at Eastern Airlines
over the last 10 years has taken its toll. It's diverted the
attention of all of us _ management and non-management alike _ and
yes, it's diverted a lot of customers from Eastern Airlines.
   Eastern today, as a result of that, has a weakened revenue
structure much too dependent on discretionary, lower-priced,
non-business travelers.
   The losses and high labor costs had to be paid from somewhere.
And they were. Over the years, in the '70s and early 1980s and up
until very recently, Eastern borrowed, very heavily, to meet the
high labor cost bill, to make up for the depressed revenue
structure, to cover operating losses.
   And more recently, when debt was not really available to us,
nobody really wanted to loan money to Eastern Airlines, we had to
sell some assets, to raise cash, to meet payroll, and to continue in
operation.
   In fact, if we had not sold the assets we have sold over the last
couple of years, this news conference would have been held about a
year and a half ago, and we wouldn't be talking about rehabilitating
the company _ the company would never fly again if we had not done
that.
</TEXT>
