<FIRST>r w AM-ResidentialRates     03-09 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Residential Rates,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Activists Told Trend Can Only Be Reversed By Pressure on Regulators</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Activists were told Thursday that they must
oppose a trend of regulated industries forcing bigger price
increases on individual consumers than on business customers.
   The trend can only be reversed by pressure on state and federal
regulators, said Mark Cooper, research director of the Consumer
Federation of America, at his group's annual convention.
   Charges for electricity, natural gas, and telephone service
increased more rapidly in the 1980s for residential customers than
others, and checking account charges rose most rapidly for
low-balance accounts, Cooper said.
   ``I think there's a lot at stake here,'' although ``these kinds
of issues don't grab the lapels of ... consumer advocates. This is
esoteric stuff that can put most regulators to sleep,'' he said.
   The rates are important because the increases reduce the buying
power of the incomes of the poor, he said.
   He said that electricity, gas, telephones and checking accounts
take up 6 percent of the average household's spending, but in the
poorest fifth of households these items eat up 26 percent of the
budget.
   Though industrial and residential rates for electricity and gas
rose together in the 1970s, in the 1980s ``rates for industrial
users became uncoupled,'' he said.
   For example, he said:
   _From 1981 through 1988, average residential electric rates rose
20 percent but industrial rates did not change.
   _In those years residential gas rates rose 5 percent, while
industrial gas rates fell 25 percent.
   _In that period local residential telephone rates rose 75
percent, private lines rose 55 percent and WATS lines rose only 5
percent.
   Though long-distance rates declined, ``unfortunately the average
consumer does not make enough (long-distance) calls to break even on
the deal,'' Cooper said.
   _The annual cost of a checking account almost doubled from 1977
to 1985 for people earning $10,000 or less per year, while those
earning more than $50,000 kept balances large enough to stop paying
fees and earn interest.
   In the three utility areas, ``industrial users assaulted the
regulatory commissions,'' Cooper said.
   ``They extracted the freedom to shop around, when residential
consumers can't. They threatened to leave town, when residential
consumers can't. They threatened to build their own systems, when
residential consumers can't,'' he said. ``None of these threats,
almost none of them, were ever backed up.''
   In banking, he said, ``The regulators essentially left the
field.''
   ``The solution is obvious: to beat the regulators about the head
until they get the pricing schemes fixed ... you have to do it
politically.''
   Edward Byers, vice president of Cambridge Reports Inc., a polling
firm, told the convention ``generally there's a lot of confusion''
about natural gas and electricity issues. ``We get very high rates
of `no opinion,' `don't know' or contradictory results.''
   Where there are clear currents of opinion, people are concerned
``that any deregulatory effort is going to raise their prices. They
are not concerned about impacts on service reliability or quality,''
Byers said.
</TEXT>
