<FIRST>r a AM-Cavazos     03-09 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cavazos,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Education Secretary Visits South Bronx Catholic School</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Education Secretary Lauro Cavazos visited a
Roman Catholic elementary school in one of the nation's most
depressed urban communities Thursday, praising its unusual blend of
art and academics.
   ``I think that any school that is well run, that is orderly, that
is free of drugs, all schools should be like that,'' Cavazos said.
   St. Augustine School of The Arts, for kindergartners through
eighth graders, nearly all of whom are black, was profiled in
December on CBS' ``60 Minutes'' as an educational oasis in
slum-ridden section of the South Bronx.
   Despite his praise for the school, Cavazos indicated to reporters
he was not interested in renewing the debate over whether parents of
Catholic and other private school students should get tuition tax
credits or vouchers.
   ``I'm not really pushing for tuition tax credits or vouchers,''
Cavazos said.
   Yet Principal Thomas Pilecki said he remained optimistic.
   ``I'm hopeful his (Cavazos') visit here will help him see the
strength of Catholic schools,'' he said. ``We don't have any money
at all. We don't have a cent.''
   From the 1970s through 1984, the school's enrollment dropped from
about 500 to less than 200 and the New York Archdiocese was
threatening to close it. But St. Augustine began an unusual
curriculum built around a fine arts program in the 1984, and
enrollment now stands at 320. Tuition is $1,100 a year.
   The curriculum combines the usual academic subjects with
instruction in art, dance and especially music, taught by
professionals. Piano is mandatory through fourth grade. Each student
must also learn at least one other instrument.
   St. Augustine is the only parochial school in the archdiocese
specializing in fine arts. Unlike most fine arts schools, it admits
all comers, regardless of talent.
   Youngsters showed Cavazos their musical prowess with a more than
respectable rendition of the national anthem during an assembly in
his honor.
   ``It takes a lot of practice,'' said 10-year-old Sharene
Lindquist, who has studied piano and clarinet. ``You don't have to
be an expert. If you've got problems, you can always go to the
teacher.''
   The arts program is supported by about $350,000 a year in
foundation and corporate grants.
   But finances are sometimes so tight that ``at times teachers have
been asked not to cash their paychecks,'' said the Rev. Robert
Jeffers, pastor of St. Augustine.
   The arts program has paid off, said Jeffers, because it ``gives
children a constant sense of accomplishment.''
   During a tour of the school, Cavazos stopped in on Yvonne
Rhem-Tittle's eighth-grade science class and quizzed youngsters
about their assignments.
   They in turn presented him with a maroon and white T-shirt with
the school emblem.
</TEXT>
