<FIRST>r p AM-BurlingtonMayor     03-09 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burlington Mayor,0541</SECOND>
<HEAD>Socialist Mayor's Successor Has Working-Class Roots</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BURLINGTON, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man elected to succeed Bernie Sanders,
the city's socialist mayor, ran on the same left-wing platform and
says his job is to ``tilt the scales'' toward those not rich enough
to protect their interests.
   But Peter Clavelle shies away from the socialist label.
   ``Very few people understand socialism. I don't have a great
understanding of it myself,'' said Sanders' community development
director, who was elected mayor Tuesday. ``I was not schooled in the
Lenin-Marxist analysis.''
   The 39-year-old Clavelle, who has taken a magazine's description
of him _ ``bald, paunchy, colorless'' _ as a badge of honor, was
chosen by the city's third-party Progressive Coalition to run after
Sanders decided against a fifth two-year term.
   He drew 5,626 votes, or 53 percent, to 4,400 or 42 percent for
Nancy Chioffi, a Democrat. A tax revolt candidate and one from the
environmentalist Greens party split the rest of the vote.
   Burlington, Vermont's largest city with a population of 38,000,
drew widespread attention eight years ago when Sanders, a rumpled,
tieless radical educated at the University of Chicago, was elected
by 10 votes.
   Clavelle and Sanders joined forces shortly afterward, when
Clavelle went to work first as personnel director and then as chief
of development.
   Clavelle has won high marks for his efforts to preserve low-cost
housing, to get more women into jobs and help stem domestic abuse,
and to create amenities such as a boathouse and bike path on Lake
Champlain.
   He and others describe his approach as low-key, not as
confrontational as Sanders.'
   Garrison Nelson, a University of Vermont political scientist,
said Clavelle has been a key behind-the-scenes player in the city's
many tussles with developers over whether they will build or
renovate affordable housing in exchange for permission to build
higher-priced properties.
   ``When Bernie Sanders makes his outburst against the rapacious
developers and stomps out of the room, Peter's the guy who will then
shut the door and say, `OK, let's sign the contract,''' Nelson said.
``He's sort of been the good cop to Bernie Sanders' bad cop.''
   Of his style of governance, Clavelle said, ``The mayor ought to
be open to perspectives from the entire community. But those who
have the money, those who have the power do a pretty good job
representing themselves. So the mayor's role is to attempt to tilt
the scales just a little bit.''
   Clavelle grew up in the blue-collar suburb of Winooski and
remembers being called a ``river rat'' by affluent high school
classmates.
   He became the first in his family to graduate from college and
pursued a career in city management because ``it seemed like
something where you could make a difference.''
   He was hired at 23 as town manager in the town of Castleton then
moved to the same job in Winooski four years later.
   When a proposed budget there was voted down, Clavelle drained the
municipal swimming pool during a heat wave, saying the city couldn't
afford it. He resigned in disgust at what he called a lack of
support for city services.
</TEXT>
