<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 1630EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Botha     03-09 0670</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Botha,0687</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Party Leader Fails to Resolve Potential Conflict With Botha</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new leader of the governing
National Party conferred Thursday with ailing President P.W. Botha,
but failed to resolve a potential power struggle.
   Botha, reportedly defying the wishes of his own party, announced
he would return to work next week after a two-month convalesence
from a stroke.
   The party leader, Education Minister F.W. de Klerk, indicated an
impasse remained, saying his talks with Botha would continue at an
unspecified later date. State-run television said the meeting ``was
apparently a very tough session'' which ended with ``no clear
agreement on working relations'' between Botha and de Klerk, the
heir apparent for the presidency.
   Botha said he would resume his duties at a Cabinet meeting on
Wednesday, when the government presents its annual budget. Last
week, Botha had said he would not return to office until April, and
indicated he was irked at suggestions that he retire.
   The independent South African Press Association reported that the
caucus of National Party members of Parliament was dissatisified
with Botha's stance and wanted a firm pledge from him to retire as
soon as feasible to make way for de Klerk.
   Botha's statement gave no indication how long he planned to
continue in office and made no mention of his meeting with de Klerk.
   Before the meeting, there were unconfirmed press reports that a
compromise would be proposed, with Botha remaining as president
temporarily but agreeing to let de Klerk succeed him in a general
election held within the next few months.
   The Star of Johannesburg, the country's largest daily newspaper,
quoted National Party sources as saying Botha might reject the
compromise and thus provoke a confrontation.
   De Klerk described his talks with Botha as ``comprehensive and
penetrating,'' but no further details were disclosed about the
meeting, held at Botha's official residence in Cape Town.
   Botha, 73, suffered a stroke Jan. 18 and resigned as National
Party leader on Feb. 2. He was replaced by de Klerk, marking the
first time that the party leader was not also the head of government.
   Among South Africa's 5 million whites, there has been a largely
favorable reaction to the prospect of a de Klerk presidency. Even
staunchly pro-government newspapers have suggested the time has come
for Botha to step aside after holding power since 1978.
   When Botha said in an interview last week that he intended to
return to office in April, there were widespread predictions of a
bitter power struggle between him and de Klerk, whose party post
gives him no formal role in government policy-making. Botha said he
had a duty to continue in office despite ``derision and attacks''
aimed at him.
   While Botha flew Thursday from his holiday coastal home to Cape
Town, De Klerk and other National Party members of Parliament met in
private to discuss the situation.
   After the meeting, the caucus released a statement saying its
members had reached unanimous agreement on the issue of political
power. It did not elaborate.
   De Klerk, who also holds the post of National Party leader for
Transvaal Province, then went to Botha's office accompanied by
leaders of the party branches in the other three provinces. The Cape
Province leader, Constitutional Development Minister Chris Heunis,
is serving as acting president during Botha's convalesence.
   Business Day, a Johannesburg financial newspaper, said only Botha
himself could arrange a dignified departure from office.
   ``If he engages in further power struggles and manipulations ...
he will leave office a pathetic figure,'' an editorial said. ``The
fact is that de Klerk has a chance of making a political
breakthrough; President Botha has none.''
   De Klerk has not repudiated any of Botha's major policies, but he
is depicted as more pragmatic and flexible. However, he has
reaffirmed the government's commitment to segregated neighborhoods
and schools for whites who want them, and he has given no indication
he would consider full voting rights for the country's 28 million
blacks.
</TEXT>
