<FIRST>u w PM-Soviet-Expelled 1stLd-Writethru a0647 03-09 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Expelled, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0647,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 3rd graf, The FBI, to give more detil on time element and
expulsion, ADDS 1 graf with source identifying Pakhtusov as a member of
the Soviet GRU</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet military attache was ordered home
today by the State Department after being caught receiving
classified documents from an American employee of a U.S. firm with
government contracts, a spokesman said.
   Lt. Col. Yuriy Nikolayevich Pakhtusov, who arrived here last
June, received documents dealing with how the U.S. government
protects classified and other sensitive information in computer
systems, State Department press officer Dennis Harter said.
   The FBI said Pakhtusov was arrested Wednesday evening. It was not
disclosed how long he is being given to leave the United States. But
one government source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said it
was expected Pakhtusov would be given 24 to 48 hours to return to
his homeland.
   Harter said the Soviet Embassy was informed that Pakhtusov was
being expelled for ``engaging in activities incompatible with his
diplomatic status.''
   The name of the company whose documents Pakhtusov sought was not
disclosed.
   Harter said Pakhtusov approached the American last August and
asked about the possibility of acquiring the secret documents. The
American, whose identity was not disclosed, reported the contact to
the FBI, which began monitoring contacts between the two.
   Pakhtusov, 35, was identified by the government source as a
member of the Red Army's GRU intelligence arm. He was described by
the source as a significant catch because of his rank in the GRU.
</TEXT>
