<FIRST>u i AM-Vatican-Bishops Bjt   03-09 0692</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vatican-Bishops, Bjt,0714</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ratzinger Tells US Bishops to Reassert Their Authority</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Vatican's chief theologian urged American
bishops to be ``martyrs'' in defending Roman Catholic teaching and
to impose their authority on dissenters, officials said Thursday.
   Several of the 35 U.S. bishops attending a special conference
responded that compromise and dialogue are necessary in the American
church in areas other than major matters of faith.
   Cardinal Joseph Ratzinger said some bishops had let dissident
theologians usurp their authority, ``leading to a growing insecurity
and disorientation'' among the faithful.
   On some issues, ``it's necessary to risk being unpopular, because
of the truth,'' said Ratzinger, the head of the Congregation for the
Doctrine of the Faith, in remarks released Thursday. ``Those who
announce the Gospel must also be martyrs, in the most profound sense
of the word.''
   His address Wednesday night was seen as the keynote of the
four-day closed meeting between the Vatican and the bishops Pope
John Paul II summoned to discuss the state of American church, which
has 52 million members.
   John Paul, who is attending the conference, has criticized the
tendency of many U.S. Catholics to disregard church teaching on
birth control, divorce and some other matters.
   Ratzinger spoke of theological experts who, ``through the mass
media, bring into the public arena their often dissonant
contributions, to the point where their voices drown out those of
the bishops.''
   In recent years, he said, many bishops have felt pressure to be
managers rather than preachers.
   ``The bishops have fully adapted themselves to this regulative
model, little defending their magisterial authority'' over that of
theologians, he said.
   He criticized those who think the spirit of free inquiry, not
church teaching, should prevail on theological issues.
   Archbishop John Roach of Minneapolis-St. Paul and other American
prelates responded with a defense of compromise and debate on church
teaching.
   ``Archbishop Roach made it very clear that U.S. bishops will not
compromise on major matters of the faith,'' the Rev. John Lynch,
secretary of the U.S. National Conference of Bishops, said at a
briefing for journalists Thursday.
   ``In other matters,'' he added, ``sometimes the discussion and
the dialogue take more time than perhaps other people would like it
to take.''
   Lynch said the bishops told Vatican officials continuing the
dialogue with dissenters, ``which can sometimes be read as weakness,
but which in our American experience often leads to a good end,
should not be seen as weakness.''
   Not all the U.S. bishops disagreed with Ratzinger.
   Addressing problems faced by the American hierarchy, Cardinal
John O'Connor of New York mentioned ``leadership in certain colleges
and universities'' and said ``some bishops in the last 20 years have
seemed to lose faith, first in themselves as people, afterward in
their magisterial authority.''
   O'Connor, considered a doctrinal conservative, said other
problems stemmed from the effect of mass media on family and sexual
attitudes, ``the `abortion' mentality, racism, radical feminism,
loss in numbers of the teaching religious, dissident theologies and
ecclesiologies, materialism, etcetera.''
   The cardinal chided the Vatican for failing to prepare its clergy
and faithful for modern reforms, however, and said it had been too
slow in clarifying its policy on artificial birth control.
   A summary of his speech also was released Thursday.
   Other American bishops asked the Vatican for greater
``theological precision,'' possibly in the form of periodic letters
on moral issues.
   Ratzinger had some praise for the bishops, commending them for
pastoral letters that shed ``the light of faith'' on social issues.
The American prelates have produced controversial letters on the
U.S. economy and nuclear weapons.
   He also said, however, that bishops must resist a society in
which individual liberties were considered paramount and moral
values consigned to the private sphere.
   Those ideas were echoed in meetings Thursday between the Vatican
and the Americans on the role of priests and on the church's
pastoral mission.
   Cardinal Bernard Law of Boston said American priests were
``extraordinarily faithful'' but faced special challenges in U.S.
society. He mentioned individualism, moral relativism, the
``isolation of sexual pleasure as an end in itself'' and failure to
recognize differences between the sexes.
</TEXT>
