<FIRST>r i AM-Asia-Refugees     03-09 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Asia-Refugees,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>International Conference Aims to Solve Refugee Problem</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARI S. MANIAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An international conference on
Indochinese refugees ruled out repatriating asylum-seekers who are
deemed not to be fleeing political persecution, officials said
Thursday.
   Delegates from 30 nations ended their three-day meeting endorsing
a draft action plan for consideration at the International
Conference on Indochinese Refugees in Geneva in June.
   Chairman Majid Mohamed told a news conference the plan would help
``provide durable solutions to the Indochinese refugee problem.''
   The draft plan suggests Vietnam launch a campaign stressing the
risks and hardships of fleeing by boat and work to end illegal
departures by ``boat people.'' It also calls on Vietnam to make
legal departures easier.
   Malaysia, Indonesia, Thailand, the Philippines and other
countries in the region have agreed to provide only temporary asylum
for refugees. Western nations were urged to take in refugees left in
camps in Southeast Asia.
   Officials speaking on condition of anonymity said the conference
voted not to recommend a deadline by which asylum-seekers would be
screened to decide whether they qualified for resettlement in the
West.
   Officials said some Southeast Asian countries had asked the
conference to recommend forcible repatriation of boat people and
others fleeing their countries for reasons other than political
persecution.
   ``The rules are very clear ... whenever refugees are repatriated,
it has to be on a voluntary basis,'' said Jean Pierre Hocke, the
United Nations high commissioner for refugees.
   The officials said the Vietnamese delegation, led by Deputy
Foreign Minister Vu Khoan, had agreed at the conference to take back
anyone who wanted to return voluntarily.
   Western delegations present said they might take in additional
refugees, and step up financial aid to help implement the plan.
   So far, 150,000 people have emigrated legally from Vietnam under
the Orderly Departure Program.
   There are about 300,000 Indochinese refugees in Southeast Asia.
About 1.5 million have been resettled since the outflow began 10
years ago, more than 800,000 of them in the United States, officials
said.
   Majid said the plan would be sent to U.N. Secretary General
Javier Perez de Cuellar in New York for the Geneva conference June
13-14.
</TEXT>
