<FIRST>r i AM-Israel     03-09 0674</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0694</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinian Killed, 10 Wounded</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Palestinian teen-ager who threatened to slash
an Israeli soldier with a broken bottle was shot and killed in the
occupied Gaza Strip on Thursday, the army said.
   At least 10 Palestinians were shot and wounded in stone-throwing
clashes with Israeli troops in the occupied lands, Arab hospital
officials said. An army spokesman confirmed four wounded and said he
was checking other reports.
   The violence erupted as Palestinians shuttered their shops and
businesses in the second day of a general strike to mark 15 months
of rebellion against Israeli rule of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Israel captured the lands from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967
Middle East war.
   The death of Atef Jundieh, 16, of Gaza City raised to at least
393 the number of Palestinians killed since the uprising began.
Seventeen Israelis, including six soldiers, also have died.
   An army spokesman, who cannot be identified under military
regulations, said Jundieh threatened a soldier with a broken bottle.
   ``The soldier fired into the air and ordered the man to stop, but
he didn't,'' said the spokesman. ``The soldier then fired toward the
man, wounding him. He died several hours later.''
   On Wednesday night, Ibrahim Haled Hubal was electrocuted in the
West Bank village of Kharbat Al-Masbah, Arab reporters said. They
said Hubal was killed after troops ordered him to climb an
electricity pole to remove an outlawed Palestinian flag.
   An army official said no troops were in the village at the time
and that Hubal, 27, may have climbed the pole to hang a flag.
   Soldiers on Thursday began leaving their base in the Shati
refugee camp in Gaza City as part of the army's plans to rely less
on stationary units and more on mobile forces, army radio reported.
   Observers have seen fewer troops in the occupied lands in recent
days. The army declined to comment on whether it was reducing its
forces in the territories.
   The head of Israel's military government in the West Bank, Brig.
Gen. Shaike Erez, has begun a series of meetings with prominent
Palestinians to discuss ``political developments ... and problems of
everyday life,'' the Hebrew daily Yediot Ahronot reported Thursday.
   The reports of troop reductions and Erez' meetings came on the
eve of Foreign Minister Moshe Arens' departure Friday for a 10-day
visit to the United States, where he is to meet with President Bush.
   Arens is expected to seek U.S. support for peace efforts that
focus on a temporary solution for the occupied territories. U.S.
officials are expected to urge Israel to stop the violence caused by
its efforts to end the uprising, known as the intefadeh.
   Dr. Hatem Abu-Ghazaleh, a physician who met with Erez on
Thursday, told The Associated Press: ``I told him this is the
generation of the occupation who rose up against Israel, and the
intefadeh will never be ended until an international peace
conference is convened in which the PLO is a partner on equal
footing.''
   Israel says the Palestine Liberation Organization is a terrorist
group and refuses to negotiate with it.
   In other violence Thursday, a 33-year-old Palestinian man was
admitted to a Nablus hospital with head wounds his family said he
suffered in a beating by settlers from a nearby Jewish community.
   Arab reports said the incident led to a clash between Palestinian
villagers and settlers and that the army was called in to restore
order. The army spokesman said he was checking the report.
   Israel radio said 15 youths were arrested in Arab east Jerusalem
on suspicion of anti-Israeli activities.
   The Yediot Ahronot newspaper said military police were
investigating allegations that 15 soldiers from the elite Givati
brigade killed a 20-year-old Gaza Palestinian, Iyad Akal, who died
in custody in February 1988.
   The newspaper said Akal was handcuffed, beaten with a weapon and
kicked. Four other soldiers from the brigade are on trial for the
beating death in August of a Palestinian in the Gaza's Jabaliya
refugee camp.
</TEXT>
