<FIRST>r w AM-SecurityRisk     03-09 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Security Risk,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Blasts Bush Proposal to Restrict Clearances</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of a House subcommittee gave a scathing
appraisal Thursday of a proposed presidential order that would
tighten the government's security clearance process but do away with
employee protections against arbitrary penalties.
   Rep. Gerry Sikorski, D-Minn., shot a series of questions at Mary
Lawton, a Justice Department official who led an interagency group
that developed the proposal over the last five years. But Lawton
offered no justification for eliminating employees' due process
rights in the order.
   ``I don't understand why we're hurting these people,'' said
Sikorsky, chairman of the House civil service subcommittee. ``What's
wrong with these minimal due process rights? Why did you obliterate
them?''
   Lawton explained that her task force, which included
representatives from the FBI, the Central Intelligence Agency and
the departments of State, Defense, Energy and Treasury, was charged
by then-President Reagan to bring government-wide consistency to
background investigations of workers whose jobs require secret
security clearances.
   The federal Office of Personnel Management estimated in 1986 that
5 million military, civilian and federal contractor employees held
various levels of security clearances; numerous government studies
have found that number too high to be manageable. That overabundance
makes periodic re-reviews of security status impossible to keep
current and increases the likelihood that secret information will be
compromised.
   When the task force completed its draft presidential order,
however, it dropped from the regulations a series of due process
guarantees that had been in place since President Eisenhower
instituted them three decades ago.
   The proposed rule would do away with a worker's right to be
notified that he or she was being denied a security clearance, to be
told the reasons for the denial in writing, to be granted a chance
to reply and to be represented by a lawyer.
   ``What's wrong with the current process of giving a reason in
writing?'' Sikorski asked Lawton.
   ``Nothing's wrong,'' Lawton answered, adding, ``There is no
liberty or property interest in (security) clearance.''
   Denial of security clearance does not always mean a person's job
will be endangered, she said. ``Access (to classified information)
is not a right, it's a privilege.''
   ``I think it's indefensible,'' Sikorski replied, adding later:
   ``What you're saying is we want to flex our muscles. We don't
want any more court cases on access denial.''
   Rep. Thomas Ridge, R-Pa., asked Lawton, ``What public interest is
preserved by not explaining the reasons for denial?''
   ``Ninety-nine times out of 100, none,'' said Lawton. In the
remaining case, she said, the government must protect the secrecy of
the source of information on which the denial is based. But she
conceded that such information is protected even under the current
system.
   Following the hearing, Lawton told a reporter she was unable to
fully discuss or defend the draft order because it is still an
internal Executive Branch document and is being reviewed by the
Office of Management and Budget, with no decision yet made on its
final form.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
