<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     03-09 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Calls for Peace in Sri Lanka</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Ranasinghe Premadasa opened
the first session of the newly elected Parliament on Thursday, and
he called for warring rebel groups to put down arms and restore
peace on the island.
   But Sinhalese rebels, who called a strike to protest the session,
hurled bombs at state-run buses in southern and central Sri Lanka,
police said. The attacks killed one bus driver and injured two
passengers.
   The Eelam Revolutionary Organization of Students, a Tamil rebel
group that won 13 seats in the northeastern province, has vowed to
boycott the session until the government takes steps toward helping
the Tamil minority.
   Premadasa asked lawmakers to narrow their differences and unite
to help eliminate poverty.
   ``You are here because our people have convincingly and
effectively defeated the bullet and enthroned the ballot,'' said
Premadasa, referring to the bloody Feb. 15 general election. At
least 56 people died in balloting and another 1,000, including
several candidates, were killed in the five-week campaign.
   Premadasa's United National Party won 125 of the 225 seats in
Parliament.
   ``I would prefer to call the opposition an alternative party and
not the opposition,'' the president said.
   People's Liberation Front, the radical Sinhalese group trying to
topple the government, had called for a nationwide strike Thursday.
   But most shops and offices were open, government and business
leaders said.
   The Front opposes the government's efforts to end a rebellion by
radical Tamils, who are demanding a separate homeland in the north
and east provinces.
   Tamils, who are mostly Hindu, make up 18 percent of the island's
16 million people. They say they are denied jobs, education and
money for development projects by the Sinhalese, who comprise 75
percent of the population.
   More than 10,000 people have been killed since the fighting began
in 1983.
   In his address to Parliament, Premadasa said he had invited
militant Sinhalese and Tamils to put down their weapons, join the
democratic process and help negotiate a settlement.
   ``The patience of the people is not unlimited,'' said Premadasa,
who was elected to a six-year term in December.
   He has promised to eliminate poverty by giving 1.4 million poor
families $75 a month for two years, beginning next month. The
average annual income in Sri Lanka is $360.
</TEXT>
