<FIRST>r w AM-DrugTreatmentGrants     03-09 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Treatment Grants,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>$75 Million Program to Aid Waiting Addicts Announced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government on Thursday announced a
$75 million grant program to expand drug treatment services to help
get addicts off the streets faster and reduce the spread of AIDS.
   The funds are designed to help drug treatment centers reduce and
eliminate waiting lists, which in some cities are six months and
longer, said Frederick K. Goodwin, head of the Alcohol, Drug Abuse
and Mental Health Administration.
   ``Given the fact that approximately one-third of all new AIDS
cases are contracted through use of contaminated intravenous
needles, it is especially critical that the nation's ability to
provide treatment to drug abusers be expanded,'' he said.
   The money will go to public and private nonprofit organizations
that are providing out-patient or residential drug treatment
services where applicants have been waiting more than a month to be
admitted to the program.
   States as well as federally recognized Indian tribes can also
apply for several local drug treatment service providers, Frederick
said.
   The grants are intended to expand treatment services for abuse of
all types of drugs, including those injected intravenously.
   In addition to the new grant program, Frederick's agency, part of
the Department of Health and Human Services, is providing $518
million this fiscal year in block grants to states for substance
abuse treatment and prevention programs, a spokeswoman said.
</TEXT>
