<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 2151EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Spain-US     03-09 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spain-US,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parliament Ratifies New U.S.-Spanish Defense Accord</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament on Thursday ratified an
eight-year U.S.-Spanish agreement that calls for withdrawing 72 U.S.
F-16 fighter bombers by 1992 but permits continued use of three
military bases and nine communications posts by the Americans.
   Because the agreement is not a treaty, it does not have to be
ratified by the U.S. Senate.
   Foreign Minister Francisco Fernandez Ordonez defended the new
agreement against opposition claims it would undermine Spanish
sovereignty and permit entry of U.S. nuclear arms into Spain.
   ``It will guarantee full sovereignty,'' including the ability to
authorize or prohibit entry of U.S. warships in Spanish ports if it
is deemed necessary, he said.
   ``The agreement clears the way for a new relation based on mutual
trust and permits us to view with optimism the future of our
relations with our allied nation,'' Fernandez Ordonez told the 314
deputies in the Cortes, or parliament.
   Spain and the United States first signed a military cooperation
treaty establishing four U.S. bases in Spain in 1953, during the
height of the cold war under the authoritarian rule of Gen.
Francisco Franco.
   After Franco's death in 1975, King Juan Carlos led the country
through a peaceful transition to democracy.
   Of the 314 deputies present at the 4{-hour debate, 279 voted in
favor, 11 voted against it and 24 abstained.
   Spain renounced all economic and military aid in exchange for the
continued U.S. military use of two air bases and a key southern
naval station as well as nine communication posts.
   Chief negotiators Maximo Cajal of Spain and U.S. Ambassador
Reginald Bartholomew signed the agreement on Dec. 1, 1988, ending
the long and sometimes tense negotiations begun in July 1986.
</TEXT>
