<FIRST>r a AM-CruiseIllnesses     03-09 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cruise Illnesses,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Inspector: Cruise Ships Cover Up Illnesses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many cruise ships fail to report serious outbreaks
of illness at sea, an assistant U.S. surgeon general says.
   One ship in particular is ``consistently misstating'' its
incidence of illness, said Dr. Vernon N. Houk, director of the
Center for Environmental Health and Injury Control, a part of the
Centers for Disease Control in Atlanta.
   The information has been turned over to a federal attorney for
action, he added.
   A check of records found that ship officers have been reporting
no illnesses to federal sanitation inspectors when in fact they have
had as many as 240 people aboard suffering from diarrhea, Houk said
Wednesday.
   ``This has public health significance. We don't intend to
tolerate it,'' he said. Houk would not reveal the names of the ships
except to say they regularly sail from South Florida.
   Ships are supposed to report diarrheal illnesses among passengers
and crew by radio at least 24 hours before arriving in a U.S. port
in order to help inspectors trace the source of a disease before
passengers fan out across the country.
   The vast majority of the nation's cruise ships adhere to CDC
standards, Houk said.
   Houk, whose charges were made at a public meeting held by the CDC
to discuss health aboard cruise ships, said the problem was
uncovered when inspectors checked the logs of some ships against
their radio reports.
   Another speaker, John Reurs of the International Committee of
Passenger Lines, representing 19 cruise cd would cooperate with any
enforcement.
   Several other cruise officials at the meeting said they did not
know what ships had been falsifying health reports. ``We cooperate
fully with the CDC on all public health questions,'' said Tim
Gallagher of Carnival Cruise Lines.
   In the past, federal officials have publicized the names of ships
that have not cooperated with CDC requirements under the assumption
that bad publicity was more effective and cheaper than a drawn-out
court case.
</TEXT>
