<FIRST>r w AM-ConsumerCredit     03-09 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Consumer Credit,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consumer Debt Grows By $4.4 Billion in January</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans took out $4.4 billion more in credit
than they paid off in January as consumer debt grew at an annual
rate of 7.9 percent, the government reported Thursday.
   The Federal Reserve Board said the January increase followed a
revised increase of $4.3 billion in December and a gain of $4.7
billion in November.
   January's rise in the seasonally adjusted rate of credit growth
was up slightly from a 7.8 percent pace in December but below the
8.5 percent rate in November.
   The increase was held back by slower growth in auto loans and the
category of debt that includes credit cards, while loans for mobile
homes increased after falling sharply in December.
   Consumer spending is closely watched as a barometer of economic
health since it accounts for two-thirds of overall economic activity.
   In January, auto loans rose by $2.2 billion, a 9.2 percent annual
rate, following a slightly larger $2.4 billion increase during
December.
   Growth in the category of debt that includes credit cards also
was weaker in January, rising by $823 million or at a 5.3 percent
annual rate. That followed a December increase of $1.3 billion that
represented an 8.4 percent rate of growth.
   Mobile home debts, which had declined by $278 million in
December, rose by $82 million in January, a 3.8 percent pace of
growth.
   Bank and credit union loans not secured by real estate rose by
$1.2 billion in January, a 9 percent annual rate of growth, after
having risen $944 million or at a 6.9 percent pace in December.
   Overall, total consumer debt reached a seasonally adjusted $670.6
billion in January, up 8.4 percent from a year earlier.
</TEXT>
