<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 2140EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Venezuela     03-09 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Venezuela,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>Venezuela Restores Some Civil Liberties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANTHONY CAPLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Thursday restored
some civil liberties suspended last week during riots over price
increases but said the military would continue patrolling major
cities to prevent new violence.
   The move gives back freedom of the press, the right to gather and
protest in public, and the right to travel inside and out of the
country. It also ends the right of the military to enter homes and
detain suspects without warrants.
   The rights were suspended Feb. 28, one day after rioting broke
out over sharp increases in public transportation fares. The riots
evolved into nationwide demonstrations against a government
austerity program.
   A dust-to-dawn curfew was imposed Feb. 28 but was lifted Monday.
   The government said 256 people died in the violence, the worst in
Venezuela's 30 years of democracy. Unofficial reports put the toll
much higher, and human rights committees in Caracas say at least 30
people are missing.
   The director of the Central Information Office, Pastor Heydra,
said military personnel will continue to control major streets in
Caracas and other cities until ``the situation is totally
normalized.''
   President Carlos Andres Perez vowed to go ahead with his economic
program to meet loan conditions set by international financial
institutions. The country has a $33 billion foreign debt and needs
to obtain loans.
   Price controls were lifted in Venezuela this week, but most shops
were hesitant in implementing new prices.
   ``Maybe next week we'll set new prices,'' said Ernesto Rangel,
owner of a pizza shop. ``We don't want to shock people all at once.''
   Roman Catholic Church leaders urged the government to ensure the
poor alone don't shoulder the ``terrible burden of sacrifices'' of
the foreign debt.
   In a document published Thursday in newspapers, Caracas
Archbishop Jose Ali Lebrun and 20 other priests criticized ``the
widening gap between poor and rich'' in Venezuela and said ``the
luxury of the few has become an insult against the misery of the
masses.''
   ``We remind economic and political leaders that they have a duty
to give examples of austerity and honesty ... so that the terrible
burden of sacrifices the country must make because of its foreign
debt will not be borne by weak and poor sectors alone,'' they said.
   The daily newspaper El Nacional reported that Planning Minister
Miguel Rodriguez said the country plans to buy back a portion of its
foreign debt on secondary markets _ meaning from creditor banks _ at
a discount of up to 75 percent.
   Venezuela's debt, the fourth-largest in Latin America, is being
offered at 25 percent of its value by the banks, said El Nacional.
   Rodriguez did not specify the amount of debt Venezuela planned to
buy back but said the acquisition would be made with reserves of the
Venezuelan central bank, according to El Nacional.
   The effect of the purchase would be to reduce the amount of money
Venezuela would owe, but the amount it could purchase would depend
on how much is available in the central bank's operative reserves.
   The government said the operative reserves were $1.5 billion in
late February, but independent estimates have put the figure at $400
million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
