<FIRST>r i AM-Arafat     03-09 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arafat,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>PLO Leader Greeted as Head of State in India</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO leader Yasser Arafat arrived Thursday
for a two-day visit and was accorded a 21-gun salute as part of
India's acknowledgment of the PLO's declaration of an independent
Palestinian nation.
   The chairman of the Palestine Liberation Organization warmly
embraced Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi and, as part of his treatment
as a head of state, reviewed a military honor guard as a band played
the Palestinian and Indian anthems.
   In a brief conversation with reporters, Arafat said he
anticipated ``fruitful and friendly talks with my old friend,'' a
reference to Gandhi.
   Indian and Palestinian officials would not elaborate on the
nature of talks.
   Arafat came to India after a two-day visit to Pakistan, which
also accorded him head-of-state treatment. He is to leave for
Bangladesh on Friday.
   India was one of the first non-Arab nations to recognize the
PLO's declaration of an independent state last November.
   The declaration was primarily symbolic, since the PLO cannot
operate openly in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip,
where nearly 400 Palestinians and 17 Israelis have been killed in a
15-month uprising against Israeli rule.
   The PLO has sought peace negotiations with Israel, but the Jewish
state has maintained its position that Arafat's group is a terrorist
organization and has rebuffed the overtures.
   It was Arafat's fifth official visit to India but the first since
the PLO declaration.
   Although treated warmly on previous trips, this was the first
time he was given head-of-state treatment such as a 21-gun salute.
   Speaking to reporters as Arafat and his 15-man delegation headed
for their cars, Gandhi denied recent Indian newspaper reports that
India was preparing to upgrade its relations with Israel.
   ``We haven't done anything yet. There's nothing in the
pipeline,'' Gandhi said.
   India, which has long expressed solidarity with the Palestinian
cause, does not have diplomatic relations with Israel. The Israelis,
however, maintain a consulate in Bombay.
</TEXT>
