<FIRST>r i AM-Romania-Rights     03-09 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Romania-Rights,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungary Backs Effort on Human Rights Probe in Romania</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungary on Thursday backed a Western effort to
launch a United Nations inquiry into alleged human rights violations
in Warsaw Pact ally Romania.
   The U.N. Human Rights Commission voted 21-7 to adopt a
Swedish-led resolution backed by Hungary and six Western nations.
   The measure expresses concern at ``allegations of serious
violations of human rights and fundamental freedoms in Romania'' and
calls for the appointment of a special U.N. investigator.
   Six Third World nations and communist Cuba voted against the
resolution. Ten other Third World countries abstained, while the
Soviet Union and the three other Soviet Bloc countries in the
43-nation panel did not participate in the vote.
   Hungary and Romania have only observer status in the Human Rights
Commission and thus have no voting rights.
   It was the first time a Soviet Bloc country joined Western
nations in seeking such a move against a Warsaw Pact ally.
   Romania's chief delegate Gheorghe Dolgu called the resolution a
``brutal interference'' in his country's internal affairs and said
Romania regarded the measure as ``null and void.''
   ``We will never accept that models be imposed on us from
outside,'' Dolgu said.
   The resolution specifically refers to growing restrictions on
Romania's ethnic minorities, which include about 1.7 million
Hungarians.
   About 15,000 Romanians, most of them ethnic Hungarians, have fled
to Hungary in the past 12 months. The outflow increased after
authorities disclosed plans for ``rural consolidation'' that would
mean razing thousands of villages.
   Dolgu said Hungary masterminded the resolution and charged its
Warsaw Pact ally with pursuing revisionist intentions aimed at
``changing frontiers established by peace treaties.''
   Romanians, he said, are familiar with such intentions. It was a
reference to a wartime deal between Nazi Germany and Hungary under
which Transylvania, the Romanian region that includes most of the
Hungarian minority, became part of Hungary. Romania, also an ally of
the Nazis' until 1944, recovered Transylvania after the war.
   ``It is under the pretext of the alleged right to protect certain
minorities that we had to go through direct aggression and
dismemberment,'' Dolgu said. ``The resolution aims once again at
arousing nationalistic and chauvinist expressions and to destabilize
Romania.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
