<FIRST>r w AM-LibyanPlant     03-09 0706</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Libyan Plant,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan Tells U.S. That Aid to Metal Plant in Libya Stopped Last Summer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci and
the State Department joined Thursday in asserting there was no
evidence that Japanese firms were directly involved in a chemical
weapons plant in Libya.
   ``Not that I know,'' Carlucci told reporters. ``When I was in the
government we had no indication whatsoever of any such diversion.''
   A State Department official said, meanwhile: ``We have no
information indicating Japanese firms were directly involved in the
Libyan chemical weapons plant itself.''
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said Japanese
firms were involved in a nearby metal fabrications facility, and
that Japan Steel Works was the prime contractor.
   However, the official said, ``the Japanese government has
informed us that as of last summer Japanese firms ceased all
involvement with that facility.''
   Denials were also issued in Tokyo by the Japanese government and
by Mitsubishi Heavy Industries, which according to a published
report had a team of 50 technicians and engineers at the plant
complex in the desert south of Libya.
   The company is involved in a proposed joint venture with the
United States to build a jet fighter, the FSX. The deal was
negotiated during the Reagan administration, in which Carlucci was
defense secretary, and is now under review by the Bush
administration.
   Carlucci said the ``memorandum of understanding'' that would
govern the program would be signed with the Japanese government.
   ``We have absolutely no instance of any compromise of technology
by the Japanese government,'' he said. ``And the Japanese government
will be accountable.''
   Still, the report on alleged involvement by Mitsubishi in Libya
raised new concerns in Congress about the proposed joint airplane
venture. A report by the defense and commerce departments to
President Bush was due on Friday.
   The State Department official said an investigation by the
Japanese government disclosed several Japanese firms had supplied
equipment to Japan Steel Works as subcontractors and that Japanese
firms exported equipment to the metal fabrication facility through
third countries.
   But, the official said, the Japanese government said all such
involvement with the facility ended last summer.
   ``Our consultation with the Japanese government concerning the
Libyan chemical weapons program has been positive and
constructive,'' the official said.
   Libya, meanwhile, has denied it was trying to develop chemical
weapons and said the plant was engaged in the manufacture of
pharmaceuticals.
   On Capitol Hill, there were calls for Congress to ban from
American markets products made by foreign firms found to have helped
build the suspected chemical weapons plant, and for Bush to abandon
the proposed joint airplane venture.
   In Japan, Foreign Ministry spokesman Taizo Watanabe said Thursday
that ``I can now confirm that Mitsubishi Heavy Industries has never
been engaged in the export of equipment or dispatch of engineers as
reported in The Detroit News.'' Mitsubishi also denied the reports.
   The Detroit newspaper on Wednesday had quoted unidentified
congressional and Defense Department sources as saying they were
told of Mitsubishi's alleged participation in the Libyan project by
intelligence sources in Washington.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said that ``we continue to
investigate this matter.'' He added that ``the Japanese government
has given us assurances that there is no intention of any Japanese
involvement with the Libyan project and has denied emphatically any
involvement by Mitsubishi Heavy Industries' technicians or engineers
in the Libyan chemical project.''
   Rep. John Bryant, D-Texas, among those seeking action by Congress
and the president, said that the nation ``must awaken to the fact
that we are naive to expect the Japanese to do anything other than
what is in their economic interests.''
   Rep. Duncan Hunter, R-Calif., said companies involved in the
Libyan plant have ``deliberately sold out the interests of the West
in helping (Libyan leader Moammar) Gadhafi and they deserve a
corporate life sentence.
   ``My bill would require the CIA to supply the names of the
companies that have participated in the construction of the Libyan
gas and bomb facilities. ... They should not have access to our
markets if they work to make chemical weapons that may one day be
used by terrorists to gas American or Israeli citizens,'' Hunter
said.
</TEXT>
