<FIRST>r w AM-HijackingTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0622 03-09 0728</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hijacking Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0622,760</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDS: Top 9 grafs new with closing prosecution argument, picks up
graf xxx pvs; deletes to tighten and conform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal prosecutors urged the jury in the Fawaz
Younis sky piracy trial to find the defendant guilty and to reject
his claim that he led the hijacking of a plane from Beirut in 1985
on orders from the Lebanese militia to which he belonged.
   Hijacking, said prosecutor Karen Morrissette, ``is a violation of
international law.''
   ``The defendant cannot hijack an airplane, then come into a
courtroom in this country and say, `Well, someone told me to do it.'
And it's alright,'' she said.
   The hijackers were trying to deliver a political message, the
prosecutor told the jury.
   ``You can send a message to that hijacker,'' she said.
   Younis, 30, has pleaded innocent in the case, considered a test
of a 1984 statute asserting ``long-arm'' jurisdiction for the United
States over the taking of American hostages abroad.
   The prosecution suffered a blow earlier in the day as U.S.
District Judge Aubrey E. Robinson Jr. blocked testimony from a
government lawyer seeking to rebut the defendant's claim he was just
following military orders in hijacking a plane from Beirut in 1985.
   With the jury out of the room, W. Hays Parks, chief of the
International Affairs Division for the U.S. Army's advocate general,
argued that Younis' defense did not meet the standards of
international or military law.
   Unable to introduce Parks' testimony as evidence, federal
prosecutors gave the Robinson proposed instructions for the jury,
and Morrissette indicated in her closing argument that the judge had
accepted the major points that Parks sought to present.
   Seeking to appear for the government as an expert witness, Parks
said that Lebanon's Amal militia, to which Younis belonged, was not
a legitimate military organization because its combatants did not
wear uniforms and attacked civilians.
   Parks, who heard Younis testify earlier this week, said that the
defendant ought to have known that hijacking a plane with civilians
aboard was a violation of international law.
   ``If a soldier receives an illegal order, he has not only a right
but a duty to disobey that order,'' said Parks, who is a colonel in
the Marine Corps Reserves.
   After listening to Parks, Robinson said ``I respect the expertise
of Colonel Parks, but he will not testify before the jury.''
   Robinson said that he, not Parks, would instruct the jury on the
law in the case, and anticipated an appeal from government lawyers
if Younis is acquitted on the defense of following a superior's
order.
   ``I may well be wrong,'' he said. ``I have been wrong before.''
   ``If it gets to the Supreme Court, it will get there,'' said
Robinson.
   Government attorneys said that the ruling was not unexpected, and
gave Robinson a proposed written jury instruction containing Park's
arguments.
   The path taken by the defense, arguing that Younis was just
following orders, appeared to cause consternation among officials
from the justice and defense departments and intelligence agencies
who have been attending the trial.
   Defense counsel Francis D. Carter put his client on the stand for
two days.
   Younis testified Wednesday that the Lebanese Amal militia was in
a ``state of war'' when its military commander, Aqil Hamiyya,
ordered him to hijack the plane.
   ``Hijacking a plane is a wartime operation,'' said Younis.
   Younis said he was ``not proud'' of his actions. ``But I was
carrying out an order given to me by my military commander. I was
trying to serve my country in the best way I knew how,'' he said.
``I believe in actions that serve my people and my country.''
   Prosecutors have produced five witnesses who identified Younis as
the man who led four other heavily armed men aboard Royal Jordanian
Airlines Flight 402 in Beirut on June 11, 1985.
   Younis was arrested on Sept. 13, 1987, by FBI agents who lured
him aboard a yacht in international waters in the Mediterranean Sea.
   The defense counsel has argued that FBI agents coerced a
confession out of Younis during four days aboard a Navy munitions
ship while he was suffering from seasickness and two broken wrists.
The hairline fractures were discovered after Younis was flown to the
United States and arraigned, and an appeals court has ruled that the
confession was valid.
</TEXT>
