<DOCNO> AP890309-0138 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 2218EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Budget     03-09 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Committee Chairman Says Administration Open to Taxes _ Later</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the Senate Budget Committee
predicted Thursday that in new budget talks the Bush administration
would agree to only ``a minimalist approach'' to deficit reduction
this year _ but would later open the door for tax increases.
   Sen. James Sasser, at a press breakfast hours before the start of
talks on the fiscal 1990 budget, reasserted his position that tax
increases were needed to reduce the deficit.
   And he said that President Bush's budget director, Richard
Darman, privately agreed _ an assertion that Darman said was untrue.
   ``Privately, Darman believes we're going to have to have revenues
to run this government,'' said Sasser, D-Tenn.
   Darman is ``a very bright guy; he knows the score ... that if
you're going to have any meaningful reduction in the deficit in the
short term, you're going to need some additional revenues,'' Sasser
said.
   Darman had told him privately, he said, ``at some juncture, he
wouldn't be averse to taking new revenues to the president, but not
this year.''
   In the meantime, Sasser predicted the administration would insist
on ``a minimalist approach'' to the fiscal 1990 budget, which under
the Gramm-Rudman law is supposed to reduce the deficit to $100
billion or less.
   ``They're going to try to meet these targets at the front end,
with overly optimistic economic assumptions and pray that the
markets will swallow it,'' he said.
   Meeting the more stringent future targets of the law, which calls
for a balanced budget by fiscal 1993, would be left for next year,
he said. And Congress would in the end go along with putting things
off, he predicted.
   ``What else can we do? If we pass new revenues, the president
will veto them and give us a lot of political heat.''
   At a session with reporters later in the day, Darman disagreed
with how Sasser characterized his position.
   ``I can't imagine he would have said that,'' Darman said. Asked
whether he was more favorable to a tax increase than his public
statements have indicated, Darman said, ``Maybe that's what he would
like to believe.''
   He said the White House and congressional leaders have already
discussed sharing the blame if stringent and unpopular actions
become necessary in the deficit-reduction package.
   Darman said that he and Bush continued to oppose any new taxes,
although he conceded that when talks got down to fine detail _
probably not in the two-week round of discussions beginning Thursday
_ there might be some small flexibility.
   As an example of what the administration might accept, he said a
Customs Service fee was scheduled to decline, and Congress might
want to keep it instead of losing $200 million in revenue.
   But in terms of accepting a major tax boost, he said, ``I do not
foresee the circumstance where we will be in that position.''
   Darman also said he found good news in a Congressional Budget
Office report released Thursday, which projected the deficit next
year at $131 billion, or $40 billion higher than White House
estimates.
   Most of the difference was because of a $22 billion disagreement
over how to account in the budget for Bush's plan to bail out the
savings and loan system. If that dispute were put aside, the deficit
would still be below the threshold at which the Gramm-Rudman law
would require automatic spending cuts.
</TEXT>
