<DOCNO> AP890309-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 1637EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-ThirdWorldDebt Bjt   03-09 0828</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Third World Debt, Bjt,780</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House Putting Together New Approach</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration, spurred by the bloody
riots in Venezuela, is putting together a new approach to the heavy
debt burden being carried by Third World countries, a problem that
Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady has called ``perhaps the most
difficult'' facing the new administration.
   The new plan, or at least some details of what it will contain,
could be revealed as early as Friday, when Brady is scheduled to
address a private conference on Third World debt at the State
Department.
   After winning the election, President Bush said he favored taking
a ``whole new look'' at U.S. policy on Third World debt and he
ordered Brady to launch a review at the Treasury Department.
   Bush's comments have raised hopes that the new administration
will respond favorably to pleas from debtor countries that they face
economic and political chaos without major debt relief.
   Those pleas gained new urgency last week when more than 300
people died in riots in Venezuela sparked by government imposition
of tough austerity measures to please creditors.
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Thursday that a
White House review of proposals being generated by the Treasury
Department had been underway for several days and was continuing.
   Other officials indicated that Brady would likely begin outlining
the new approach at Friday's conference and would follow the speech
with a more detailed report to Congress in the coming weeks.
   According to sources who have been involved in discussions with
Treasury Department officials, the administration plan will
encourage commercial banks to voluntarily forgive a portion of the
Third World debt they hold.
   To encourage this debt reduction, the administration is
considering a variety of enticements, including some type of loan
guarantees on the reduced level of debt that would still be held by
the banks.
   Also under consideration are a proposal to increase the size of
tax deductions banks could take for losses on Latin loans and a
proposal to lower the amount of money banks are forced to hold in
reserve to cover loan losses.
   But it is the loan guarantees that are attracting the most
attention. These guarantees might take the form of assurances that
the 151-nation World Bank or its sister institution, the
International Monetary Fund, would make debt or interest payments if
a debtor country defaulted.
   A Bush administration strategy emphasizing debt forgiveness, even
on a limited and voluntary basis, would mark a major change from the
Reagan administration's approach, which became known as the Baker
plan after then-Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III.
   Baker's strategy emphasized new lending on the part of banks, the
IMF and the World Bank to countries that agreed to adopt economic
reforms. The idea was that the new money would spur the debtor
countries' economies, making them more creditworthy.
   In reality under the Baker plan, commercial banks lent relatively
little in new funds and the debtor countries wound up paying out far
more in interest and principal than they were receiving in new
financing.
   The Morgan Guaranty Trust Co. estimates that the foreign debt of
the 15 principal borrowers, including 10 Latin American countries,
rose to $505 billion last year, with interest the countries had to
pay totalling $42 billion.
   Baker, who is now secretary of state, did lend support to some
limited debt-reduction measures, but he rejected a variety of more
ambitious plans offered by such people as Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J.,
and James Robinson III, the chairman of the American Express Co.
   The proposals under review by the Bush administration were
praised Thursday by economists as a more realistic approach to the
debt problem.
   ``The reality of the situation is that something different has to
be done. The idea of throwing good money after bad just hasn't
worked,'' said Cynthia Latta, a financial economist with Data
Resources Inc. ``It has just left them deeper in debt and is leading
to great political instability in the debtor countries.''
   Brady, referring to the administration review last week, said
that the urgency of the problem had not been lost on the new
administration.
   ``Perhaps the most difficult of the major issues facing us at the
outset of the Bush administration is the problem of Third World
debt,'' Brady said in a speech to the American Bankers Association.
``Unlike the federal budget deficit or even the savings and loan
industry crisis, this is not a problem that we in the U.S. have the
power or the resources to solve by ourselves.''
   The debt owed by all Third World countries totaled $1.32 trillion
at the end of 1988, up from $800 billion in 1982, the year the debt
crisis first erupted with the announcement by Mexico that it could
not meet its obligations.
   The largest debtor country is Brazil, with $110 billion owed,
followed by Mexico with $107 billion owed. Other big debtors are
Argentina, $50 billion, and Venezuela, $33 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
