<DOCNO> AP890309-0141 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 2141EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Salvador-Massacre     03-09 0704</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-Massacre,0727</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sources: Officer to be Indicted for Rights Abuse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SEBASTIAN, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three army officers have been
arrested in the massacre of 10 peasants, and at least one will be
indicted, judiciary and government sources said Thursday.
   An indictment would mark an unprecedented effort to apply
civilian rule to the military, said the sources, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Another officer _ a colonel and commander of an army brigade _
has been removed from his command because of his alleged link to the
killings, they said.
   The arrests followed strong pressure from the United States to
investigate civilian killings, including the peasant massacre Sept.
21 in the hamlet of San Francisco, four miles south of San Sebastian.
   ``What we all want to avoid is punishing only the scapegoats,''
Judge Alcides Guandique said in an interview. Guandique will
announce this month who will be tried by a jury in the case.
   Sources said at least one of the three officers arrested will be
among those indicted.
   The United Nations, local and international human rights groups
and churches have blamed government security forces for the torture
and murder of thousands of leftists during the 9-year-old war
guerrillas have waged against the government.
   Eight soldiers have been convicted, six for killing U.S.
citizens. No officer has ever been tried, and the army has denied
any involvement in death squad killings.
   According to witnesses and relatives, the peasant massacre
occurred when soldiers from the Jiboa battalion marched into San
Francisco, home to about 15 families. They detained most of the
residents in a one-room school and accused them of collaborating
with guerrillas, witnesses and relatives said.
   Working from a list, the troops selected seven men and three
women, took them to a nearby ravine and killed them with explosives
and rifle fire, according to documents and witness accounts.
   The army at first said the dead were guerrillas killed in an army
ambush. It later said the victims were detainees killed in a
guerrilla ambush while being marched away.
   Vice President Dan Quayle visited El Salvador last month and told
the high command that El Salvador's tradition of military immunity
for human rights abuses must end, and that the San Francisco killers
must be punished.
   The United States provides El Salvador, a country of about 5
million, with about $1.5 million a day in economic and military aid.
   ``What do we have to say? No convicted officer, no more aid?
That's too blunt. But Quayle was unambiguously talking about
continued aid,'' said a high U.S. official on condition of anonymity.
   The army version of the peasant killings is about to change,
according to government and judiciary officials with access to
preliminary conclusions of an army tribunal investigating the
slayings simultaneously with Guandique's inquiry.
   ``Remove from your head any doubt that they might have been
killed by anyone but the soldiers,'' said a government official.
   Four Jiboa soldiers _ a corporal and three privates _ were
charged with murder by Guandique's predecessor, but Guandique said
there is no indication the four did the killing.
   ``They are kind of scapegoats, unlucky enough to have been
recognized,'' the judge said. He said he has taken sworn testimony
from about 20 soldiers present the day of the killings.
   The three arrested officers were in San Francisco on Sept. 21,
according to military sources and Carlos Castellon, a lawyer for one
of the officers, Lt. Arnoldo Vasquez.
   Castellon and the sources identified the other officers as
Intelligence Maj. Mauricio Beltran and Lt. Manuel Galvez.
   Col. Jose Chavez Caceres, commander of the 5th Army Brigade and
the Jiboa battalion, has been removed from his post but is not
directly implicated in the massacre, military sources said.
   ``His responsibility appears to be limited to believing his
subordinates,'' said one source.
   1988 was the first year in five that number of civilian killings
rose from the previous year. The Roman Catholic Church's legal aid
office says 261 people were killed last year, 67 percent more than
in 1987.
   The church blamed security forces for 92 of the killings and
death squads for 60. Guerrillas fighting the government were blamed
for 44 summary executions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
