<FIRST>r w AM-Obit-Rumbaugh 630   03-09 0620</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Rumbaugh, 630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walter Reed Chief Dies After Parachute Accident</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A two-star Army general who commanded the
Walter Reed Army Medical Center in Washington died earlier this week
after sustaining injuries in a parachute accident in Honduras, the
Pentagon said Thursday.
   Maj. Gen. James H. Rumbaugh, 49, was being evacuated by airplane
from the Soto Cano Air Base outside Comayugua, Honduras, on
Wednesday night when he suffered an apparent heart attack, the
Pentagon said in a prepared statement.
   A day earlier, on Tuesday, Rambaugh suffered apparent abdominal
injuries while making a parachute jump from a helicopter, officials
said. The general was in Honduras participating in the annual Ahuas
Tara 89 exercise with a forward surgical deployment team, the
Pentagon added.
   ``Maj. Gen. Rumbaugh, an experienced parachutist, had
participated in a parachute jump with members of the 44th Medical
Brigade at about 7:30 a.m. on March 7,'' the Pentagon said in a
prepared statement.
   ``He went about his normal duties immediately after the jump.
Several hours later he sought medical attention for abdominal
pains.''
   According to defense sources, who insisted on anonymity,
physicians in Honduras discovered bleeding around Rumbaugh's
abdominal wall and recommended he be flown to the Brooke Army
Medical Center.
   ``Preliminary information indicates that the general suffered
cardiac arrest on the airplane and physicians were unable to
resuscitate him,'' the Pentagon said in its statement.
   ``An autopsy will be performed at Walter Reed to determine the
cause of death.''
   One source said the plane carrying Rumbaugh was diverted to
Cancun, Mexico, when the two-star general failed to respond to
cardiopulmonary resuscitation. The plane landed in Cancun around 8
p.m. Wednesday, but Rumbaugh was pronounced dead a few minutes
later, the official said.
   His body was then flown on to Kelly Air Force Base in San Antonio
Wednesday night.
   ``Gen. Rumbaugh ... was a 24-year Army veteran whose assignments
included one as surgeon for the XVIII Airborne Corps at Fort Bragg,
N.C., the home of the 82nd Airborne Division,'' the Pentagon said.
   ``The general was jumping (in Honduras) as part of his regional
oversight responsibilities as commander of Walter Reed.''
   The Pentagon declined to elaborate. But several Pentagon
officials said it was unusual for a two-star general to participate
in parachute jumps and that Rumbaugh would have been under no
requirement to perform such jumps.
   Rumbaugh took command of the Army's most prestigious hospital
center last August. A native of Washington, Pa., Rumbaugh earned a
degree in history from Thiel College and then earned his medical
degree from the Thomas Jefferson University School of Medicine in
Philadelphia.
   He joined the Army in June 1963 while completing his studies at
Thomas Jefferson and then served his internship and a residency in
psychiatry at Walter Reed.
   Rumbaugh spent his first decade in the Army working in a variety
of psychiatry posts, including a tour in Vietnam with the 1st
Cavalry Division. He later worked as an alcohol and drug control
officer before taking command of the medical organization serving
the XVIII Airborne Corps at Fort Bragg.
   Rumbaugh served from June 1985 to July 1986 as the deputy
commander at Walter Reed, then two years as the director of
professional services for the Army surgeon general before assuming
command of Walter Reed.
   Rumbaugh earned his first star as a brigadier general in
September 1986 and his second last October. His decorations included
the Legion of Merit, the Bronze Star, the Meritorious Service Medal
with Oak Leaf Cluster, the Army Commendation Medal and the Expert
Field Medical Badge.
   He is survived by his wife, Norma Jean, and four children _ John,
Kate, Nell and James. The Pentagon said funeral arrangements had not
been completed.
</TEXT>
