<FIRST>r w AM-TVDumping     03-09 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-TV Dumping,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zenith Welcomes Government Plan to Monitor TV Imports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zenith Electronics Corp. on Thursday welcomed
the government's decision to monitor television imports from Mexico
and Malaysia, saying the action could help curb the dumping of
imported TVs at less than fair-market value.
   Acting at Zenith's request, the Commerce Department last week
agreed to monitor imports of complete and incomplete color
televisions from the two countries.
   Zenith President and Chairman Jerry K. Pearlman said the
monitoring program should help reduce schemes in which manufacturers
in the Far East who have been found guilty of dumping then evade
anti-dumping penalties by establishing assembly operations in other
countries, such as Mexico and Malaysia.
   The monitoring program, which will last up to a year, will
determine whether there has been evidence of dumping from the two
countries sufficient to warrant a full-scale anti-dumping
investigation.
   Pearlman said color TV imports from Mexico and Malaysia are
almost as large as those from Japan, Korea and Taiwan combined.
   ``Mexico has become the principal source of color TVs in the U.S.
and imports from Malaysia have now surpassed those from Japan,'' he
said.
   Zenith in December had asked the government to monitor imports
from Malaysia, Mexico, Singapore, Hong Kong, China, Thailand and the
Philippines.
   The department said it decided to monitor imports from Mexico and
Malaysia ``because it has reason to believe or suspect that an
extraordinary pattern of persistent, injurious dumping exists and is
causing a serious commercial problem for the domestic TV industry.''
   The agency said the request to monitor imports from the other
countries did not ``meet the statutory threshold for establishing a
monitoring program.''
   Anti-dumping orders now in place cover TVs from Japan, Korea and
Taiwan, and color picture tubes from Japan, Korea, Canada and
Singapore, Zenith said.
</TEXT>
