<FIRST>r w AM-Elderly-Homes     03-09 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Elderly-Homes,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel Looks At Rest Home Abuse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House-Senate committee exploring rest home
abuses viewed color slides of neglected residents Thursday, and
heard gripping testimony from a ``survivor'' of a California home in
which seven bodies were found buried in the yard.
   Rep. Claude Pepper, D-Fla., released a report attributing
problems at the homes in part to neglect by states and the decision
about 25 years ago to move away from putting mentally ill persons
into institutions.
   Pepper and the joint panel of the House and Senate aging
committees focused their attention on so-called ``board and care
homes.''
   In different states, the homes are called everything from rest
homes, group or personal care homes, to domiciliaries. They provide
rooms, meals and help with daily routines _ but not regular medical
care such as provided by nursing homes.
   John Sharp, 64, testified that he was a ``survivor'' of the
unlicensed Sacramento, Calif., home run by Dorothy Puente. Seven
bodies were found buried in Puente's yard, and she was charged last
November with murder.
   ``I often wonder why I was spared a terrible fate at the Puente
home,'' Sharp said.
   He recalled seeing her going through residents' mail and
wondering why residents seemed to be disappearing from the home.
   He said a pivotal moment came when he refused to allow her to
begin receiving and cashing his government checks.
   ``I told her that those checks were my lifeline and I couldn't
trust them to anyone but myself. I didn't turn over my Social
Security checks to her and, looking back, that's probably what saved
my life,'' he said.
   The report released by Pepper was prepared by the House Select
Committee on Aging's health subcommittee, of which he is chairman.
Many of the report's conclusions echoed those of a similar study
released Wednesday night by the General Accounting Office.
   Pepper's report termed board and care homes ``a national
tragedy.''
   ``We found that most of the one million elderly, disabled and
mentally ill persons who reside in board and care homes are being
warehoused in understaffed, underegulated, shoddy and unsafe
facilities,'' Pepper said.
   The report identified many board and care residents as former
state mental hospital inhabitants who were released in the 1960s as
part of a push to place such patients in community settings.
   The panel also heard a scratchy, secretly-recorded tape of an
Alabama board and care operator slapping a resident, and describing
how she had shot a woman for pulling her wig off.
   The unidentified operator was described by Jefferson County,
Ala., ombudsman Julie Oetting at the hearing as a ``convicted
murderer.''
   Earlier, Pepper, 88, narrated slides of residents bound to
wheelchairs and lying on floors, and homes without proper fire
safety equipment. In Maryland, he said, an owner continued to house
11 residents in a burnt-out home without adequate fire safety
equipment.
   Board and care homes typically serve many residents who rely on
Supplemental Security Income to pay the bills.
   New Jersey attorney David Lazarus and Rep. James Florio, D-N.J.,
used the analogy of a dog in a kennel to describe the lack of public
commitment to rest home residents.
   ``On average, it costs $11 per day to board a 70-pound dog in New
Jersey. Astonishingly, New Jersey board and care residents dependent
upon SSI receive a low of $11.30 to a high of just under $16 for
their lodging, meals, and care in a board and care home,'' Florio
said.
   ``And in states that do not supplement the federal SSI amount,
the daily rates are even lower,'' he said.
   Barbara Jameson of the National Association of Residential Care
Facilities said in an interview that she hoped the hearing would not
convey the impression that the mistreatment was widespread.
   ``I really don't believe there is widespread abuse,'' she said.
``I think there is far more abuse in biological families,
unfortunately, than in licensed care homes.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890309-0147 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 1717EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Watkins-SwearingIn     03-09 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Watkins-Swearing In,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Vows Quick Start On Long-Term Cleanup Of Nuclear Waste</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Thursday vowed to ``waste no
time'' starting a massive cleanup of tons of radioactive waste and
widespread soil contamination from the Energy Department's 12-state
nuclear weapons complex.
   At a swearing-in ceremony for Energy Secretary James D. Watkins,
the president said the department's top priority is modernizing the
weapons plants, which have badly deteriorated and, in some cases,
been forced to shut down.
   ``This task is critical,'' Bush told an audience of several
hundred Energy Department employees. He added that the environmental
cleanup also was important.
   ``These problems developed over time and they'll be fully solved
only over time, but we'll waste no time getting started on fixing
these problems,'' Bush said.
   The weapons complex _ including nuclear reactors, processing,
manufacturing and assembly plants and laboratories _ build and test
the Pentagon's nuclear arsenal, which is a vital element in the
nation's defense strategy.
   The department in the waning days of the Reagan administration
issued a broad-brush plan for spending $81 billion over the next 21
years to modernize and begin cleaning up the weapons complex. Bush
has not explicitly endorsed the plan.
   Watkins said his main goal was to instill a new, more responsible
attitude in Energy Department workers that would lead to sounder
practices in the nuclear field.
   ``Nuclear power demands no less than the best from all who
control it,'' he said. ``This, then, is exactly what I ask of my
department: a commitment to excellence.
   ``So I ask you to help me forge in the workplace a culture that
rejects the mediocre and substandard.''
   Watkins was confirmed by the Senate last week and has moved
quickly to begin developing a comprehensive strategy for dealing
with the nuclear weapons problem. His department, however, is still
lacking Bush appointees to key positions.
   The White House announced Thursday that Bush intends to nominate
John C. Tuck to be under secretary of energy, the No. 3 job,
replacing Donna R. Fitzpatrick. Tuck served in several posts in the
Reagan administration, including director of the chief of staff's
office during the administration's final six months.
   Bush last month said he planned to nominate former Rep. Henson
Moore of Louisiana as deputy energy secretary, the No. 2 position,
but no confirmation hearing has been set because the nomination has
not been forwarded to the Senate Energy and Natural Resources
Committee, committee staffer Nancy Blush said Thursday.
   Watkins has circulated a memo to department employees around the
country spelling out some of his priorities, including developing
five-year objectives for waste cleanup at each of the nuclear
weapons sites, department spokeswoman Christina Sankey said.
   Other priorities mentioned in the memo include legislation to
remove the remaining price controls on natural gas; moving ahead
with the $5.9 billion superconducting super collider project to
study the nature of matter and energy; pushing legislation to allow
oil exploration on the coastal plain of the Arctic National Wildlife
Refuge in Alaska, and developing an integrated national energy
policy.
   Watkins also stressed a need to restart the reactors at Savannah
River, near Aiken, S.C., that produce a perishable gas needed to
manufacture nuclear warheads. The three reactors there have been
shut down since last spring for safety.
   Watkins said in the memo that he intended to have a more
``all-inclusive set of objectives'' within three months.
</TEXT>
