<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 2120EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-S&amp;Ls     03-09 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Doesn't Want Buyers' Tax Breaks Continued</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration said Thursday it
opposes the continuation of preferential tax breaks that federal
regulators have been using to attract buyers for insolvent savings
and loan associations.
   ``Unequivably, we do not favor the continuation of favorable tax
treatment,'' White House Budget Director Richard Darman told the
Senate Finance Committee.
   Darman said the administration assumes that the scheduled January
elimination will proceed of a tax break allowing purchasers of
insolvent S&amp;Ls to exclude from taxable income 50 percent of whatever
aid they get from federal insurors for paying off depositors in the
acquired institutions.
   Meanwhile, the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. on Thursday took
control of an additional 45 failed savings and loans, with $13.6
billion in assets, in eight states.
   That brings to 118 in 24 states the total number of institutions
the agency has taken control of since Bush announced his S&amp;L rescue
package in early February.
   Until this year, purchasers of insolvent S&amp;Ls could avoid paying
taxes on 100 percent of whatever they received from the FSLIC, the
agency that insured S&amp;L depositors against losses up to $100,000 in
each account, much as the FDIC insures commercial bank depositors
against losses.
   Before the 100 percent FSLIC aid exclusion was cut in half Jan.
1, 1989, S&amp;L regulators used it in December it as a lure in
attracting buyers for 75 insolvent thrift institutions.
   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board, which until February also ran
the insurance fund as well as regulating S&amp;Ls, estimated the tax
revenue losses to the Treasury from the December action at $4
billion.
   But Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill. and chairman of the House Ways
and Means Committee, said Thursday that the tax benefits in the
December resolutions could be more than $7 billion.
   Another tax incentive for S&amp;Ls scheduled to expire at the end of
1989 allows net operating losses of an insolvent S&amp;L to be
transferred to its new owner, who can use them to reduce taxes that
would otherwise be owed.
   Both the General Accounting Office and the Congressional Budget
Office have recommended against continuing the tax breaks.
   FDIC Chairman William Seidman in his new role in the S&amp;L crisis
has called for continuing the tax breaks beyond this year.
   He told Congress last month that the tax breaks would reduce the
impact of the S&amp;L bailout to the federal budget and promised to use
them ``to minimize the government's total cost.''
   Sen. David Durenberger, R-Minn., and Rep. Pete Stark, D-Calif.,
introduced bills Wednesday to repeal the tax breaks immediately upon
passage of Bush's S&amp;L bailout proposal instead of waiting until
January.
   In other developments:
   _Congressional Budget Office Director Robert D. Reischauer told
the Senate Appropriations Committee that Bush's fiscal 1990 deficit
will total $131 billion rather than the administration's projected
$91.1 billion. About $22 billion of the $40 billion difference is
attributable to different accounting treatment of the S&amp;L rescue, he
said.
   _Rep. Thomas R. Carper, D-Del., said he and other members of the
House Banking Committee are looking into whether the stock of the
regional Federal Home Loan Banks should be opened up to public
ownership. The stock is currently owned only by S&amp;Ls, which could
benefit if the price of the stock rose after public trading was
allowed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
