<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 1745EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Tower-PastRejectees     03-09 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tower-Past Rejectees,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tower Joins History's List of Failed Cabinet Nominees</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tower, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With John Tower's defeat in the Senate on
Thursday, his name joins the likes of Roger B. Taney, Caleb Cushing
and Lewis L. Strauss on history's short list of failed Cabinet
nominees.
   Eight times before in its 200 years, the Senate voted to deny
confirmation to a president's choice for members of his Cabinet.
   Tower, President Bush's nominee for secretary of defense, became
the ninth, rejected by a vote of 53-47.
   Tower's defeat carries other distinctions, too: the first nominee
to be voted down in nearly 30 years, the first nominee of a
just-elected president to be defeated as the chief executive was
shaping his first Cabinet, and the first former senator to be beaten
in a Senate floor vote.
   Still more presidential nominees have run afoul of the Senate and
failed to win confirmation, according to a Library of Congress
study. In four cases the nominations were withdrawn rather than
pressed to a vote, as some had suggested Tower might have done. In
two other cases, nominations died in Senate committees and thus
weren't put to a vote on the floor.
   Before Tower, the last rejection had been on June 19, 1959, when
Strauss, President Dwight Eisenhower's choice for secretary of
commerce, was beaten by 49-46.
   Strauss had been on the job since the previous November, having
been appointed during a congressional recess, but his earlier
performance as chairman of the Atomic Energy Commission he had made
too many Senate enemies.
   The first Senate reject was Taney, who was President Andrew
Jackson's nominee for secretary of the treasury.
   The Senate voted 28-18 to reject his nomination on June 24, 1834,
although Taney had been serving since the previous September.
Jackson later appointed him chief justice, and he won a Senate
confirmation vote.
   President John Tyler, facing opposition in Congress from his own
Whig Party because of legislation he vetoed, saw four Cabinet
nominees rejected.
   He nominated Cushing to be secretary of the treasury, and on
March 3, 1843, the Senate voted three times to reject. Tyler tried
and failed again with a treasury nominee: James S. Green was
rejected on June 15, 1844, although the vote was not recorded.
   In January 1844, Tyler's nomination of David Henshaw to be
secretary of the navy and James Madison Porter to be secretary of
war were both rejected. Porter got just three votes in his favor.
   President Andrew Johnson's nomination of Henry Stanbery to be
attorney general was rejected in 1868. He had held the job
previously and stepped down to help Johnson's fight against
impeachment.
   President Calvin Coolidge's nomination of Charles B. Warren as
attorney general was rejected twice in one week in 1925.
   Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., speaking against Tower's nomination on
Wednesday, recalled much of that history and said the Constitution's
requirement that nominations be made with ``the advice and consent
of the Senate'' does not specify that it vote.
   ``The Constitution does not say that we senators even have to
vote on a nomination,'' Byrd said. ``There have been nominations
that have never been voted on and, therefore, never been confirmed.
There have been some that have been withdrawn.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890309-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 1750EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-LaserTheft     03-09 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Laser Theft,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Powerful Laser Gun Taken During Burglary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOCA RATON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A burglar who ransacked a medical office
stole a pistol-shaped laser gun capable of blinding or burning a
person up to 30 feet away with an invisible beam when plugged in,
authorities said.
   Investigators say the thief came across the gun during a break-in
at a doctor's office Wednesday and took the sophisticated $20,000
piece of medical hardware apparently without knowing what it was.
   ``They could just point it at somebody and blind them,'' said
Palm Beach County Sheriff's Sgt. Ken Deischer. ``We could have some
serious problems with this.''
   Dr. Martin Shank, the podiatrist from whose office the laser gun
was stolen, agreed the instrument ``is not a toy.''
   ``It can be disastrous in the wrong hands,'' he said. He said the
gun's light is ``invisible, and will burn a hole in the eye.'' The
device has no warnings printed on it, officials said.
   The laser, used to remove skin cancer, ingrown toenails and fungi
from feet, can burn a hole through a hand at its most powerful
setting.
   It can also blind a person up to 30 feet away and ignite most
non-metallic materials, flammable liquids and some explosive gases,
authorities said.
   The laser gun was made by Pfizer Laser Systems of Irvine, Calif.
It weighs 10 ounces and looks like a small pistol with a long handle.
   Its power charger, which was also taken, is about the size of a
business telephone. The device takes only three seconds to warm up.
   Shank said the fact the laser gun must be plugged is encouraging.
   ``The only consolation is knowing that these burglars aren't
going to be roaming the streets hurting people with it,'' he said.
   Lawrence Rutledge, Pfizer Laser Systems' Florida sales
representative, said from his Orlando office that the laser is ``not
like a flame thrower or anything.''
   But the manufacturer recommends several precautions, such as
wearing protective eyewear because the beam is easily reflected off
shiny metal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
