<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-09 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dry Weather Almost Coast To Coast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A long-lived storm finally moved off the East Coast on Thursday
with a parting shot of cold, wet weather.
   During the night, sleet, snow and freezing rain lashed parts of
Virginia and North Carolina, and light rain and drizzle fell along
the coast of Georgia and Florida.
   By noon, there was only a scattering of rain along the central
Atlantic Coast and east-central Florida. However, advisories for
gale-force wind remained in effect along the coast of the Carolinas,
Georgia and northeastern Florida.
   Elsewhere, rain was scattered from western Montana across the
northern half of the Pacific Coast.
   During the six hours up to 1 p.m. EST, no measurable snowfall or
significant rain were reported, the National Weather Service said.
   In the aftermath of the storm, Oklahoma National Guardsmen and
inmates pitched in Thursday to help dispose of an estimated 3
million chickens killed when the storm collapsed dozens of farm
buildings in under ice and up to 16 inches of snow.
   State Agriculture Commissioner Jack Craig said poultry losses are
estimated at more than $3 million. Some rural Oklahoma roads were
still snow-covered.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 26
degrees at Limestone, Maine, to 86 at Gila Bend, Ariz. Thursday's
low for the Lower 48 states was 23 degrees below zero at Fort Kent,
Maine.
   For Friday, rain was forecast from central and northern
California across the northern Pacific Coast and over the northern
half of the Plateau. Snow was forecast over higher elevations of the
Northwest.
   Highs in the 30s and 40s were predicted from New England across
the Virginias, the Great Lakes, the upper Mississippi Valley,
northern North Dakota and northeastern Montana; in the 50s and 60s
from the Carolinas across central Florida, from the central Gulf of
Mexico coast into the upper Ohio Valley, much of the remainder of
the Mississippi Valley, the remainder of the Dakotas, the central
Missouri Valley, the Rockies, the northern Plateau, the Great Basin,
the northern and central Pacific Coast, and southwestern California;
in the 90s over the desert Southwest, and in the 70s and 80s over
the remainder of the nation.
</TEXT>
