<SECOND>AM-Bennett, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0633,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Confirms Bennett as Drug Czar</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with eight new grafs with Senate confirms Bennett; pick
up fifth graf pvs: ``As head ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Education Secretary William J. Bennett
won Senate confirmation Thursday as head of the war on drugs, with
lawmakers urging him to waste no time in fashioning a strategy for
fighting the invasion of illegal narcotics.
   ``Mr. Bennett is in for the fight of his life, but more important
he is in for the fight of our children's lives,'' Sen. Alfonse
D'Amato, R-N.Y., said before the Senate voted 97-2 for confirmation.
   The opposition votes were cast by Sens. Jeff Bingaman, D-N.M.,
and Paul Simon, D-Ill. Sen. John Warner, R-Va., didn't vote.
   The full Senate acted hours after the Judiciary Committee voted
13-1 to send Bennett's nomination to the floor with a favorable
recommendation.
   Following the tumultuous floor fight over President Bush's
nomination of former Sen. John Tower as secretary of defense,
approval of Bennett came easily despite controversy that swirled
around his brash style and outspoken views as education secretary.
   Sen. Alan Simpson, R-Wyo., told the Senate that congressional
oversight of the so-called drug czar must be streamlined or Bennett
will be forced to squander his time on ``seven-camera hearings'' on
Capitol Hill instead of battling the tide of narcotics.
   Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., a longtime ally of teacher groups,
expressed concern on the Senate floor that Bennett would produce ``a
blizzard of press releases but not much action.''
   He had told the Judiciary Committee earlier that Bennett had
sought a cut in the Education Department's drug education budget
and, as an administrator, ``was not strong.''
   As head of the new Office of National Drug Control Policy,
Bennett will be in charge of drawing up plans to attack the nation's
drug problems.
   The ``drug czar'' is required to study the spending plans of
Cabinet officers and prod them to increase what they have designated
for the war on drugs if he deems that is necessary. Disputes
ultimately would be settled by the president.
   ``I've been struck these last few weeks, as I've met with people
inside government and out, by the pessimism many have about our
mission in the war on drugs,'' Bennett told lawmakers last week.
   Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., told the Judiciary Committee on
Thursday that Bennett ``has a difficult job (but) it shouldn't be
considered mission impossible.''
   Committee Chairman Joseph Biden, D-Del., told lawmakers that the
real issue was ``not about whether Dr. Bennett is going to put
together a strategy.''
   ``This is about whether President Bush has a strategy, whether he
is going to enunciate that strategy and whether he is going to put
that strategy into effect,'' Biden said.
   Sen. Strom Thurmond of South Carolina, the top Republican on the
committee, replied there was no question that Bush was focusing hard
on the drug problem.
   ``I have been in the White House several times recently and I
assure you that he is vitally interested,'' Thurmond said.
   Biden said he had no doubt that Bush was interested but it
remained to be seen if the interest would be ``matched by
overwhelming commitment of resources and action.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
