<FIRST>r a AM-MissionfromLockerbie     03-09 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mission from Lockerbie,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Police Officers Meet with Families of Lockerbie Victims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four senior Scottish police officers have arrived
in the United States and plan to visit families of the 259 victims
of the Pan Am Flight 103 bombing to clear up complaints about the
crash investigation.
   The officers said they will visit several cities to talk to
relatives who complained that police have been too slow in releasing
personal possessions of those who died in the terrorist bombing over
Scotland in December.
   ``I lost a 16-year-old daughter and she had four suitcases with
her, almost everything she owned,'' said Paul Hudson, a lawyer in
Albany, N.Y., who formed the 300-member relatives support group
Victims of Pan Am 103 in February. ``She had her Christmas presents
with her. Many of our memories of her were with her on that plane.''
   So far, only five or six relatives of the victims have received
any returned possessions, Hudson said.
   ``It's the last thing they have to remember their sons and
daughters,'' said North Adams Mayor Jim Barrett, who represented
several Massachusetts families after the crash. ``Rings, bracelets,
it would mean so much to them to get them back.''
   The British officers arrived in Boston on Wednesday night and
flew to Washington on Thursday to meet with State Department
officials.
   ``There has been some misinformation. There has been some rumor''
about the release of possessions, Assistant Chief Constable Paul
Newell told British television before he left for the United States.
   ``We feel that to try to ease the frustrations of the relatives
here we should come personally and explain to various groups of
relatives exactly what the position is.''
   A letter from the families to Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher
last month may have resulted in the visit, said Hudson.
   ``It's a very emotional time,'' said Joe Horgan of West Point,
Pa., whose brother-in-law was on Flight 103. ``The additional trauma
of not having things returned means that the healing process cannot
hit full stride.''
   Horgan said the families understand that Scottish law differs
from American and authorities there do not want to release what they
consider evidence in a criminal investigation.
   But he said the families became upset after receiving a letter
from a State Department official last month that hinted that some
victims' luggage and clothing might be destrztat'' but it was found
later to be false. He said the families are not angry at Scottish
authorities, who ``have been very sensitive to our needs.''
   State Department officials did not return telephone calls
Thursday.
   Scottish police recovered more than 11,000 items of property
scattered over 845 square miles.
   As ownership was established and the items were eliminated from
the criminal inquiry, the property started to be returned via the
U.S. consulate in mid-February, a police spokesman said.
   The Scottish police are scheduled to meet with families in New
York on Saturday and in Boston on Sunday, travel to Canton, Ohio, on
Monday and see families in Detroit on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
