<FIRST>u w AM-NorthTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0666 03-09 0857</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-North Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0666,860</SECOND>
<HEAD>Witness Says North Wrote White House Letter to Congress</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with testimony on letter to Congress, other detail in
top 11 grafs, picking up in 3rd graf pvs, Even U.S.; subs 2 grafs for final
7 grafs pvs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A witness testified Thursday that Oliver North
was irritated about having to answer ``asinine questions'' from
Congress _ the first direct testimony that North drafted a letter
denying he helped the Nicaraguan Contras.
   The letter, dated Oct. 7, 1985, is at the heart of one of the
criminal charges against North. He is accused of having said falsely
that he did not use his influence to get supplies to the Nicaraguan
resistance.
   Also, during a day when three witnesses testified against North,
the former National Security Council aide's lawyer tried to show
that fund-raiser Carl Channell had changed his story on a damaging
conversation in which Channell quotes North as not caring about
lying to Congress or going to jail.
   Later in the day, Daniel L. Conrad testified that then-National
Security Adviser Robert McFarlane had received a letter from
Congress with 20 to 30 questions about fund-raising activities.
   ``Colonel North said `I just got this and I'm supposed to develop
the answers,''' Conrad testified. ``His boss had to testify and he
(North) was supposed to draft the answers.
   ``He angrily went through the questions. He was irritated he had
to take the time to develop answers to `these asinine questions.'''
   Conrad, who was a go-between for Channell and North, said that in
the same conversation, North said he didn't want Conrad to visit him
so often in the White House complex because visitors' logs were kept.
   Conrad, who specialized in giving talks on fund-raising,
testified that briefings about Nicaragua by the State Department
failed to motivate people to help the Contras. He then heard North
and ``there were light years of difference. He was far superior,
exciting and motivated.''
   He said North told him that money raised by Channell was turned
over to a public relations firm, International Business
Communications. From there it was sent to an account in the Grand
Cayman Islands, then to a bank in Switzerland and finally went to
pay for supplies for the Contras.
   Richard Miller, who ran IBC, followed Conrad to the witness
stand. He called North ``the point man for Central American policy
in the White House,'' and said North once had him arrange to have
Contra leader Alphonso Robelo flown from Costa Rica to Washington to
be present at a fund-raising meeting.
   As Channell was winding up his testimony, North attorney Brendan
Sullivan said: ``Yesterday you were putting the words in Ollie's
mouth.'' On other occasions, he said, Channell either had left out
the quotes on North not caring about lying to Congress or going to
jail, or else attributed the words to Nelson Bunker Hunt, the other
person in the conversation.
   Even U.S. District Judge Gerhard Gesell signaled his skepticism,
saying at one point that Channell had offered ``three versions
already that Colonel North said what he did relating to these two
questions.''
   On Wednesday, Channell had testified at North's trial that on
Sept. 11, 1985, Hunt, a wealthy Texan, asked North if he were
worried about ``getting in trouble'' for his activities on behalf of
the rebels.
   North's reply, which Channell said ``stuck in my mind,'' was, ``I
don't care if I have to go to jail for this; I don't care if I have
to lie to Congress about this.''
   The judge asked, ``How do you explain to the jury it stuck in
your mind and that you had no doubt about it?''
   Sullivan, who had led Channell through gentle questioning for
more than an hour, said, ``It's hard to remember what was said ...
sometimes when you have such an urge to cooperate, there is a
tendency to want to put words in people's mouths.''
   He said Channell never mentioned the North comments in interviews
with government investigators in January and March 1987. And he
suggested Channell mentioned the conversation first a month later as
a bargaining chip when he himself was plea bargaining with
Iran-Contra prosecutors.
   But in later questioning, prosecution lawyer Michael Bromwich
brought out that records of those interviews were not stenographic
transcrips, but summaries _ and that Channell had never been asked
about either the ``go to jail'' or ``lie to Congress'' statements.
   ``Were you ever told in words or substance, `Give us Ollie
North,'?'' the prosecutor asked.
   ``No,'' said Channell.
   ``Were you ever told your sentence depended whether North would
be convicted or acquitted?''
   ``No, I've been told just the opposite''
   The day after the Hunt meeting, the government charges in one of
12 counts, North drafted the letter signed by his boss, McFarlane,
in which he denied to a congressional committee that the National
Security Council had a hand in fund-raising for military aid to the
Nicaraguan Contras. Official aid was at that time forbidden by law.
   One man who contributed to the Contra cause, beer magnate Joseph
Coors, is to testify Friday.
</TEXT>
