<FIRST>u w AM-TowerFarewell     03-09 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tower Farewell,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tower Bids Pentagon, Colleagues Farewell in Somber Goodbye Statement</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tower Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After watching the Senate vote to reject his
nomination, John Tower walked to the private Pentagon dining room
reserved for the secretary of defense and said goodbye.
   The former Texas senator, who by all accounts had longed to make
that room his own, had reported for work earlier in the day in a
transition office upstairs.
   Now, speaking in his clear, deep baritone, Tower said he might be
judged harshly by history but was returning to his home state ``at
peace with myself, knowing that I have given a full measure of
devotion to my country.''
   The debate over Tower's bid to become the nation's 17th defense
secretary was dominated by allegations of excessive drinking and
womanizing and concerns over Tower's lucrative defense consulting
work after leaving the Senate.
   ``No public figure in my memory has been subjected to such a
far-reaching and thorough investigation nor had his human foibles
bared to such intensive and demeaning public scrutiny,'' Tower said.
   ``And yet, there is no finding that I have ever breached
established legal and ethical standards nor been derelict in my
duty.''
   After undergoing weeks of personal scrutiny, Tower clearly had no
intention Thursday of subjecting himself to more.
   He watched the Senate vote on television and then appeared only
briefly in the secretary's dining room before a TV camera and two
reporters. He stayed just long enough to read his statement.
   Looking dapper in his trademark three-piece, pinstripe suit, he
declined to take any questions.
   ``I will be recorded as the first Cabinet nominee in the history
of the republic to be rejected in the first 90 days of a presidency
and perhaps be harshly judged,'' Tower said.
   ``I am deeply grateful to our great president for his continuing
confidence in me and his unflagging support in the most difficult of
circumstances. He also thanked his ``old colleagues in the Senate
who rallied to me with fervor, zeal and eloquence in the face of
staggering political odds.''
   Referring to the rancorous six-day debate over his fate, Tower
said it was time for ``the bitterness, rancor and anger to fade, and
for those elements of government who have been involved in the
confirmation process to unite and to be about the people's
business.''
   Tower said he would return to private life in ``my beloved
Texas.''
   He then ignored a reporter's question, said ``Thank you'' and
walked from the room to the private elevator that would take him to
his car.
</TEXT>
