<FIRST>r w AM-CommoditiesProbe     03-09 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodities Probe,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>CFTC Chairman Says Current Powers Enough to Ensure Market Integrity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Commodity Futures Trading Commission has
enough power to protect options and futures market integrity,
despite questions raised by a Chicago trading scandal, its chairman
told a Senate panel Thursday.
   Commission Chairman Wendy L. Gramm testified before the Senate
Agriculture Committee, which said an FBI investigation involving two
exchanges in Chicago ``raises fundamental questions about the
futures regulatory system.''
   Congress is considering legislation to reauthorize the commission
through 1994, extending its authorty to enforce federal futures and
options trading laws.
   A future is a contract to buy or sell a commodity at a specified
price on a given date. An option is the right to buy or sell a
commodity for a specified price at some time in the future.
   The House and Senate agriculture committees have jurisdiction
over the CFTC. The committee chairmen say reauthorization was
expected to be a brief process but reports of an FBI investigation
into alleged fraud and illegal trading on Chicago futures markets
made a congressional inquiry necessary.
   The bureau's probe reportedly involves allegations that brokers
and traders cheated customers out of millions of dollars in deals on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange and Chicago Board of Trade.
   Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., who heads the Senate committee, said
the panel wants to know how well the CFTC enforces the laws
regulating U.S. futures and options exchanges and how it can be sure
the 14 exchanges do an adequate job of self-policing.
   ``The results of the not-yet-complete Chicago investigation may
provide new information as to the effectiveness of existing programs
upon which changes can be based,'' Mrs. Gramm told the committee.
   However, she said no program can detect every instance of
wrongdoing, particularly when it occurs off the trading floor.
   ``The commission believes that its existing regulatory authority
should be sufficient to discharge its responsibilities to protect
the integrity of U.S. futures and options markets,'' Mrs. Gramm said.
   ``To the extent that any improprieties or abuses found in the
course of the ongoing investigation warrant changes in the existing
programs, systems, or rules, the commission has publicly stated that
it stands ready to take such actions as may be appropriate to
address those circumstances,'' she added.
   Leahy ordered the CFTC, within 30 days, to submit an analysis of
12 proposals made to tighten oversight of exchange floors.
   ``The committee has not yet judged the wisdom of any one of these
approaches, nor do we prejudge the outcome of the Chicago probe,''
he said. ``Our goal, rather, is to begin the focus of public debate
on tangible reforms aimed at maintaining confidence in the
marketplace.''
   Among the proposals were requiring exchanges to devote more
resources to floor surveillance, and increasing penalties for
trading abuses.
</TEXT>
