<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 2152EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PetProject     03-09 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pet Project,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Animal Hospital Launches Pet Blood Drive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hospital is seeking a new breed of blood donors _
dogs and cats _ to help set up a blood bank for pets.
   Special liquids will replace the usual orange juice chasers and
not all of the donors are expected to sit quietly as they give the
gift of life. But in many respects the blood drive beginning April 2
will resemble its human counterpart, Dr. Alicia Faggella, a
veterinarian with the Angell Memorial Animal Hospital, said Thursday.
   The blood drive, overseen by the Massachusetts Society for the
Prevention of Cruelty to Animals, will enable the creation of a
blood bank at the hospital, which gave more than 300 life-saving
transfusions to dogs and cats last year.
   ``I have not heard of any drives that have been conducted in any
part of the country. So they're plowing some new ground,'' said Dr.
John Albers, executive director of the American Animal Hospital
Association in Denver. ``It's a neat idea.''
   Currently, veterinarians keep a few animals in their clinics as
mascots and blood donors or rely on a network of former patients
that can be called in, he said.
   The Angell hospital currently has workers bring in their pets for
regular donations, Faggella said. Hospital officials hope to expand
that to a more formal blood-storage system that would operate like a
human blood bank.
   Plasma would be separated from the blood and frozen, making it
last longer, and more types of blood would be on hand, Faggella
said. Like humans, animals have different blood types, and cat blood
is different from dog blood.
   Accidents are the most common reason pets need blood, but it also
is used in treating such diseases as feline leukemia, she said.
   ``People really don't realize that our expertise is very similar
in many instances to human medicine,'' she said. ``We treat pets
with cancer; we do total hip replacements. We have animals who have
diabetes. We do cardiovascular heart surgery to repair different
defects in the heart. There's a specialist in every area.''
   Dogs usually are willing to cooperate in donating a pint, said
Faggella. Cats a extra persuasion to donate the usual amount of
about 3 tablespoons. ``We do tranquilize them so they don't get
stressed out,'' she said.
   So far, a few pet owners have registered for the drive.
   ``I think they will be interested in it,'' she said. ``I know we
have several clients who in the past, when blood was very scarce,
they've been very thankful that their animals have been saved by
it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890309-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 1855EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Kassebaum     03-09 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kassebaum,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Tower, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Gentlelady from Kansas Proves to be Lone GOP Dissenter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE GOULD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associted Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nancy Landon Kassebaum, the determined
gentlelady from Kansas, was the lone Republcian to vote against John
Tower for secretary of defense Thursday.
   It wasn't the first time the junior senator from Kansas had gone
against her party _ and her party's leader, Bob Dole, the senior
senator from Kansas and the leader of the losing fight to save the
nomination.
   Dole frequently charged that the fight was strictly partisan,
minority Republicans against majority Democrats. Kassebaum saw
things differently.
   ``This has not been an easy decision for me or for any of us,''
Kassebaum said in a statement entered into the Congressional Record
but not spoken on the Senate floor. ``Members I highly respect on
both sides of the aisle are diametrically and vehemently in
opposition.''
   If there was any irony in Kassebaum spliting with Dole on such a
key vote, there was also the matter of Kassebaum's concern about
Tower's attitudes toward women.
   Kassebaum, one of only two women in the Senate, noted that a
Pentagon study ``recently highlighted the seriousness of the
problems of harassment and promotion. ... I am not confident that
Senator Tower would give these issues the priority they demand or
would demonstrate the necessary sensitivity to their seriousness.''
   But her prime concern was not women. Nor was it Tower's past
drinking habits, which several sentors noted but she mentioned not
at all.
   ``Most importantly,'' Kassebaum said, ``the next secretary of
defense is going to have to counter the debilitating impact that the
defense procurement scandal has had on public confidence in our
defense establishment.''
   ``In meeting these challenges, the next secretary of defense must
have the confidence, trust and respect of the American people and
the Congress. ... I do not believe he can provide the leadership
that is necessary to forge a consensus on the critical national
security issues confronting us today.''
   ``My most serious concerns about the nomination of John Tower are
from the public record,'' Kassebaum said. ``Although Senator Tower
did not break any laws, his consulting activities over the past
couple of years, in my opinion, raise very serious concerns about
the nominee's judgment and his sensitivity to those major issues of
conflict of interest.''
   Later, Kassebaum told reporters she would have voted for Tower if
hers were the deciding vote.
   ``I had told the president I would have voted for him even though
I had serious misgivings,'' she said, ``because, at that point, I
wouldn't have wanted to be the vote to defeat.
   Her vote wasn't needed, and Kassabaum became the only senator on
the Republican side of the aisle to stand and say ``no'' when the
roll was called.
   Kassebaum, 56, went against Dole, her party and then-Sen. Dan
Quayle in the summer of 1986, when she opposed the nomination of
Daniel Manion as a federal judge in Indiana. Kassebaum voted no, but
was persuaded by Quayle to ``pair'' her vote with an absent senator
who reportedly would have voted yes. Pairing, in effect, cancels out
each vote. Manion was confirmed.
   Kassebaum also bolted from the party fold later that year, siding
with Democrats to override President Reagan's veto of limited
economic sanctions against South Africa.
   She was first elected to the Senate in 1978, with her only
previous public office that of a local school board. She is,
however, the daughter of the late Alf Landon, the Republican
presidential nominee who lost to Franklin D. Roosevelt in 1936.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
