<FIRST>u i AM-Vatican-Finances     03-09 0594</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vatican-Finances,0611</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vatican Announces Tighter Control Over Bank Wracked By Scandal</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Vatican-Bishops</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Vatican on Thursday announced closer
scrutiny over its scandal-tainted bank with sweeping reforms to
abolish the post of president held by U.S. Archbishop Paul C.
Marcinkus and to hire more professionals.
   The changes were announced in a statement summing up three days
of meetings by a special commission of cardinals studying the
Vatican's financial problems. It forecast a record budget deficit of
more than $78 million this year.
   The statement said Marcinkus, a native of Cicero, Ill., will
assist the Vatican Bank during a ``transition phase.''
   The changes at the bank call for a new post of secretary to be
held by a non-bishop cleric, a special council of five financial
experts from various countries, and a director and a deputy director
named by that council.
   The Vatican also will set up a watchdog commission of five
cardinals named by the pope for the bank, which is formally called
the Institute for Religious Works.
   Pope John Paul II outlined the changes last June when he
overhauled the Curia, the church's central administration, but
Thursday's statement gave the first details.
   Marcinkus, 67, who has headed the bank since 1969, said he didn't
know exactly when he would leave.
   ``I will probably move on when it's all set up,'' Marcinkus said
in a telephone interview with The Associated Press.
   He noted he holds another post, the equivalent of deputy governor
of the Vatican city-state, adding, ``They haven't taken that away
yet.''
   Warrants for the arrest of Marcinkus and two lay Vatican bank
officials were issued in 1987 after Italian prosecutors charged them
with being accessories to the fraudulent bankruptcy of Banco
Ambrosiano, a Milan-based bank that collapsed in 1982. It was
Italy's biggest postwar banking scandal.
   But the arrests were never made. Italy's Constitutional Court
ruled that a Vatican-Italian treaty precluded any interference by
Italian authorities into the affairs of Vatican, an independent
city-state.
   The Vatican Bank, which was the largest shareholder in Banco
Ambrosiano, denied any wrongdoing in the bank's collapse, but agreed
in 1984 to pay $250 million to its creditors.
   The bank went under after the default of $1.3 billion in Vatican
Bank-assured loans made to 10 dummy corporations set up in Latin
America. The body of Roberto Calvi, Banco Ambrosiano's former
chairman, was found hanging from a London bridge in June 1982. An
Italian civil court ruled in January that Calvi was murdered.
   Announcing its financial position, the Vatican said it expected
revenues of $56,145,384 in 1989 and expenses of $134,326,153,
leaving a deficit of $78.1 million.
   The Vatican was in the red by about $66 million in 1988. A press
statement said the big jump in expenses was ``more apparent than
real'' because of a change in accounting practices that now put
costs of running the Holy See's diplomatic missions in 118 countries
directly under the budget of the Holy See.
   This expense had previously been covered by a special Vatican
fund that had run out.
   To cover the deficit, the Vatican said it would count heavily on
Peter's Pence, contributions by Catholics to the pope, which it said
amounted to nearly $53 million last year. It said it was also
expecting help from a special fund called the Papal Foundation, set
up by Cardinal John Krol, retired archbishop of Philadelphia.
   The statement said that while the cardinals found the Vatican's
expenses justified it urged the Holy See to make every effort to
reduce them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
