<FIRST>u i AM-Sudan-Relief     03-09 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan-Relief,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Donors Pledge Relief Aid, Await Rebel Acceptance of Truce</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aid donors pledged Thursday to provide
money and end red tape in a joint effort to save 100,000 people in
the southern war zone from starvation, but success now depends on
rebels accepting a cease-fire.
   A U.N.-sponsored conference of Western donor nations, relief
agencies and Sudanese government officials produced pledges
estimated at $132 million.
   Western health officials said an outbreak of meningitis also has
spread into southern Sudan and estimated the dead at 400. They said
the disease began in Ethiopia and was following an annual route
through northeastern Africa.
   Julia Taft of the U.S. Agency for International Development, said
the United States had pledged two military C-130 transports to the
airlift.
   Prime Minister Sadek Mahdi's government repeated its pledge to
observe a truce in April so food and medical supplies could be
stockpiled in the south before the rainy season begins in May.
   No word was received from the Sudan People's Liberation Army,
which has fought since 1983 for more autonomy and economic
advantages in the south, most of whose people are black Christians
or animists. Northern Sudan, which controls the government, is
predominantly Arab and Moslem.
   Mahdi said: ``I have nothing but smiles and handshakes for you
all. I thank you all and assure you that your recommendations will
find necessary and proper response from my government.''
   Relief workers want to move 165,000 tons of food, medicine and
other supplies south before the rainy season, which virtually
isolates the region for six months.
   The United Nations is trying to prevent a repeat of 1988, when up
to 500,000 southerners died of starvation, disease or the fighting.
Many of them died in summer, cut off in small towns when rain turned
roads into swamps and made airstrips unusable.
   U.N. experts say starvation and disease threaten 2.3 million
southerners this rainy season and up to 100,000 could die. Other
sources estimate the number at risk as high as 600,000.
   On Wednesday, Mahdi endorsed a cease-fire during April but said
the rebels also must accept it. Ms. Taft said she would visit Addis
Ababa, Ethiopia, on Friday and ask the insurgents to agree.
</TEXT>
