<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 2229EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Quayle     03-09 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Veep Says U.S. Must Accept Responsibility for Its Own Drug Problem</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States must accept responsibility
for its own drug problem and not just ``blame other countries for
what's been happening to us,'' Vice President Dan Quayle said
Thursday.
   Quayle, in remarks prepared for a speech to the International
Mayors Conference in New York, said some of the nations where drugs
originate have met ``several critical milestones in narcotics
control.''
   A text of his speech was released by his Washington office.
   ``We can't just blame other countries for what's been happening
to us. We must recognize that substantial efforts are being made by
some nations to stem the drug supply problem,'' Quayle said.
   He cited Peru, Bolivia and Mexico as countries making such
strides.
   Peru, for example, eradicated more than 5,130 hectares of coca
plants, used to make cocaine, over a four-month period, Quayle said.
   He also said the Bush administration ``will look into a number of
policy options that would allow us to do more to reinforce the
anti-narcotics efforts'' in Peru and other Andean countries.
   The U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration already has agents
stationed in South America to assist in anti-drug efforts. They
gather intelligence, assist local police and help in drug
eradication.
   ``At the same time that we work with other nations, we must also
recognize that we have become a drug-source nation ourselves. About
a quarter of the marijuana consumed in this country is domestically
grown. And a large number of drugs are illegally produced in
clandestine laboratories in this country,'' he said.
   The vice president said there is no reason for a ``feeling of
gloom that seems to envelop this issue like a thick, clammy fog,''
because although the situation is serious, the war against drugs is
winnable.
   He cited drug use surveys by the National High School Senior
Survey that show drug use among that group at its lowest level since
the survey began in 1975.
   ``In other words, the pessimists are being proven wrong once
again: the American demand for drugs is not insatiable; the American
people are not incapable of self-control.''
</TEXT>
