<FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovakia     03-09 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Czechoslovakia Convicts Two Dissidents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Czechoslovak court sent a popular rock
musician and another dissident to jail Thursday for demanding the
communist government explain the death of a jailed activist, emigre
sources and a rights group said.
   Ivan M. Jirous, a cultural activist and leader of the pop group
Plastic People, was convicted Thursday and sentenced to 16 months in
jail, and fellow defendant Jiri Tichy drew six months, said the
sources and the Vienna-based International Helsinki Federation, a
group monitoring East bloc human rights.
   Emigre sources said activists Pavel Dudr and Jaromir Nemec
received suspended sentences of 12 months and 18 months,
respectively, on Thursday at Kromeriz, Czechoslovakia, on charges of
circulating anti-state literature.
   The trials were part of a communist government crackdown that
earlier jailed playwright Vaclav Havel for nine months and resulted
in prison terms, fines or suspended sentences for seven other
activists.
   Tichy and Jirous were convicted of inciting anti-state activity
and harming the state's interests abroad, said Jan Kavan of the
London-based Palach Press newsletter, which monitors events in
Czechoslovakia.
   Jirous already had spent nearly eight years in jail for human
rights activities before he was arrested again, with Tichy, on Oct.
20, 1988.
   Tichy and Jirous immediately appealed their sentences, passed in
a court in the Moravian town of Jihlava, Palach Press said.
</TEXT>
