<FIRST>u i AM-UN-Soviet 1stLd-Writethru a0700 03-09 0699</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Soviet, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0700,0714</SECOND>
<HEAD>Experts Say Soviet-Human Rights Test in World Court Unlikely</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf `The Soviets...' to explain discrepancy between
number of treaties and subjects.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States welcomed Soviet
acceptance of World Court authority on human rights, but a
government legal expert said Thursday the justices probably never
will hear a case testing the Kremlin's commitment.
   On Wednesday, the Soviet Union said it would accept the court's
jurisdiction in six human rights treaties, reversing its policy of
resisting outside judgment of its practices.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev also has spoken recently in favor
of a larger U.N. role in such international areas as arms control
and space exploration, which traditionally have been dominated by
the Soviet Union and United States.
   U.N. and State Department legal officers said his acceptance of
jurisdiction by the World Court, a U.N. agency, will bring Gorbachev
international good will with little risk of embarrassment over
Soviet human rights practices.
   It also should help the Soviet effort to hold a human rights
conference in Moscow in 1991 as one of several follow-up meetings to
the 1975 Helsinki agreements on European security and cooperation.
   In January, Washington changed its position and said it would
accept a Moscow conference, citing the Soviet release of political
prisoners, easing of emigration and more tolerant views on free
speech and freedom of religion.
   The six treaties on which the Soviets will recognize the court's
authority deal with five areas. They condemn genocide, ban slavery,
guarantee political rights for women, prohibit racism and outlaw
torture.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman said the United States
welcomes ``any step in the submission of disputes of this kind to
binding decisions by neutral bodies such as the International Court
of Justice,'' the court's formal name.
   Pieter Kooijmans, U.N. special investigator on human rights, said
in Leiden, the Netherlands: ``It would be a real breakthrough for
human rights if the Soviet Union would recognize the right of
individuals'' to file complaints of rights abuses.
   Under the Optional Protocol to the International Covenant on
Civil and Political Rights, individual citizens can complain of
rights abuses to an international body of legal experts with the
power to order compensation. Hungary ratified the protocol last year.
   A State Department legal expert said privately: ``The
International Court of Justice has never handled a human rights
dispute'' and the Soviet acceptance of jurisdiction ``may amount to
nothing more than a meaningless gesture.''
   ``It would be unlikely that a human rights dispute would ever
wind its way to the World Court,'' he said.
   Only governments can take cases before the court, which has 15
judges and sits in The Hague in the Netherlands. It has no authority
to deal with complaints of individuals or private organizations.
   The United States has ratified only one of the six human rights
treaties. The Soviets have accepted all six.
   Last year, the Senate finally ratified the 1948 Convention on the
Prevention and Punishment of the Crime of Genocide, but rejected
World Court authority over its interpretation. The United States has
signed the five other treaties but the Senate has not ratified them.
   ``We have accepted (World Court) jurisdiction over many more
treaties than the Soviet Union has, bilateral and multilateral,''
the State Department legal expert said.
   Washington accepts World Court rulings under about 60 treaties
dealing with a range of diplomatic and commercial rights. The
Soviets have refused to recognize the court's authority.
   Last year, the United States, Soviet Union, Britain, France and
China began negotiations toward an agreement under which they would
submit to World Court rulings on all treaties that did not involve
sensitive national security issues or the use of force.
   They are the five permanent members of the U.N. Security Council
and have veto power in the council.
   The United States rejects World Court's jurisdiction in national
security cases.
   In 1986, Nicaragua asked the court to rule on the mining of its
harbors and covert U.S. support for Contra rebels. The court ruled
in Nicaragua's favor but the United States, which did not
participate in the case, refused to accept the decision.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
