<FIRST>r a AM-LimousineAmbush     03-09 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Limousine Ambush,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Businessman In Limousine Ambushed By Hail Of Bullets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BREA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man with interests in bars and horses was
killed in a fusillade of bullets fired from ambush just after his
chauffeur-driven limousine passed through the gate to his estate
early Thursday, police said.
   Horace Joseph McKenna, 46, a former California Highway Patrol
officer, was hit numerous times and died at the scene.
   There were no arrests and the number of assailants and the motive
were unknown, said police Capt. Jim Oman, who said McKenna
apparently owned bars in the Los Angeles area and owned or trained
horses at the estate.
   At least 20 rounds of 9mm bullets were fired and, based on the
rapidity of fire, either a semiautomatic or fully automatic weapon
was used, Oman said. Investigators found no guns.
   Oman said the chauffeur, Robert Berg, told police they were
returning from bars McKenna owned near Los Angeles International
Airport. But he said he wasn't certain how much Berg really knew of
McKenna's business.
   State Alcohol Beverage Control Board deputy division chief Carl
Falletta said McKenna had never been licensed to own a bar.
   The limousine had just passed through the gate at least a mile
from the house when the shots were fired, Oman said. ``There was a
second blast of gunfire and he (Berg) accelerated up the hills,''
Oman said.
   The estate, a house on a ridge with stables down below, is in the
rural hills and canyons of northern Orange County, southeast of Los
Angeles.
   The Los Angeles police and sheriff's departments turned away
requests for any information on McKenna. Orange County sheriff's Lt.
Dick Olson said his department was not involved, except for possible
technical assistance.
   McKenna joined the California Highway Patrol in June 1968 and
served as a motorcycle patrolman in the West Los Angeles CHP office
until he resigned June 15, 1972, said CHP headquarters spokesman Sam
Haynes.
   Haynes did not know the circumstances of McKenna's resignation,
and did not know anything about his activities over the subsequent
17 years.
</TEXT>
