<HEAD>Commentary on Eastern Bankruptcy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With AM-Eastern Bjt ^By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Chapter 11 means there's still a patient and it's undergoing
surgery and it's coming back. That's better than the continued slow
dismantling of Eastern under Texas Air.'' _ John Bavis, head of the
Eastern pilots.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``There's never been a more classic example of a robber baron.
Anytime anyone buys a ticket on Continental, they're making a
contribution to treachery ... to atrocity ... to evil.'' _ Eastern
Machinists leader Charles E. Bryan, urging a nationwide boycott of
Eastern's sister airline, non-union Continental Airlines.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``They don't have much left. I think they're a dead duck.'' _
Paul Gibson Jr., New York attorney and airline industry analyst,
assessing Eastern's survival chances.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``This bill would prevent Frank Lorenzo and any other airline
buccaneers from using bankruptcy to escape their creditors and
destroy their workers.'' _ Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, who filed
a bill to allow Eastern creditors to collect from Texas Air,
Eastern's parent company.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``The issue is fundamentally whether a troubled and sick business
in a competitive marketplace should be allowed to change itself and
manage its survival.'' _ Frank Lorenzo, chairman of Texas Air,
Eastern's parent company.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``We tried mightily to keep Eastern from bankruptcy.'' _ Phil
Bakes, president of Eastern Airlines.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``The entire labor movement learned something from the
Continental experience, and this time Lorenzo and his flunkies are
learning something about the power of union solidarity.'' _
President Owen Bieber of the United Auto Workers, which pledged
$50,000 to support strikers and their families.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``This ought to be called the Frank Lorenzo memorial
bankruptcy.'' _ Henry Duffy, head of the Airline Pilots Association.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``His (Lorenzo's) ultimate goal is to get the most of Eastern
airlines and let the rest of it sink.'' _ Robert Blanchard, Eastern
pilot.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``Starting tomorrow, I'll be looking for another job after 12
years here. But I'll still be right out here picketing and
protesting. I want my paycheck. I've got rent, food, clothing to
buy.'' _ Cynthia Carrasco, an Eastern officer service worker and
single mother of two daughters.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``I've been saving money all along all my life. I wasn't
necessarily saving them for a strike or loss of employment, but I
guess that's what I'm going to use it for.'' _ Co-pilot Gary Greska,
a 16-year Eastern veteran.
</TEXT>
