<FIRST>r w AM-France-Pouches     03-09 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Pouches,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>French Say Pouches Detained Illegally by US Agents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The French government has expressed concern to
the State Department that French consular officials were temporarily
denied access to diplomatic pouches by U.S. Customs agents in Miami,
American officials said Thursday.
   Based on x-rays and an inspection by drug-sniffing dogs, the
pouches were thought to contain cocaine packages when they arrived
in Miami from Santo Domingo Wednesday night.
   But once the pouches were released to French custody and flown to
Paris, French officials notified U.S. diplomats the containers were
drug-free.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman said that under
international law, diplomatic pouches are inviolable even if they
are believed to be carrying illegal substances.
   Another official, who asked not to be identified, said Customs
turned over the pouches to French consular officials unopened but
not before the containers had been withheld for a period from the
envoys.
   A French foreign service courier who accompanied the pouches was
detained for nine hours until he was ordered released by the State
Department, according to officials.
   Michael Sheehan, a Customs spokesman in Miami, said, ``We are
completely confident that what our dogs alerted to and what our
x-rays saw was cocaine.''
   But Thierry Reynard, the French consul in Miami, said the pouches
contained paper work in boxes that were packaged in lager boxes.
   ``I'm very surprised they could mistake the two things,'' he
said. ``They have to do their homework on investigations.''
</TEXT>
