<FIRST>r w AM-NeedleExchange     03-09 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Needle Exchange,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rangel Opposes Sullivan on Needles for Addicts to Fight AIDS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., issued a stinging
attack Thursday on Health and Human Services Secretary Louis
Sullivan for supporting clean-needle programs for drug users in
communities trying to stop the spread of AIDS.
   Rangel said he found it shocking that Sullivan, who took over the
health agency last week, would advocate the idea of exchanging
needles with drug addicts instead of proposing programs to expand
drug treatment services.
   ``The first step he takes in drug abuse is to appear to give
support to addicts by giving them needles,'' Rangel said. ``It's an
immoral thing to distribute needles to addicts. The next thing you
know they'll be distributing drugs.''
   ``It sends a message to the minority community that we don't have
the time, the resources or the will to try to get you off drugs and
back into the mainstream, but we do have the time to give you
sterile needles,'' he said.
   Sullivan, in an interview Wednesday, said he does not believe
needle-exchange programs condone drug abuse, but rather could deal
with one way the deadly AIDS virus is spread _ among drug addicts
through the use of shared needles. Once infected, addicts also can
spread the disease to sex partners and their babies.
   While emphasizing that decisions on such programs should be made
locally, Sullivan said needle-exchange programs ``deserve a chance
for an appropriate trial'' in communities that want them.
   New York City Health Commissioner Stephen C. Joseph said
Sullivan's support was a ``tremendous boost'' to his program, one of
only a few in the country.
   The New York program has enrolled 92 addicts, 60 percent of whom
are infected with the AIDS virus _ ``and that's viruses taken off
the street,'' he said.
   However, Rangel called the New York program ``a complete flop.''
He also opposes a recent HHS proposal to make it easier for heroin
addicts to get methadone while waiting for comprehensive treatment,
saying the program would only ``substitute one addictive drug for
another.''
   In a related development Thursday, the Alcohol, Drug Abuse and
Mental Health Association announced a $75 million grant program to
expand drug treatment services in cities that have waiting lists of
more than one month. A critical purpose of the grants, the agency
said, is to help get addicts off the streets faster to reduce the
spread of AIDS.
</TEXT>
