<HEAD>With AM-Eastern Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT DVORCHAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frank Lorenzo, boss of Eastern's parent company,
said Thursday unions should quit picking on him and start picking up
the pieces of his airline.
   ``It's time the messenger stops getting shot because the
messenger is unpopular,'' a worn but stone-faced Lorenzo said.
``Eastern is a troubled company that has to change in order to
survive.''
   Lorenzo, who is known among employees as a union-buster and one
of the toughest bosses in America, is a lightning rod in the
6-day-old strike by Machinists. Pilots and flight attendants have
honored the picket lines.
   He is chief executive officer of Texas Air Corp., the largest
airline conglomerate in the United States. It absorbed Eastern three
years ago when the airline was on the brink of bankruptcy.
   Pickets have lambasted Lorenzo, 48, who announced Thursday that
Eastern filed for protection from creditors under federal bankruptcy
law.
   AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland called him the ``Typhoid Mary of
union busting.''
   Charles Bryan, leader of the striking Machinists, said of
Lorenzo: ``There's never been a more classic example of a robber
baron.'' He described the stand let the rest of it sink,''
said Blanchard, wearing his pilot's cap.
   Police in bulletproof vests stood outside the hotel where Lorenzo
spoke, and 21 motorcycle officers parked in formation outside. There
were no disruptions.
   A marathon runner, Lorenzo was raised by Spanish immigrants in
the New York City borough of Queens, within earshot of LaGuardia
Airport's jets. A one-time member of the Teamsters union, he drove a
Coca-Cola truck and had the schoolboy nickname ``Frankie Smooth
Talk.''
   A graduate of Columbia and Harvard Business School, he worked as
an analyst for Eastern before building his airline empire.
   The hard-driving Lorenzo apologized to Eastern employees, their
families and travelers affected by the strike. ``I'm very sorry to
see these people impacted,'' he said. ``The events of the last week
are very troubling.''
   He got the only laugh of an hour-long news conference when he was
asked if Eastern had been a bad buy.
   ``It sure hasn't done much for my leisure time,'' Lorenzo
answered, saying his golf and tennis time have suffered.
