<FIRST>r a AM-People Subs a0654 03-09 0157</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People, Subs, a0654,0160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs last item to CORRECT to 31 years ago sted 21.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American space researcher James A. Van
Allen was named the winner Wednesday of the 1989 Crafoord Prize for
his discovery 31 years ago of the radiation belts surrounding the
Earth.
   The Royal Academy of Sciences also cited the professor emeritus
at the University of Iowa for providing the first instruments ever
carried to another planet, those taken on the 1963 mission to Venus
by Mariner II.
   His work with the Explorer I satellite led to the discovery in
1958 of the Earth's radiation belts, now called the Van Allen belts.
   The prize, which includes a $252,000 cash award, is given
annually by the Royal Academy, which also awards Nobel Prizes.
   The award was founded in 1980 for excellence in physical sciences
outside those stipulated by the 1896 will of Alfred Nobel:
chemistry, physics, and medicine.
</TEXT>
