<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Mapplethorpe     03-09 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Mapplethorpe,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Avant Garde Photographer Dies At 42</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Avant garde photographer Robert Mapplethorpe,
considered among the most prominent young artists in his field, died
Thursday at a Boston hospital at the age of 42.
   Mapplethorpe, who lived in New York City and had suffered from
AIDS for three years, died at Deaconness Hospital, according to
friends. The hospital refused to release any information.
   Mapplethorpe, whose work focused heavily on homosexual themes,
was best known for his startling photography of sadomasochism and
his depiction of athletic male nudes. He also was known for
photographs of celebrities.
   His favorite medium was black and white photography but he also
experimented with color. Most of his work, whether of people or
objects, is presented as if they were pieces of sculpture.
   ``I want to get a picture that is the way I want to remember
someone. It's like a diary in the end,'' Mapplethorpe once said.
``My work is about order. I am a perfectionist.''
   A major retrospective of his work was recently shown in New York
at the Whitney Museum.
   At the time of his death, an exhibit of his works titled ``Robert
Mapplethrope: The Perfect Moment'' was in Chicago at the Museum of
Contemporary Art on the second leg of a five-city American tour that
began in Philadelphia.
   He emerged in the mid-1970s as part of an offbeat culture that
included longtime friend rock singer Patti Smith. He worked in
several media, including collage and film.
   At least four books on his works have been published.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
