<FIRST>r a AM-SovietExpelled-History     03-09 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Expelled-History,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>Past Cases of Diplomatic Expulsions</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet Expelled</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some past instances this decade of expulsions of Soviet
personnel from the United States and of U.S. personnel from the
Soviet Union:
   March 7, 1983: Richard Osborne, U.S. economics attache in Moscow,
expelled.
   June 12, 1983: Louis Thomas, a civilian working in the U.S.
Embassy security division, expelled. Soviet media say he had been
caught during a ``pre-arranged conspiracy meeting.''
   August 17, 1983: Anatoly Yevgenyevich Skripko, an attache at the
Soviet Embassy in Washington, expelled.
   August 19, 1983: Yuri Petrovich Leonov, an assistant air attache
at the Soviet Embassy in Washington, expelled. Skripko and Leonov
are declared persona non grata.
   Sept. 12, 1983: Lon David Augustenborg, U.S. diplomat, expelled
from the Soviet Union. He and his wife had been detained outside
Leningrad and accused of trying to collect what Soviet newspapers
called a ``spy container.''
   Nov. 6, 1983: Norman J. Zabusky, University of Pittsburgh
Mathematics Professor on exchange in Moscow, expelled for ``conduct
unacceptable.'' Zabusky had spoken with a group of Refusenik
scientists.
   June 1984: Bruce Rosenberg, U.S. economics officer, is
``compelled'' to leave after being accused of speculating in Western
goods and distributing anti-Soviet materials, Soviet media say.
   May 13, 1985: Regina Sipple, American tourist from Salt Lake
City, expelled from Moscow for carrying biblical literature and
cassettes.
   June 1985: Paul Stombaugh, expert on Baltic States in the U.S.
Embassy's political section, expelled; Soviet media say he was
ordered out for ``conducting an espionage action.''
   March 14, 1986: Michael Sellers, second secretary at the U.S.
Embassy in Moscow, is accused of spying and of having a
``clandestine meeting'' with a Soviet citizen and expelled. The
action came a week after the United States angered the Kremlin by
ordering Soviet missions to the United Nations in New York to cut
from 279 personnel to 170.
   May 14, 1986: Erik Sites, attache of the U.S. Embassy in Moscow,
is expelled; Soviet media say he had been arrested May 7 when he met
secretly with a Soviet citizen recruited by the C.I.A.
   Sept. 17, 1986: United States announces 25 members of the Soviet
mission to the United Nations must leave by Oct. 1. The Reagan
administration had announced in March that it would require
reductions in the Soviet UN staff.
   Oct. 19, 1986: The Kremlin expels for actions ``incompatible with
their official status'' First Secretary William Norville, Third
Secretary Charles Ehrenfried, attaches Gary Lonnquist and David
Harris from the embassy in Moscow. A consular staff employee in
Leningrad, Jack Roberts, also is expelled.
   Oct. 21, 1986: The U.S. expells 55 Soviet diplomats from
Washington and San Francisco. Fifty of these were ordered out to
bring the Soviet staffs to parity with the U.S. contingents in
Moscow and Leningrad. The remaining five are declared persona non
grata: Vasily Fedotov, Oleg Likeachev and Aleksandr Metelkin,
counselors; Nikolay Kokovin, attache, and Lev Zaytsev, consul.
   Oct. 22, 1986: The Kremlin expels Naval attache Capt. Thomas
Holme, Army attache Col. Richard Naab, second secretary Michael
Morgan, Third Secretary Michael Matera and Leningrad Vice Consul
Daniel Grossman, saying they engaged in ``impermissible activities.''
   Dec. 17, 1987: Mikhail Katkov, midlevel official at the Soviet
Mission to the United Nations, expelled.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
