<SECOND>AM-Satanic Verses, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0722,0782</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nine Former Iranian Embassy Employees Told to Leave in 10 Days</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: To UPDATE with comment from Iran, SUBS 3rd graf `A conservative...'
with 2 grafs and INSERTS 3 grafs after 15th pvs, ``I have...' Pick up 16th
pvs, `Bishop H.J.A....'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has targeted nine former Iranian
Embassy employees for deportation if they do not leave Britain
voluntarily within 10 days, an immigration official said Thursday.
   The U.N. secretary-general, Javier Perez de Cuellar, said he has
issued appeals to protect the life of British author Salman Rushdie,
whose new novel led to the Britain-Iran dispute.
   Iran's official radio said Britain must bear responsibility for
``the sacred wrath of Moslems'' as a result of its stance on the
book, ``The Satanic Verses.''
   A conservative Roman Catholic bishop in the Netherlands joined
Moslems in denouncing the book, saying it ``defiled'' the figure of
Mohammed.
   Spain's national EFE news agency quoted intelligence sources as
saying an Iranian commando team recently was in that country trying
to obtain weapons, apparently to kill Rushdie and collect a $5.2
million bounty offered by Iranian clerics.
   An Interior Ministry official cast doubt on the report, which
also said the team had dispersed and infiltrated Britain, West
Germany and France. Officials in Britain said they had no
information to confirm the report.
   Critics of ``The Satanic Verses'' say it blasphemes Islam by
portraying Mohammed's wives as prostitutes and insinuating Mohammed
wrote the Koran himself rather than receiving it from God.
   The book led Iran to break relations with Britain on Tuesday.
Britain, in turn, announced Wednesday it plans to expel ``a number''
of Iranians because of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's refusal to
revoke his death sentence against Rushdie.
   The author, a British citizen who was born into a Moslem family,
has been in hiding since the Feb. 14 execution order.
   ``I can confirm to you that the names of nine Iranian individuals
have been sent over to the FCO (Foreign and Commonwealth Office),''
a spokesman for the Home Office, the department responsible for
immigration, said Thursday.
   ``This would be to initiate the proceedings to secure their
removal,'' he said, speaking anonymously in keeping with British
custom. When asked if they were former embassy employees who no
longer have diplomatic status, he said, ``I can confirm that.''
   About 25,000 Iranians live in Britain, including 2,400 students.
   According to the Spanish news report, seven Iranians were tracked
in Spain more than 10 days ago. It quoted intelligence sources as
saying the group apparently tried but failed to obtain weapons in
Spain to kill Rushdie.
   Spain's Secretary of State for Security, Rafael Vera, told The
Associated Press, ``There has been an error in the way the
information has been given.'' He refused to elaborate.
   Perez de Cuellar, in Nepal as part of an Asian trip, told
reporters it is important not to dramatize the issue but to make
appeals to ensure the death order is not carried out.
   ``I have already made more than one appeal in order to protect
the life of this gentleman who authored the book. But, at the same
time, I was sad to see that expressions were written which were
offensive for millions of Moslem people all over the world,'' he
added.
   Tehran Radio, in a commentary monitored by the British
Broadcasting Corp., declared that ``this is just the beginning of
the path for Iran, as well as for other world Moslems.''
   ``In the event that Britain does not want to abandon its improper
and anti-Islamic posture and does not make a retreat in this regard,
it must reciprocally bear liability for everything that is to follow
henceforth.
   ``The sacred wrath of Moslems will not subside through the
expulsion of some Iranian Moslems from Britain or by closing down
the Iranian consulate in Hong Kong,'' Tehran Radio said.
   Bishop H.J.A. Bomers of the Netherlands gave unexpected support
to Moslems in an interview with Dutch radio Thursday.
   Bomers, who conceded he had not read ``The Satanic Verses,'' said
Khomeini's threat was ``totally wrong'' but added, ``It is not the
Moslem protesters'' who are to blame for the furor over Rushdie's
book.
   ``You can't just go and defile a historic figure who is believed
and respected by millions of people today,'' Bomers said in a
reference to the prophet Mohammed.
   Iraq's president, Saddam Hussein, made his first public statement
on the controversy, telling a newspaper Khomeini's death threat
``does more damage to Islam than Salman Rushdie's book.'' He was
quoted by the Saudi newspaper Al-Sharq Al-Awsat.
</TEXT>
