<HEAD>Bush Kicks Off Anti-Drug Crusade</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Adds new last graf to show Bush cut New York speech short</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush served notice Thursday to
cop-killing drug traffickers that ``hunting season is over'' and
said he is determined to attack the nation's drug problem on both
the supply and demand fronts.
   Kicking off what the White House has billed as ``drug week,''
Bush flew to New York to pay tribute to Drug Enforcement
Administration agents killed in the line of duty.
   Bush, who headed a drug interdiction task force as vice
president, told his audience at the DEA's New York offices that ``it
used to be unthinkable to shoot a cop.''
   But heightened pressure against drug traffickers has raised the
level of violence, he said, citing the recent slaying of DEA agent
Everett Hatcher.
   Just before his speech, Bush met with Hatcher's widow, Mary Jane
Hatcher.
   Later, Bush used an address to the United Negro College Fund to
sound his anti-drug theme.
   ``My friends, drug abuse is America's 20th Century version of
human slavery,'' Bush said. ``It chains the spirit and imperils the
ability to learn.''
   He vowed to wage ``unconditional war'' against drug abuse and
said, ``We must fight on every front: education, treatment,
interdiction, enforcement.''
   Bush had been scheduled to kick off his anti-drug crusade Tuesday
with appearances in Lancaster, Pa., and Wilmington, Del., but bad
weather forced the cancellation of that trip.
   In Thursday's speech to drug enforcement officers, the president
cited legislation passed by Congress last year providing the death
penalty for drug kingpins who commit murder while trafficking in
drugs.
   ``Just as the penalty for cop killers helps even the odds,
stripping our enemies of their ill-gotten gains turns the table in a
dramatic and highly effective way,'' he said, adding:
   ``I have some bad news for the bad guys: Hunting season is over.
The rules on our side have changed too. It's about time.''
   ``Here in New York City, as in other cities across the country,
the war on drugs is no metaphor,'' he said. ``Before we could bury
Everett Hatcher last week, another officer was gunned down, felled
by a single shot fired point-blank beneath his bullet-proof vest.''
   ``Today, narcotics agents are sometimes the first ones shot,
targeted by criminals armed with a staggering array of battlefield
weaponry,'' he said.
   Nine DEA agents have been killed in the line of duty since 1982.
   Bush, who has opposed strict gun controls and who has defended
the right of sportsmen and hunters to have semiautomatic rifles, did
say in his speech that he has asked William Bennett, his drug policy
coordinator, to ``look into what can be done to prevent fully
automatic assault weapons from falling into the hands of the
criminals you face.''
   In choosing New York to launch his drug campaign, Bush went to a
city with an estimated 260,000 heroin addicts and 600,000 people
believed addicted to cocaine.
   On Feb. 9, Bush asked Congress for $5.5 billion for the war on
drugs, with the bulk of that going to law enforcement efforts,
including intensified border interdiction.
   At the same time, he is trying to put pressure on law enforcement
officials and leaders in other countries to staunch the flow of
drugs to the United States. Bush noted that he will soon receive a
report from Attorney General Dick Thornburgh on his just-completed
trip to Bolivia, Colombia and Peru.
   In an apparent jab at Democratic Gov. Mario Cuomo, Bush noted
that ``it's been over 25 years since anyone has faced the death
penalty in this state.'' The state legislature is oving to enact a
death penalty statute, which Cuomo opposes.
   ``While there may not be light at the end of the tunnel, there
does seem to be some light coming in under the door,'' the president
said. ``At the Apollo Theater in Harlem one Wednesday last month,
the amateur night performances were interrupted by spontaneous
anti-drug messages from the stage and chants from the crowd.''
   In the text of his speech to the United Negro College Fund, Bush
also discussed the importance of education, telling his audience,
``Education can give minorities a greater voice _ and make sure that
voice is heard.''
   The president also quoted slain civil right leader Martin Luther
King Jr.'s words that ``injustice anywhere is a threat to justice
everywhere.''
   The president declared:
   ``Black and white, together _ we know that America will not be a
good place for any of us to live until it is a good place for all of
us to live.'' r, Insert,000
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Bush cut his New York speech short, quipping that ``the Senate is
still meeting and my dog is expecting.'' He only read about half the
speech. The program had been running behind schedule.
</TEXT>
