<FIRST>r a AM-HaitianWave     03-09 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Haitian Wave,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Coast Guard Intercepts 236 More Haitians</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Coast Guard intercepted 236 more Haitians
sailing to the United States on Wednesday, bringing to more than 550
the number of refugees stopped and sent back home since Sunday.
   The latest refugees were packed onto two Haitian sailboats
stopped by Coast Guard cutters about 30 miles north of Haiti, Coast
Guard spokesman Jerry Snyder said.
   U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service agents interviewed
the refugees on board the cutters and ordered them returned to
Port-au-Prince after deciding they were trying to enter the United
States for economic reasons, Snyder said.
   Two separate Haitian refugee groups attacked the INS procedure
Wednesday, claiming many Haitians who fear political persecution are
unjustly returned to their country.
   ``There is an automatic assumption that Haitians are economic
refugees,'' said Haitian Refugee Center attorney Cheryl Little at a
news conference in Miami's Little Haiti community.
   The New York-based National Coalition for Haitian Refugees
released a report criticizing the INS for interviewing Haitians in
international waters rather than inside the United States.
   ``The boat people intercepted on the high seas, ignorant of their
rights and fearful of repercussions should they testify to political
repression, are denied this opportunity,'' the 12-page report said.
   ``Many of the passengers on those few boats that do reach the
United States safely, when informed of their rights and given
adequate private interviews, ask for political asylum.''
   Leon Jennings, chief interdiction officer for the INS in Miami,
said ``nobody is ever sent back without asking them if they're
afraid. ... We're there to find out if anybody is going to be
persecuted.''
   The Coast Guard intercepted 113 Haitians on two 30-foot wooden
sailboats in international waters Tuesday off Fort Lauderdale and
Miami. Then 202 migrants aboard the Coast Guard cutter Bear were
returned to Haiti late Tuesday.
   The latest wave of refugees was caused by false rumors
circulating throughout Haiti last weekend that U.S. interdiction and
immigration policies were being relaxed, INS and Coast Guard
officials said.
   The Coast Guard has intercepted 837 Haitian migrants since
January 1.
</TEXT>
