<FIRST>r a AM-AvalancheSurvivor     03-09 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Avalanche Survivor,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Avalanche Survivor Ordered To Pay More Than $3,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A first-year ski instructor who
survived an avalanche that killed two friends while they were skiing
out-of-bounds must pay more than $3,000 in fines and costs and make
public safety announcements.
   U.S. Magistrate Jill Clifton sentenced Todd Richards, 23, after
he pleaded no contest Wednesday to a charge of skiing out-of-bounds.
   Richards survived the avalanche near the Telluride Ski Area on
Feb. 14 with minor injuries, but Anthony Shelley of New Zealand and
Paul Wolfort of Telluride were killed.
   Richards, who returned to Grand Junction from his home in
Chelmsford, Mass., to enter his plea, admitted he and his two
companions illegally entered an area known as ``Temptation Gulch.''
   ``I ducked a rope'' marking the area as out-of-bounds, Richards
said.
   ``I almost lost my life, I lost two friends, I lost my dignity, I
lost my job, skiing privileges, hundreds of dollars worth of ski
equipment, thousands of dollars in costs,'' Richards said. ``I just
want to go home.''
   His attorney, William Harmsen, said Richards will make a
safe-skiing public safety message for the U.S. Forest Service and
that he already has spoken to students at Telluride High School
about the dangers of skiing out-of-bounds.
   Richards said he also is writing letters to editors about safe
skiing.
   His sentence includes paying $3,090 to various agencies for the
costs of his rescue and the recovery of the bodies of his friends
and a $2 fine for skiing out-of-bounds, as well as a $10 victims'
fund fee.
</TEXT>
