<FIRST>r a AM-Tonys-Robbins     03-09 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tonys-Robbins,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Jerome Robbins' Broadway' Eligible for Best Musical Tony</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Jerome Robbins' Broadway,'' the biggest hit of
the theater season, can be nominated for best musical, but its
choreography, sets and costumes are ineligible for prizes, the Tony
Awards administration committee ruled Thursday.
   The 24-member committee also determined that Robbins' direction
of the show, a cavalcade of dances from 11 of his old musicals, is
eligible for a nomination as is the new lighting designed by
Jennifer Tipton.
   Tony Awards can help a show at the box office, particularly a
play. Last season's best-play winner, ``M. Butterfly,'' didn't start
to sell out until it had won the top award.
   ``Jerome Robbins' Broadway,'' an $8 million musical, includes
scenes from Robbins' productions from ``On the Town'' in 1944 to
``Fiddler on the Roof'' in 1964.
   In declining to allow nominations for the show's choreography,
sets and costumes, the committee said they ``substantially
duplicated those in other productions.''
   The administration committee consists of 10 members of the League
of American Theaters and Producers, 10 members of the American
Theater Wing and four members of the stage unions.
   Harvey Sabinson, executive director of the league, called the
meeting ``cordial and very measured. There was no hysteria.''
   Some members of the theater community had predicted a fierce
battle over eligibility for ``Jerome Robbins' Broaday'' between the
Shubert Organization, which co-produced the Robbins show, and the
Nederlander Organization, which runs the theater where another
potential musical nominee, ``Black and Blue,'' is playing.
   The Tony nominations will be announced May 8 and the awards given
on June 4.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
