<FIRST>r i AM-Thailand-Kidnapping     03-09 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thailand-Kidnapping,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Businessman Kidnapped In Laos Rescued In Thailand</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police raided a kidnappers' hideout
Wednesday night, rescuing a Japanese business executive and killing
two of the men who abducted him a week ago in neighboring Laos,
authorities said Thursday.
   Yoshiaki Asao, 61, was abducted by four gunmen March 1 in the
Laotian capital of Vientiane, where he was branch manager of the
trading firm Mitsui and Co. The intruders seized him at his home
after tying up his wife, Michiko, and two maids.
   Asao was rescued in Thailand's Loei province, which is just to
the west of Nong Khai, a border town that is a main trading and
social link between Thailand and Communist-ruled Laos. Loei is about
270 miles northeast of Bangkok.
   It was not immediately known what happened to the other two
kidnappers.
   Mitsui and Co. Vice President Minoru Nakamura told a news
conference in Tokyo that there was no ransom demand and ``no contact
at all'' with the kidnappers. But Japan's Kyodo News Service,
quoting a source in Bangkok, said the kidnappers demanded $2.8
million.
   Japan established diplomatic relations with Laos in 1976, the
year after the Communists seized power in the landlocked Southeast
Asian nation.
   The kidnapping came at a time when Laos has been trying to
attract investment from the capitalist countries in a bid to develop
one of the world's poorest economies.
</TEXT>
