<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Lebanon     03-09 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Lebanon,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Protests To Israel Over Closing Of Border</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN AYON LEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Nations has protested Israel's
temporary closing of the Lebanon-Israeli border to U.N. peacekeeping
troops, U.N. officials said Wednesday.
   Israel closed the border for nearly 20 hours, from Tuesday
afternoon until Wednesday morning.
   ``This unacceptable action was stated to be in retaliation'' for
an incident Tuesday in which U.N. peacekeeping troops blocked
Israeli army vehicles from entering the village of Ebel es Saqi,
said Nadia Younes, spokeswoman for Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar.
   Ms. Younes said that under a longstanding informal agreement, the
Israeli army is barred from deploying vehicles in Ebel es Saqi,
where the headquarters of the Norwegian battalion of the U.N.
Interim Force in Lebanon are located.
   The Israel Defense Forces ``challenged UNIFIL's action and a
tense situation ensued,'' during which an Israeli tank was used to
force U.N. vehicles off the road, said Ms. Younes.
   Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin said at a military base in
northern Israel on Wednesday: ``We have said time and again, when it
comes to UNIFIL, that we don't ask them to stay here, we don't ask
them to leave, but at the same time we will not allow any change in
their deployment and any interference by UNIFIL to the freedom of
movement of the IDF. This is the way that we see it.''
   The peacekeeping troops of the U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon
patrol a narrow strip north of Israel's self-declared ``security
zone,'' which forms a buffer zone between northern Israeli
settlements and Shiite and Palestinian guerrilla bases in Lebanon.
   Last month, the commander of the Norwegian battalion compared
Israeli army actions in south Lebanon to Nazi tactics in World War
II. Israel demanded his removal because of the comment.
   Israel and a Christian-dominated militia it backs, the South
Lebanon Army, prevent UNIFIL from controlling much of the area in
southern Lebanon that it is supposed to watch over.
   UNIFIL deploys about 5,800 men from Fiji, Finland, France, Ghana,
Ireland, Italy, Nepal, Norway and Sweden.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890309-0198 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 2222EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Tibet 2ndLd-Writethru a0729 03-09 0850</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tibet, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0729,0878</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foreigners Expelled From Lhasa, Troops Reportedly Round Up Tibetans</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUB grafs 6-7, `Several foreigners...' with four grafs UPDATING
with Friday developments. Pick up 8th pvs, `She said...' with minor editing
to trim</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TOK3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign tourists were expelled from Lhasa on
Thursday, and Chinese troops began rounding up Tibetans in the city
and hauling them away in trucks, a Tibetan woman said.
   China said four more people had died after suffering injuries
earlier this week in the Tibetan capital during bloody protests of
Chinese communist rule in the remote mountain region.
   The report brought the official death toll to 16. Western
travelers have quoted Tibetans as saying that many more have died.
Most Tibetans reportedly put the figure at between 20 and 30.
   Some Western tourists accused Chinese troops of atrocities, a
charge denied by a Foreign Ministry spokesman.
   ``They're grabbing everyone,'' said the Tibetan woman,
interviewed late Thursday by telephone from Beijing. ``Soldiers are
all over the place and they're grabbing everyone.''
   Another Tibetan woman said when contacted by telephone on Friday
that it was quiet with the army occupying ``all the roads. ... There
are new arrests. ... There are many, but we don't know how many.''
   A man came on the line and said: ``Don't talk a long time. There
are a lot of police. We can't talk long.''
   Several foreigners who work in Lhasa have been allowed to remain,
but foreign tourists, estimated at 140, were ordered to leave by
Thursday _ the eve of the 30th anniversary of a rebellion in Tibet.
   The first Tibetan woman, speaking from a hotel in the city, said
the last of them departed Thursday, some for the airport to wait for
a Friday flight to Chengdu, the capital of Sichuan province. Others
took a bus to neighboring Qinghai province or the Nepalese border,
she said.
   She said the soldiers then began rounding up Tibetans.
   ``Many people. It is many more than when the foreigners were
here. I can't speak to you, we are all afraid,'' she said.
   Tibetan women at two other hotels also said the foreigners had
left the city, and one seconded the report of detentions.
   Foreign reporters were barred from the city and there was no way
to confirm their observations independently.
   Western travelers who arrived in Chengdu on a flight from Lhasa
said Tibetans had feared mass arrests.
   ``People begged us repeatedly over the last few days _ `Tell the
world, help us, please,''' said an American from New Orleans, one of
40 foreigners on the flight.
   One group on the flight issued a statement they said would be
sent to the United Nations and the Dalai Lama, Tibet's spiritual
leader who fled China after the 1959 uprising.
   ``The world community should carefully and critically examine the
causes of this conflict and the methods and motives of the
authorities,'' said the statement, signed by 35 foreigners.
   ``Shootings by the authorities have been excessive,
unpredictable, indiscriminate and there have on occasion been
atrocities,'' it said.
   State-run radio reported the four additional riot-related deaths.
It said the people died in the hospital ``during emergency
life-saving procedures.'' The report did not say whether the dead
were Tibetans.
   During three days of riots that began Sunday, thousands of
Tibetans ransacked Chinese-owned shops and set fire to Chinese
property.
   China imposed martial law on the city of 70,000 at midnight
Tuesday, and thousands of troops moved in to set up checkpoints at
every block.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Li Zhaoxing on Thursday denied Chinese
authorities were violating human rights in Tibet. He blamed the
disturbances on a ``clique'' run by the Dalai Lama, who lives in
exile in India.
   The official Xinhua News Agency charged that members of ``a
separatist clique based abroad'' recently sneaked into Tibet with
weapons to instigate the riots, and said the protesters fired guns
``as they please.''
   Foreigners said demonstrators only threw rocks and used primitive
slingshots.
   The U.S. State Department on Wednesday said it recognized the
Chinese government's right to maintain order, but objected to the
``unwarranted use of lethal force'' against the protesters.
   Li said Thursday that China will not tolerate foreign meddling in
the situation.
   In a statement marking the anniversary of the 1959 uprising, the
Dalai Lama said from New Delhi that ``No amount of repression,
however brutal or violent, can silence the voice of freedom and
justice.''
   China claims Tibet has been an integral part of Chinese territory
for seven centuries. Most Tibetans maintain it was an independent
nation before the communists took over in 1949.
   The official media has given no figures on arrests, but the
Communist Party's official People's Daily reported from Lhasa how
police raided one home and pulled out a man screaming for leniency.
They then went next door and found a man hiding under a blanket,
according to the report.
   The man's wife was quoted as saying, ``Hurry up and dress and go
with them. I told you not to take part in the riots but you had to
anyway.''
</TEXT>
