<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Vet'sFast     03-09 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Vet's Fast,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>WWII Vet Ends 20-Day Fast Over Prince's Attendance Of Hirohito Funeral</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An elderly World War II veteran on Thursday ended a
20-day hunger strike protesting Prince Philip's attendance at
Emperor Hirohito's funeral after a second appeal from Buckingham
Palace.
   Anthony Burgess, 70, recently received a letter on behalf of
Queen Elizabeth II saying she was ``personally concerned'' and
asking him to reconsider, said a palace spokeswoman, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   ``Though Her Majesty fully appreciates the deep feelings which
have prompted you to take this course of action, she hopes that you
will reflect further and decide to end your fast,'' said the letter
written by the queen's private secretary, Sir William Heseltine.
   It said the queen decided to send her husband, Philip, to the
funeral for the Japanese emperor ``after receiving ministerial
advice that she should be represented by a senior member of her
family.''
   It added that she would be ``very sad'' if Burgess decided to
send back his war medals, as he had threatened to do.
   Burgess, who lives in Swansea, south Wales, stopped ingesting
anything but black tea last month to protest the visit of the
queen's husband to Hirohito's funeral Feb. 24.
   Veterans were angered that Philip, a veteran and patron of the
Burma Star veteran's association to which Burgess belongs, attended
the funeral of the man in whose name so many atrocities were
committed. He vowed to fast until Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher
and the prince apologized to soldiers.
   Burgess' condition was not known, but a friend and fellow
veteran, Ken Evans, said he was weak. He said the letter and the
concern of his relatives persuaded Burgess to stop his fast.
</TEXT>
