<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 0805EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WeekendTV-Newhart Adv10-12   03-09 0764</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekend TV-Newhart, Adv 10-12,0788</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv10-12</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, March 10-12, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bob Newhart and Don Rickles Take Friendship to TV</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Even mild-mannered Bob Newhart could take only
so many slings and arrows from insult artist Don Rickles.
   Newhart, as Dick Loudon on CBS' ``Newhart,'' blew up and called
Rickles ``fat and bald.''
   ``He picks on me and picks on me, and I finally blow up,'' said
Newhart, after the cast broke for lunch. But the tiff was only in
the script, and he and Rickles headed for Newhart's dressing room
together.
   Off camera, the quiet, introspective Newhart and the loud,
explosive Rickles are a real ``odd couple'' as best friends. Their
wives are also best friends, and the two couples frequently vacation
together.
   Rickles' appearance on this Monday's episode of ``Newhart'' is
one of their rare times together on the same stage. He plays
out-of-work comic actor Don Prince who ends up as host of a talk
show on the same Vermont television station where Loudon works.
   Their last joint appearance was in 1972 on an episode of ``The
Don Rickles Show.'' Rickles said it was on the same soundstage at
the CBS-MTM Studios where ``Newhart'' is filmed.
   ``A guy who's a grip says it was the same stage,'' said Newhart.
``Painful things like that you can't recall.''
   ``We've always talked about appearing together on `Newhart' for
some time, but we wanted it to be something special,'' said Rickles.
   ``I said in TV Guide that we hadn't been able to come up with an
idea. We got hundreds of letters saying he should do this, he should
do that,'' said Newhart. ``The story our writers came up with is
that Don had his own show on CBS called `It's Always Moishe.' He did
a special called `A Very Moishe Christmas.' When he gets canceled he
comes to Vermont to do a talk show. I'm like his Ed McMahon. He
insults me, the band leader, the audience.''
   That's when Newhart has had enough to bark back. But he quickly
apologizes and Rickles confesses he's been insulting everybody to
get out of his contract, because CBS wants to put ``It's Always
Moishe'' back on the air.
   Newhart and Rickles have been friends for more than 21 years.
   ``Our wives were friends before he even knew his wife,'' said
Rickles, whose wife, Barbara, had been a secretary for his agent.
Newhart's wife, Ginny Quinn, had been an actress.
   ``We had completely different personalities but we have the same
values,'' Rickles said. ``We could travel and get along. We get
along great and have never had any troubles. It's all due to me.''
   Newhart said, ``Ginny and I were in Las Vegas and she had never
seen his act. She said Barbara, Don's wife, was there and suggested
we get together. She said Don was such a nice man. I warned her he
may not be the same nice man on stage.
   ``We went to the show and he said, `Bob Newhart is a stammering
idiot and his wife is a former hooker from Bayonne, N.J.' Ginny's
mouth was wide open the rest of the show.''
   Newhart and Rickles say they never talk about work or show
business. What do they talk about?
   Newhart: ``His career.''
   Rickles: ``My golf and my good shots.''
   ``He makes me laugh and I make him laugh,'' said Newhart.
   Said Rickles: ``We come from different backgrounds. He was a man
for the books. I'm trying to read them.''
   Newhart's wife has suggested they do Neil Simon's play ``The Odd
Couple.''
   ``Don is the neat one,'' Newhart said. ``It's the opposite of
what you would think.''
   ``It's been done so many times,'' said Rickles. ``I did it once
with Ernest Borgnine. We did it in the round with the audience all
around us.''
   Rickles works mostly in Las Vegas and Atlantic City and is an
occasional guest on ``The Tonight Show,'' ``Late Night With David
Letterman,'' or the Bob Hope specials.
   His first movie was ``Run Silent, Run Deep'' in 1958 and last
movie was ``Kelly's Heroes'' in 1970. In the 1970s, he starred in
the short-lived sitcom ``The Don Rickles Show'' and ``C.P.O.
Sharkey,'' which ran for two years.
   ``When I started doing my nightclub act I developed a very strong
image,'' Rickles said. ``Producers began to back off. It also became
very hard for me to do both. I'm not out there as a working actor.
I'm not looking for work.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, March 10-12</NOTE>
</DOC>
