<FIRST>r f PM-HeinzModernization     03-09 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Heinz Modernization,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>Board Approves $90 Million Plant Modernization</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   H.J. Heinz Co. said its board of directors has
approved its largest-ever spending plan, which was contingent on
union ratification of a five-year labor contract.
   The approval of a $90 million modernization of its Pittsburgh
factory came after Local 325 of the United Food &amp; Commercial Workers
Union, representing 980 workers, last Friday ratified a five-year
labor contract. The pact provides moderate wage increases and
cost-of-living protection.
   ``We are now ready to move forward with the largest single
capital investment in Heinz U.S.A.'s 120-year history, a project
that will make us more competitive and also provide employees with
much greater job security in the future,'' David Sculley, president
of Heinz U.S.A., said Wednesday.
   The restructuring involves converting the existing warehouse
building at the company's North Side complex to a state-of-the-art
manufacturing facility for soups and baby food and constructing a
new warehouse and a separate cold storage facility.
   Heinz pushed for a contract long enough to ensure labor peace and
continued production during the estimated four-year construction
period.
   The factory employs about 1,000 workers. Heinz expects employment
to drop to about 700 to 750 workers, mostly through attrition, once
construction is completed.
 
</TEXT>
</DOC>
