<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 0231EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Women'sWork Bjt   03-09 0671</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Women's Work, Bjt,0692</SECOND>
<HEAD>Feminist Causes Stir With Business Review Article About Woman Managers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A feminist who works to advance career
opportunities for women caused a stir by writing in the Harvard
Business Review that female managers cost corporations more than
male ones do.
   Felice N. Schwartz also urged employers to recognize two kinds of
woman managers: those who put their careers first and those who care
more about their children.
   ``The cost of employing women in management is greater than the
cost of employing men,'' Ms. Schwartz wrote in the review's
January-February issue in her article, ``Management Women and the
New Facts of Life.''
   ``This is a jarring statement, partly because it is true, but
mostly because it is something people are reluctant to talk about,''
she wrote.
   Published by Harvard Business School, the review has 210,000
subscribers, about 95 percent of them in business. Since the issue
was published, furious debate has ensued, said managing editor Alan
Webber. Woman managers are talking about it at business conferences
and the magazine has received a dozen letters. ``It struck a
nerve,'' he said.
   While many readers, men and women alike, applaud Ms. Schwartz
boldness, some protest that it is damaging to women.
   ``Everybody's very troubled by it,'' U.S. Rep. Patricia
Schroeder, D-Colo., said Wednesday in an interview from Washington.
   The article gives ammunition to those opposed to women's
advancement, Ms. Schroeder said.
   ``There's nothing they love more. If you can find a woman who can
say `We don't deserve equal pay' they love it,'' the congresswoman
said. ``Women have really felt in the '80s they were really going
backward anyway, and this gives the aura of the seal of approval of
the Harvard Business School. That's the tragedy.''
   Webber, however, said the reaction he has received generally
touches on two themes. ``A lot of people say it is a mistake to
categorize the issue as a women's issue, that it's a family issue.
... Younger men who are interested, as a generation, in raising
children are facing pressures not unlike those facing women,'' he
said.
   Other letter-writers said they were glad someone opened debate on
the subject. ``It's been kind of a dirty little secret,'' Webber
said.
   Richard Lewis, chairman of Corporate Annual Reports Inc., wrote
to the review that the article is ``a historical turning point in
the discussion of women in business.''
   Ms. Schwartz is founder and president of Catalyst, a non-profit
research and advisory group in New York that works with corporations
to foster career and leadership development of women.
   A self-described social advocate for 45 years, Ms. Schwartz said
she is the mother of three sons and has four grandchildren, all of
them in two-career families.
   In the article, Ms. Schwartz said heightened sensitivity to
charges of sexism, as well as fear of confrontation and lawsuits,
prevent people from discussing the matter.
   Only a minority of women put their careers first, but they must
be cultivated, the article asserts. At the same time, women serious
about both their careers and their families can provide corporations
with flexibility through job-sharing and part-time work, even if it
slows the women's progress up the ladder, it says.
   In an interview from New York, Ms. Schwartz said ruefully that
those who attack her ideas need to read her article more closely.
   Her point was that corporations need to adjust to demographic
facts: ``There are not enough good men to go around,'' she said
   She disagreed that corporate executives would use her article as
an excuse to keep women back. ``What they want is the best and the
brightest to come to their companies. They're not looking for
excuses,'' she said.
   ``We're trying to educate employers that it makes good business
sense to accommodate women who want to reach out'' _ women who want
to take a career break to bear and raise children, she said.
   ``I want corporate America to realize that women cost more ...
but it's a short-term cost.''
</TEXT>
