<FIRST>r f PM-TimeWarner-Networks Bjt   03-09 0635</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Time Warner-Networks, Bjt,0655</SECOND>
<HEAD>Major TV Networks Say Time Warner Deal Shows Importance of Deregulation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The major commercial television networks are
pointing to the merger pact between Time Inc. and Warner
Communications Inc. to support their campaign for relaxed federal
regulation of program ownership.
   But independent television stations, who have become a much
stronger competitor for the ABC, CBS and NBC networks in recent
years, say deregulation would unfairly skew the competition for
programming in favor of the networks.
   One of the motivations cited for the Time-Warner combination was
an interest in keeping pace with what is quickly becoming a global
market for media and entertainment companies.
   Time, a leader in magazine publishing, cable networks and cable
system operations, has the potential to provide more outlets for
Warner's entertainment production units, including its movie and
television studios.
   The networks say they share the ambition to compete in the global
marketplace, but are hamstrung by a court decree limiting the amount
of prime-time programming they may produce and federal regulations
forbidding them from having a financial interest in the other shows
they run.
   ``The Time-Warner agreement is a vivid example of how greatly the
media world has changed,'' said Cory Dunham, general counsel for the
National Broadcasting Co. ``But by government regulation, the
networks can't participate in this evolution.''
   George Schweitzer, a spokesman for CBS Inc., said, ``Those we
compete with and are in the same business are free to think of any
competitive situation they want ... They are free to grow their
business and we are not.''
   Under terms of a 9-year-old court consent decree due to expire
next year, the television networks may produce no more than five
hours of their own prime-time entertainment programming.
   Even at that, the networks have shown little inclination to
produce their own shows. ABC's ``Moonlighting'' was recently placed
on hiatus, but the other two networks have none of their own shows
on their prime-time schedules.
   Separately, the networks are prohibited from having a financial
interest in other shows they run or sharing in the proceeds from the
syndication of network shows for reruns under terms of Federal
Communications Commission rules adopted nearly 20 years ago.
   In addition, there are rules that prohibit networks from
packaging their own programs with programs others produce and
selling them here or abroad.
   The networks and Hollywood studios have been negotiating
privately for months on reaching a compromise on the issue of
federal regulation of networks.
   The networks argue that their dominance of the television market
has slipped since the FCC rules were enacted.
   As of last November, the three networks' share of the prime-time
audience fell to 68 percent from 92 percent in the 1978-79 season,
according to Nielsen Media Research. Network executives say they
expect their combined share may fall even further.
   NBC's Dunham said the networks are not so much interested in
being able to buy a studio as they are in being able to invest in
new productions and to buy and package programs for distribution
abroad.
   ``To be a viable player in this business, you need to be a player
in the businesses that make it up,'' he said.
   But the movie studios and the independent television stations
argue that the networks simply want to strengthen an already strong
market position.
   Lawrence Laurent, a spokesman for the Association of Independent
Television Stations, said before the financial interest rules were
enacted the networks withheld their most popular shows from the
syndication market or sold them first to their own stations and
their own network affiliates.
   Enactment of the rules allowed independents to compete more
effectively for popular shows, a position they don't want to
relinquish. ``It's very difficult to depend on your competitor for
programming,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890309-0227 </DOCNO>
