<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     03-09 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Plunge, Dollar Gains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices plunged on the Tokyo Stock Exchange
today amid political uncertainties and economic rumors, while the
dollar gained against the Japanese yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 181.21 points, or 0.57
percent, closing at 31,656.45.
   The market's main barometer, a 100.28-point loser Wednesday, made
moderate gains in today's early trading following gains on overseas
markets overnight, but then turned downward.
   ``Trading was inactive as investors stepped off to the sidelines
in the absence of market-affecting incentives today,'' said a dealer
with Nomura Securities, Japan's largest brokerage.
   Uncertainties over how Japanese politics will be affected by a
major stock-profiteering scandal, in which prosecutors have arrested
12 people, also discouraged many investors, said the dealer,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Two of the arrests came Wednesday, and opposition parties began
boycotting budget debates in Parliament, demanding that Prime
Minister Noboru Takeshita's Cabinet resign or at least submit
documents to clarify the involvement of leading politicians in the
scandal.
   The Nomura dealer added that price declines in afternoon trading
followed a rumor that the Bank of Japan might raise interest rates.
   In thin trading, first section volume was estimated at 800
million shares.
   The dealer predicted that the inactive trend would continue at
least until February's U.S. employment figures are released Friday.
   In currency dealings, the dollar closed at 129.23 yen, up 0.50
yen from Wednesday's 128.73-yen finish. It opened at 129.32 yen and
ranged between 129.10 yen and 129.40 yen.
   Currency trading was also inactive before the U.S. employment
report, said a dealer with Daiwa Bank in Tokyo, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   ``Although the dollar-yen rate moved little, the market sentiment
was toward a stronger dollar, especially after the comment (by U.S.
Council of Economic Advisers Chairman Michael Boskin) that indicated
a possible tax raise in the United States,'' he added.
   Speaking before a congressional committee, Boskin said the
administration of President Bush has ``not ruled out a discussion''
of taxes as part of budget negotiations with Congress.
   ``The dollar-yen rate has been moving in `a box range' between
128.50 yen and 129.50 yen in recent dealings, but the market expects
central bank intervention if the dollar gets stronger,'' the dealer
said.
</TEXT>
