<HEAD>Dollar Higher, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was higher in early European trading
today. Gold prices fell.
   Foreign currency dealers said they expected little movement
before Friday's release of U.S. unemployment figures for February.
   ``The market is without direction and is waiting for some new
signals either to take it (the dollar) up or down,'' said one trader
in Rome.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.50 yen to a closing 129.23. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 129.30 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Wednesday's
rates, included: 1.8623 West German marks, up from 1.8585; 1.5905
Swiss francs, up from 1.5865; 6.3145 French francs, up from 6.3080;
2.1015 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0930; 1,366.50 Italian lire, up
from 1,363.20; 1.1985 Canadian dollars, down from 1.20155.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7165, cheaper for buyers
than $1.7200 Wednesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $392.40 a troy ounce,
down from $393.80 bid late Wednesday. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $392.50.
   In Zurich, the bid price was also $392.50, down from $394.75 bid
late Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 55 cents to close at a bid
$393.51.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.87 a troy ounce,
down from Wednesday's $5.91.
</TEXT>
