<FIRST>r f PM-Streep-Alar     03-09 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Streep-Alar,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>Apple Industry Strikes Back At Actress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Meryl Streep says her national
television appearances warning against eating chemically treated
apples doesn't mean she's ``beating up on farmers.''
   But the Washington apple industry blasted the movie star
Wednesday, saying her involvement in a nationwide controversy on the
chemical Alar is hurting growers.
   ``Three years ago movie actresses were spilling all over the
place trying to save the family farm,'' said Chris Schlect, an
industry lobbyist based in Yakima. ``Now we have actresses going out
trying to destroy agriculture.''
   Schlect, head of the Northwest Horticultural Council, said the
Academy Award-winning actress has credibility because of her movie
roles but, ``It doesn't make her a scientist or expert on
nutrition.''
   Ms. Streep, a founder of the group Mothers and Others for
Pesticide Limits, told The Associated Press her lack of scientific
training was not the issue.
   ``I'm not a scientist so I have to go with the best information
available,'' she said. ``I eat them and I feed them (to my three
children) so I am involved in the apple issue.''
   ``I'm not interested in beating up on farmers,'' Ms. Streep said.
``I'm interested in farmers being supported to grow in ways not
threatening to health.''
   Although the safety of Alar has been debated for years, the
latest controversy was stirred last month because of a report by the
Natural Resources Defense Council.
   The council, a non-profit consumer group, projected that 5,500 to
6,200 preschoolers eventually would get cancer because of childhood
exposure to six to eight chemicals used in fruits and vegetables.
   It found the greatest risk from UDMH, a breakdown product of
Alar. The council estimated that the average preschooler's cancer
risk was approximately one case for every 4,000 preschoolers exposed
to UDMH.
   The report has been attacked by some scientists and the U.S.
Environmental Protection Agency as misleading and alarmist, although
the agency did announce plans to ban Alar by 1990.
   Fears of a consumer backlash have prompted the apple industry to
severely cut its use of Alar. The grower-financed Washington Apple
Commission says only about 5 percent of total apple acreage is
treated.
   Washington is the nation's largest apple producer, growing about
half of all supermarket apples.
   Ms. Streep, whose group is affiliated with the council, has
appeared on shows like ``Today'' and ``Donahue,'' denouncing the use
of Alar and calling on farmers to reduce chemical use.
   The controversy showed no signs of easing Wednesday as the New
York Board of Education said it has barred the sale of apples in
school cafeterias.
   To combat the negative publicity, the Apple Commission announced
it was spending $1 million on full-page advertisements that will
appear Friday in New York, Washington, D.C., and Los Angeles papers,
as well as USA Today, spokeswoman Vicky Scharlau said.
   The ads will say that Alar is used only sparingly, that its
health threat isn't proven and that the benefits of eating apples
far outweigh any risks.
   Alar is not a pesticide. It is a chemical growth regulator
sprayed on trees to improve the color and firmness of apples,
extending shelf life and the harvest period. Because it works
internally, Alar cannot be washed off like other chemicals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890309-0231 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 0757EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-FamilyIncome     03-09 0602</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Family Income,0624</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blacks, Hispanics Trail in Income Growth</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blacks and Hispanics missed out on the rise in
median family income to $30,850 in 1987, the highest real level
since the string of recessions that began 14 years earlier, the
Census Bureau says.
   In a report released Wednesday, the bureau said the 1987 median
family income figure was 1 percent higher than the previous year's
and represented the fifth consecutive annual increase.
   Since 1982, the figure has grown nearly 12 percent, the report
said.
   ``These recent increases have brought real median family income
comparable to that of 1973, a year when median family income reached
an all-time high before a series of recessions resulted in
substantial declines in family income,'' the report said.
   Overall, white families increased their median income by 1.1
percent from 1986 to 1987, according to the report ``Money Income of
Households, Families and Persons in the United States: 1987.''
   The 1987 median income of white families was $32,274, up from
$31,935 a year earlier, the report said.
   By comparison, median income for black familes was $18,098, down
from $18,247, while for Hispanics the median fell to $20,306 from
$20,726, according to the study. The study is an expanded version of
an analysis released in August that found nearly one-third of all
black Americans living in poverty.
   While the earlier report detailed the poverty status of various
segments of society, the new edition contains extensive detail on
income for differing groups.
   Among family groups, the highest incomes were reported for white
married couples at $35,295, up from $34,647. Black married couples
saw their median income fall from $27,554 to $27,182, while for
Hispanic couples there was a drop from $24,786 to $24,677.
   White families maintained by a woman with no husband present had
an income increase from $16,290 to $17,018.
   Black female householders reported an increase from $9,640 to
$9,710. Among Hispanics the median for this group edged up from
$9,777 to $9,805.
   The biggest income gain by education was for people with one to
three years of college. Families headed by people in this category
saw their incomes rise from $35,455 to $36,392.
   Ranked by education, families headed by people with more than
five years of college still had the highest income at $54,491, but
that was down a bit, from $54,595. And for those with four years of
college, income fell from $47,269 to $46,533.
   High school grads saw a 0.6 percent increase from $29,765 to
$29,937, while income for families headed by those with some high
school education climbed from $20,854 to $21,265. Family income for
those with no high school education fell from $14,616 to $14,547.
   Regionally, Southerners led in income gains, with median family
income rising from $27,684 to $28,250, up 2.0 percent.
   Despite having the largest gain, Southerners continue to have the
nation's lowest median income.
   In the Northeast, the rise was 1.8 percent, from $33,335 to
$33,938, and in the Midwest, 1.1 percent, from $30,665 to $30,991.
In the West, median income slipped 0.2 percent from $32,096 to
$32,026.
   By residence, the greatest gain was 3.6 percent for families
living in the suburbs of cities with less than 1 million people.
Their income rose from $32,034 to $33,192.
   Rural residents were next, increasing their incomes 1.3 percent,
from $24,078 to $24,397. Large-city suburbanites had income growth
of 1.1 percent from $39,850 to $40,270.
   Inner-city residents of large cities had an income drop from
$27,654 to $27,458, while families in smaller inner cities saw their
income dip from $27,614 to $27,294.
   Median is the middle number in a series.
</TEXT>
