<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 0758EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BrokeCounty     03-09 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Broke County,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Taxpayers Coughing Up Bucks Voluntarily To Help Strapped County</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORREST CITY, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents concerned about a financial
crisis that threatens mass layoffs of St. Francis County employees
have paid more than $100,000 in taxes in recent days, seven months
before they were due.
   ``I know it's unusual. I've never seen anybody come to the
collector's office without a (tax) statement to look me up and say,
`Here's the money,''' County Clerk Dick Krablin said Wednesday.
   ``It's great, although we are not out of the woods by any means.''
   The eastern Arkansas county, which has the state's highest
jobless rate, owes about $240,000 and has only about $20,000 in the
bank. Officials blamed the shortfall on the elimination of federal
revenue sharing and costs such as $106,000 in court-mandated jail
improvements.
   As a short-term solution to the crisis, county officials began
encouraging early tax payments on Friday, the day the Quorum Court
Budget Committee considered emergency spending cuts. The full court
is to vote Tuesday on other actions, including slashing payrolls by
50 percent.
   Without new money, the county can't meet a March 31 payroll.
   The county usually mails property tax statements from March to
June, and payments aren't due until Oct. 10. But to encourage early
payments, volunteers have crowded county offices each night to
stuff, sort and mail statements that include a letter pleading for
early remittance.
   About 9,000 out of 25,000 tax statements had been mailed by
Wednesday, and volunteers will work through the weekend, Krablin
said.
   ``But the money we've gotten so far _ gosh, $109,000 _ that's
from people who heard we had problems and just stepped right up to
help. We haven't advertised. It's just been media coverage and word
of mouth,'' Krablin said.
   The volunteers include two dozen county employees with a personal
stake in the fiscal crisis.
   Jerry Smith, chairman of the county office of the Cooperative
Extension Service, said he's faced with laying off about 10 of his
14 employees in a worst-case scenario.
   ``These courthouse employees are doing their dead-level best to
help,'' Smith said. ``They've been working hard, and we will keep
working.''
   If all of the taxes are paid promptly, about $4 million will be
generated, Krablin said.
   But the county general fund gets only 10 percent of the total,
with most obligated for schools. And Krablin said not everyone can
pay quickly because the county has been battered by industrial
layoffs, a slumping farm economy and the burden of Arkansas' highest
unemployment rate _ 23.4 percent in January.
   ``It's just going to be impossible for some people, and we don't
want to embarrass them,'' Krablin said. ``It is a voluntary
gesture.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
