<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern-Mood Bjt   03-09 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Mood, Bjt,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Striking Workers Encouraged By Solidarity of Three Unions</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Eastern Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SANDRA WALEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jerrell Sheppard has cleaned aircraft engines at
Eastern Airlines for the past five years and takes pride in a job
well done.
   Six months ago, he was in a car accident and was placed on
short-term disability at half pay. That stopped last month after a
company doctor said he could go back to work, but the letter from
the carrier authorizing his return never came.
   Now Sheppard, 43, is walking a Machinist picket line wearing a
neck brace. He has medical debts of about $6,000, has lost his
insurance benefits and faces the prospect he may lose his
$30,000-a-year job.
   ``You feel bad about not being at work, but you have to come out
here and support the union and what you believe in,'' Sheppard said
Wednesday.
   Similar sentiments came from other Eastern employees, including
pilots and flight attendants who joined the Machinists when they
struck the Miami-based carrier Saturday.
   ``I think people are still very pumped up,'' said Peggy Richards,
34, a flight attendant picketing in front of a virtually empty
Eastern terminal at Miami International Airport. ``We've all cried,
but the depression hasn't set in. We're still on a high.''
   Emotion was evident Wednesday night at a rally just outside the
Machinists union hall, which has turned into a sometimes chaotic
strike headquarters for pilots and flight attendants as well. Jesse
Jackson charged up about 3,000 workers with a message that in unity
they would prevail.
   The solidarity of the Machinists, pilots and flight attendants
has surprised some of the pickets.
   ``I'm encouraged mainly because of the support of all the
unions,'' said Dwight Bush, 43, a 22-year Eastern employee. ``If
it's not going to work out, we're better off looking for something
else.''
   Many workers say they have been contacting other airlines or
considering a career change if the company collapses. But finding
another job might prove difficult in the Miami area if thousands of
colleagues have to do the same, Bush acknowleged.
   The Machinists union has a $100 million strike fund and is paying
$100 a week to members who picket at least four hours a week. The
pilots union expects to pay its members 30 days after their last
paycheck, but no figure has been set.
   Flight attendants don't have a strike war chest, although the
Association of Flight Attendants and the AFL-CIO were expected to
provide some funds.
   Richards started full-time with Eastern 13 years ago and calls
the job ``addicting.'' But she said if she can't return to the
airline, she'll probably get a nursing job.
   Richards said she went back to school as labor turmoil escalated
at Eastern. If she sought employment at another airline, her
starting pay could be half her current salary.
</TEXT>
