<FIRST>u f BC-Britain-Stocks     03-09 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks,0178</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Flagging At Midday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were slowly sinking in patchy midday
dealings Thursday, with a handful of sellers able to push the
overall market lower.
   ``In this low volume, it doesn't take much margin to pull things
down,'' one salesman said.
   Caution ahead of Tuesday's British budget kept many players
sidelined, while the approaching close of a very active two-week
trading account gave participants little reason to modify existing
positions, observers noted.
   Dealers also claimed that loose talk of rights issues in several
leaders were responsible for dragging the market lower. Some said
they were waiting for Friday's release of U.S. unemployment figures
for February before committing fresh funds to the market.
   At midday, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was
down 12.7 points, or 0.6 percent, at 2,072.0, a shade above its
midmorning low of 2,069.2 but well off the opening high of 2,077.7.
   Turnover registered 272.9 million shares by midday compared with
324 million shares at the same time Wednesday.
