<HEAD>New York-Boston Pan Am Flight Forced To Land In Norwood</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORWOOD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New York-to-Boston Pan Am Express flight
made an emergency landing at an airport 15 miles southwest of Boston
after pilots detected a vibration in the plane, officials said.
   Pan Am flight 794 from Kennedy International Airport landed at
Norwood Airport at 10:10 p.m. Wednesday after pilots heard the
vibration and requested a priority landing, said Federal Aviation
Administration spokesman Michael Ciccarelli. At the time the problem
developed, the plane was five miles south of Norwood.
   There four-engine Dehavilland, with 48 people on board, landed
safely, Ciccarelli said. The passengers were taken to Boston by bus.
   The cause of the vibration was not immediately determined.
   The plane will remain at Norwood until Pan Am and the Federal
Aviation Administration have a chance to go over it, he said.
   Pan Am Express is a commuter subsidiary of Pan American.
