<HEAD>Judge Opens DeLorean's Assets To Creditors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has allowed creditors to begin
claiming the assets of former automaker John DeLorean after an
extension ran out on a $9.4 million bankruptcy settlement.
   U.S. District Judge James Woods on Wednesday accepted an order
from creditors who seek DeLorean's first payment of $4.9 million.
The money was due Feb. 28.
   The 1987 settlement stems from claims against DeLorean, whose
sports car company went bankrupt in 1984 after his arrest on federal
cocaine smuggling charges. DeLorean was acquitted. He also was
acquitted of fraud in Detroit.
   Mayer Morganroth, an attorney representing DeLorean, said
Wednesday that a Utah bank and a New York mortgage banking company
are preparing a loan for DeLorean.
   The payment hasn't been made because DeLorean is fighting a $53
million judgment handed down on behalf of a British creditor,
Morganroth said.
   DeLorean's assets _ which could be claimed and sold if he fails
to produce the payment _ include a Utah manufacturing company, a New
York City apartment and a mansion and farm in New Jersey.
