<FIRST>u f PM-Eastern-Icahn 1stLd-Writethru   03-09 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Icahn, 1st Ld-Writethru,0644</SECOND>
<HEAD>TWA Chairman Says Eastern Strikers Contacted Him About Possible Takeover</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: grafs 1-4 new to UPDATE with Eastern bankruptcy filing, affect
on any Icahn bid; uppicks 4th graf pvs: ``I would ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trans World Airlines Chairman Carl C. Icahn said
he is willing to meet with Eastern Airlines unions to discuss buying
the strike-paralyzed carrier if he is invited by Eastern's
management.
   But pressed to the limit, Eastern filed for protection from its
creditors under federal bankruptcy laws today, a move that could
make an Icahn takeover more cumbersome. The acquisition of a company
operating under Chapter 11 protection requires approval from both
creditors and the bankruptcy court.
   Icahn's emergence in the quickly deteriorating situation at
Eastern came Wednesday, the fifth day of a strike at the subsidiary
of Texas Air Corp., run by an old Icahn adversary, Frank Lorenzo.
Both battled for control of TWA in 1985, a fight Icahn eventually
won.
   Icahn said the striking Machinists union had contacted him
several times in the last week, asking him to enter into talks with
the union ``concerning the acquisition by TWA of Eastern.''
   ``I would be willing to speak to the unions only if Eastern
permits me to, because I do not want to be accused by Eastern of
interfering with the collective bargaining process,'' Icahn said in
a statement from his suburban New York office.
   He had mulled a possible bid for Eastern last fall, when Lorenzo
was considering selling the airline. But Icahn and the unions
couldn't agree on terms for a worker stake in a merger of TWA and
Eastern and talks broke off in October.
   The financier reportedly was seeking $250 million to $300 million
in labor concessions in exchange for an equity stake in Eastern for
the unions. Brian Freeman, financial adviser to the International
Association of Machinists, said he has asked Icahn to consider
restarting merger or takeover talks since the Eastern strike began
Saturday.
   Freeman, who also advises TWA employees, said he first suggested
acquiring Eastern to Icahn last year.
   ``Icahn seemed serious when we were discussing it with him a long
time ago,'' he said. ``I think to anyone who looks at this logically
... it makes a lot of sense. It's not a panacea. It's a way to
problem-solve lesser evils.''
   ``This is the most reasonable alternative if terms can be worked
out,'' he added.
   A secretary for Charles E. Bryan, president of the Machinists
local in Miami, said the union leader would not comment on Icahn's
statement.
   Eastern spokesman Robin Matell said the airline would not comment
on Icahn.
   Icahn, one of the decade's leading takeover investors, has chased
several large companies. Besides his takeover of TWA, he has
undertaken battles for steel-energy conglomerate USX Corp. and oil
giant Texaco Inc. He remains a major stockholder in both of those
companies.
   Wall Street considers a sale to TWA as one possible solution to
the financial woes at Eastern, which analysts estimate is worth
between $400 million plus debt assumption to $900 million if sold as
an entity.
   ``If Icahn _ and this is a big if _ is serious about keeping TWA
a major player well into the '90s, he has to make some capital moves
to acquire some other airlines or major equipment buys,'' said Louis
Marckesano, an analyst with Janney Montgomery Scott Inc. in
Philadelphia. ``It would seem Eastern would be cheapest way to do
both.''
   Icahn, who took TWA private last year, reportedly was interested
in Eastern's north-south routes, especially between New York and
Miami, as possible feeders into the airline's trans-Atlantic system.
   TWA is the nation's sixth-largest airline in terms of capacity
while Eastern is the seventh-largest.
</TEXT>
