<FIRST>r f PM-Palmer-KWQC     03-09 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Palmer-KWQC,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palmer Puts Iowa's First TV Station Up For Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAVENPORT, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iowa's first television station, KWQC of
Davenport, has been offered for sale by Palmer Communications Inc.,
the privately held company announced.
   William Ryan, president and chief executive officer of the Des
Moines-based communications company, said Wednesday that Palmer has
hired Howard Stark, a New York television broker, to sell the
station, which Palmer officials said is worth more than $45 million.
   Ryan said the decision to sell the station was made after Palmer
agreed Feb. 27 to buy KTVY-TV of Oklahoma City from Knight-Ridder
Inc. Terms of that sale were not disclosed.
   Ryan said that by selling its Davenport station and reinvesting
the capital gain in the Oklahoma City property, Palmer could defer
taxes on the gain from the sale. No other property could be sold in
order to get the tax deferment, he said.
   ``This was not an easy decision. KWQC-TV is a great television
station. It has performed exceedingly well and we're very proud of
it.'' Ryan said.
   ``While the potential sale of KWQC-TV is outside our normal
activities, these unique tax circumstances may allow Palmer, in
effect, to sell a station in the 79th largest market and buy one in
the 39th largest market for little money,'' he said.
   Ryan said the company hopes to find a buyer by late this year,
but it is possible that a transaction might not be completed until
1990. While KWQC-TV is an attractive property, he said the market
for television stations has softened lately because of rising
interest rates.
   Ryan announced the pending sale after flying to Davenport to tell
the station's staff. KWQC-TV employs 98 people.
   John Sloan, the station's general manager, said employees reacted
with cautious optimism. Because of the station's success, he said,
any knowledgeable buyer likely would carry on business as usual.
   KWQC-TV first went on the air in 1949 and used to have the call
letters WOC.
   Palmer also owns WHO-TV and radio stations WHO-AM and KLYF-FM in
Des Moines; radio stations in Tallahassee, Fort Myers and Naples,
Fla.; cable television systems in Palm Desert, Calif, and
Naples-Fort Myers, Fla.; and personal communication systems in Iowa,
New Mexico, Florida, Georgia and Alabama.
</TEXT>
