<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 1050EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Budget 1stLd-Writethru f0032 03-09 0671</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0032,0691</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress, White House Begin Budget Negotiations</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Top 5 grafs new with Fitzwater comments; picks up 3rd graf pvs,
White House Budget.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiations between Congress and the White
House on a fiscal 1990 budget ``should usher in a little more give
and take,'' an administration spokesman said today shortly before
the talks were to begin.
   White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater said the meeting
scheduled to begin this afternoon will build on informal sessions
between administration and congressional officials that laid the
groundwork.
   ``This formalization of the negotiating process should usher in a
little more give and take,'' said Fitzwater.
   He said Bush would also convene a larger meeting with staff and a
wider group of congressional leaders, possibly as soon as next week,
to work on budget compromises.
   ``If there's enough good will here on both sides, then we can
find an answer,'' said House budget chairman Leon Panetta, D-Calif.,
who announced the new talks along with Senate budget chairman Jim
Sasser, D-Tenn.
   White House Budget director Richard Darman, leading the Bush
administration negotiating team, has been pushing for the talks ever
since the president sent his $1.16 trillion spending plan to
Congress on Feb. 9.
   ``We're very pleased to see this development,'' said Barbara
Clay, Darman's spokeswoman.
   House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, who has been cool to the idea
of early budget negotiations with the Republican White House,
downplayed expectations for the new round of discussions. Rather
than calling it a ``summit,'' he told reporters it was ``a budget
plateau.''
   Democrats wanted to ``start with a level playing field'' _ with
military programs subject to cuts, not just domestic programs as
President Bush proposed in his $1.16 trillion spending plan, he said.
   Darman has been meeting with congressional budget writers of both
parties for weeks, but lawmakers insisted that those talks be
limited to quizzing the administration on details of its plan.
   The new discussions were welcomed by the White House.
   Congessional budget writers have been meeting privately with
Darman for weeks, but Democrats insisted those discussions were
limited to finding out more detail about the budget Bush presented
last month.
   Many Democrats contend the Bush budget revealed mostly the
politically popular aspects of a spending plan that, in order to
reduce the federal deficit, will eventually require cuts in federal
programs.
   ``We propose that the budget task force discussions enter a new
phase: an exploration of areas of possible compromise between
Congress and the administration on a fiscal year 1990 budget,'' said
the letter released Wednesday by Sasser and Panetta.
   Panetta said he hoped the talks would be modeled after the 1987
agreement between the Reagan White House and Congress and produce
``a framework for a budget resolution,'' agreement on overall
spending limits for broad budget categories such as defense, foreign
aid and entitlements.
   Taxes also would be discussed, Panetta said, although Bush has
insisted he would agree to no increases.
   The talks were approved by Senate Majority Leader George
Mitchell, D-Maine, and Wright. The Democratic leaders planned to
review the progress after two weeks to determine whether the talks
would continue, according to the letter.
   The Gramm-Rudman law calls for Congress and the president to
reduce the federal deficit to no more than $100 billion in the
fiscal year beginning Oct. 1.
   Bush contends his plan accomplished that goal without tax
increases. Some leading Democrats contend taxes are needed along
with spending cuts, and a report by the non-partisan Congressional
Budget Office, to be released Thursday, calculated the president
exceeded the deficit target.
   The CBO said that Bush's budget would leave a deficit of about
$109 billion, not including sell-offs of government assets which
don't count as deficit reduction under Gramm-Rudman. That's about
$14 billion higher than the Bush administration estimate.
   The CBO also estimates that another $25 billion would be added to
the deficit if Bush's bail-out ``off-budget'' plan for the savings
and loan industry were included in the deficit calculations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890309-0243 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 1109EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Eastern-Finances 1stLd-Writethru   03-09 0797</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Finances, 1st Ld-Writethru,0822</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bankruptcy Could Lead To Fire Sale Of Eastern's Assets, Experts Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with bankruptcy filing; EDITS thruout
to conform; No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At a late afternoon press conference Wednesday,
Eastern Airlines said it would file for bankruptcy only as a last
resort. Just 17 hours later, the time arrived.
   Attorneys for the strike-hobbled airline filed for protection
from creditors under Chapter 11 of federal bankruptcy laws shortly
after 9 a.m. today.
   Analysts and lawyers say Frank Lorenzo, chairman of Eastern's
parent, Texas Air Corp., will have a tougher time breaking union
contracts, imposing lower wages and keeping the airline alive than
he did when he reorganized Continental Airlines under federal
bankruptcy law.
   Eastern attorney Bruce Zirinsky said the company would seek to
reorganize under the bankruptcy laws. But he would not comment on
whether the plan would dissolve the carrier or attempt to keep it
flying.
   After Lorenzo put Continental into bankruptcy in September 1983
he reduced the number of employees to about 4,000 from 12,500.
   Partly because of that, Congress amended federal laws in 1984 to
require bankrupt companies to negotiate with unions and prove
economic necessity before abrogating their contracts.
   Lorenzo has been careful to operate Continental, Eastern and
Texas Air as independent concerns to eliminate the possiblity that a
bankruptcy judge might raid the parent company for money to pay
Eastern's creditors. For example, Continental paid above-market
prices recently to buy planes from Eastern, an analyst said.
   ``He has absolutely kept them separate and at arms length,'' said
one Wall Street analyst who asked not to be identified. ``He's got
the best bankruptcy guys in the world going for him.''
   Analysts said a likely scenario would be the demise of the
60-year-old carrier and a fire sale of its assets to competitors.
   ``If the idea of Chapter 11 is the way Lorenzo sees to fly
through this thing, he still faces the problem of finding people to
fly the planes,'' said Henry Oechler, a New York aviation lawyer.
``But the bankruptcy laws do significantly reduce the financial
hemorrhaging he is now facing.''
   The possibility Eastern had re-emerged Wednesday when Trans World
Airlines Chairman Carl Icahn said Eastern unions asked him to resume
talks begun last year about acquiring the ailing carrier. Icahn said
he would be willing to do so if Eastern permitted the talks.
   Wall Street analysts estimate Eastern has been losing $2 million
to $7 million daily during the six-day-old walkout by Machinists,
pilots and flight attendants.
   Eastern spokesman Robin Matell said Wednesday the airline would
consider bankruptcy only as a last resort.
   Chapter 11 protection frees Eastern of its obligations to
creditors. But it also could hamstring Lorenzo in selling parts of
the airline to raise money. Every deal would require court approval
under a reorganization plan, which also would be subject to creditor
approval.
   Lorenzo could have sought creditor protection under Chapter 7,
which governs liquidation of a company. That would have meant an
auction of Eastern's assets, reportedly worth $3.8 billion last
September.
   Wall Street estimates Eastern is worth far more in a
piece-by-piece auction than the $400 million to $900 million it
could fetch as a unit. Its major assets include landing slots and
gates at major airports. Its South American operation is valued at
$150 million and its Miami maintenance facility at $300 million.
   ``They're better off opening the doors Monday morning and saying
that Friday at 2 o'clock we'll be accepting bids for any part of
Eastern Airlines,'' one analyst said.
   In a move to inject cash, USAir announced Wednesday that it had
reached agreement to buy all eight of Eastern's gates at
Philadelphia International Airport for $70 million and Eastern's
Philadelphia-Toronto and Philadelphia-Montreal routes for $15
million. The airlines said the deal had been in the works for some
time.
   Richard Lieb, a New York bankruptcy attorney, said large
companies with a debt as big as Eastern's normally file under
Chapter 11, leaving unions in a better position to receive pensions
and allowing the company to be broken up and sold if need be.
   Miami-based Eastern is rapidly spending the $402 million in cash
it had at the beginning of the year, most of which represented
prepaid tickets the airline now must refund to passengers or pay to
competitors who honor Eastern tickets.
   Eastern had a $70 million debt payment due at the end of March
and expenses for aircraft leases, airport gates, other overhead and
salaries for the 1,500 workers who remain on the job.
   It also owed payments of about $25 million a month on $2.5
billion in debt Texas Air inherited when it bought Eastern for about
$615 million in February 1986.
</TEXT>
