<DOCNO> AP890309-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 1135EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-CompanyStore     03-09 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Company Store,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company Store Employees Accept Wage Deferral</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LA CROSSE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Employees of The Company Store have agreed
to a wage reduction plan designed to get the producer of down-filled
blankets, clothing and other items through what management calls a
temporary financial bind.
   Workers this week agreed to a deferral of 9 percent of their
wages, an arrangement that Terry Gillette, Company Store president,
described as being a loan from employees.
   Gillette said the money is needed to help the privately held
company through some difficult economic times.
   He indicated one of the company's main problems involved getting
raw materials for its down products from suppliers in Jamaica and
South Korea. A hurricane in Jamaica and the Olympics in Korea
interrupted supply lines, he said.
   The wage deferral was approved Tuesday by more than 80 percent of
employees, an action that Gillette said indicated strong faith in
the future of the business.
   A wage increase scheduled to take effect next fall also will be
deferred. The plan calls for the workers to get half of their
deferred wages back in December, and the other half is to be
returned next February.
   The business has faced, and survived, financial problems before.
   In 1973, when it was known as the La Crosse Garment Manufacturing
Co., it faced bankruptcy. Gillette, a La Crosse lawyer appointed by
a court to handle the company, bought the business.
   In 1982, it abandoned its tradition of producing sleeping bags
and down outerwear for military contracts. It converted to a
direct-mail business, and sales of its down products have increased
1,000 percent since 1982.
   The Company Store now mails about 25 million catalogs annually,
employs more than 1,000 workers in its busy season, and had 1988
income of about $100 million.
</TEXT>
