<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 1139EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WatkinsSwearing-In     03-09 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Watkins Swearing-In,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Secretary Urges Higher Standards For Nuclear Plants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy Secretary James D. Watkins pledged at
his swearing-in ceremony today to weed out ``mediocre and
substandard'' practices in running the nation's problem-ridden
nuclear weapons complex.
   ``Nuclear power demands no less than the best from all who
control it,'' he told a ceremony attended by President Bush and
several hundred department employees.
   ``I ask you to help me'' promote a work attitude within the
department ``that rejects the mediocre and substandard,'' said
Watkins, 62, a retired admiral.
   Bush, in introductory remarks, highlighted problems at the
nuclear weapons plants, which are operated by private contracters
for the Energy Department. Safety, technical and environmental
problems at many of the 16 major plants in 12 states have virtually
crippled the nation's nuclear arms production.
   The department has estimated it will cost at least $52 billion
over the next 21 years to modernize the weapons plants, plus $65
billion or more to repair environmental damage caused by four
decades of nuclear bomb-making.
   ``The most pressing challenge is to manage the modernization of
America's nuclear weapons complex,'' Bush said, adding, ``We need to
clean up the pollution that's been created at these plants.''
   Bush told the Energy Department employees he rejected former
President Ronald Reagan's goal of trying to dismantle the
department, which was created in 1977.
   ``There's been talk in the past that this department was not
necessary ... but let me say you have important work to do. You are
on the cutting edge now, and this department is here to stay,'' Bush
said.
   The department has about 16,000 employees and a budget this year
of $14 billion.
   ``As I see it, the responsibilities before this department have
never been greater than today,'' Bush said, adding that he was
counting on Watkins, whose 41-year Navy career included work with
the service's nuclear reactor program, to restore the nation's
capability to produce nuclear arms without harming the environment.
   ``I selected a big man to do a big job so, Jim, we better swear
you in and let you get to work,'' Bush said.
   Watkins was confirmed by the Senate last week.
</TEXT>
