<FIRST>u f PM-High-DefinitionTV 1stLd-Writethru   03-09 0828</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-High-Definition TV, 1st Ld-Writethru,0851</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prestowitz Says Government Must Help HDTV Makers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 7 grafs new with testimony; picks up 2nd graf pvs, In my
view.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government must assure U.S.
electronic manufacturers they will be protected from marketing
policies in Japan before the next generation of television
technology can develop in this country, Congress was told today.
   U.S. manufacturers of TV receivers and VCRs were driven out of
business in the 1960s and 1970s primarily because of price-slashing,
collusion and so-called dumping of low-priced Japanese TV sets in
this country, said Clyde Prestowitz, a senior associate at the
Carnegie Endowment for International Peace.
   Faced with the possibility of that kind of competition from the
Japanese again, U.S. manufacturers may be reluctant to enter the
burgeoning era of high-definition television, Prestowitz said.
   ``It was the marketing factors that were the most important ones
in the demise of the U.S. industry,'' Prestowitz told the second day
of a House subcommittee hearing on what government policy should be
regarding HDTV in the next century.
   At the same time, Prestowitz said, the U.S. government must tread
carefully in any effort to protect the U.S. electronics industry
because U.S. companies also are trying to enter foreign markets.
   ``We might consider some reciprocity requirement,'' conditioning
foreign participation in U.S. efforts to develop HDTV on the
possibility of U.S. participation overseas.
   Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher testified Wednesday that the
private sector should determine what, if any, aid it needs before
the government becomes a partner with business to develop an HDTV
industry in the United States.
   ``In my view the private sector must take the lead,'' with the
government ``getting the hindrances out of the way,'' Mosbacher told
the subcommittee.
   Rep. Edward J. Markey, D-Mass., asked the administration to
provide Congress with quarterly updates on progress towards an HDTV
manufacturing capacity _ a burgeoning technology that witnesses at
the House hearing said was crucial to U.S. competitiveness in the
next century.
   Markey asked witnesses before the subcommittee, which he chairs,
if a government-industry consortium would help the United States
overcome a big Japanese lead in technology that promises wall-sized
TV screens with motion-picture clarity.
   The Defense Department is offering $30 million to private
companies to develop HDTV technology. But Markey said ``What we
would clearly like to see is a civilian orientation.''
   Mosbacher said it was premature to seek such a government-private
sector link in the face of foreign competition until the private
sector decides what it needs.
   The government is considering tax incentives and possible
antitrust exemptions for U.S. companies that wish to band together
in the HDTV effort, he said.
   U.S. industry must remain ``pre-eminent'' in the drive to develop
HDTV, which he said could represent $140 billion in sales of TVs and
VCRs in the United States in next 20 years, he said.
   The impact of HDTV will go far beyond entertainment uses to areas
such as medicine, education, retailing and defense, he said.
   Establishing government policy in this area has the ``highest
priority'' at the Commerce Department, Mosbacher said, and he
expects to be able to make a recommendation to Congress on the
government role in the next two months.
   The Defense Department is offering $30 million to industry to
help develop HDTV, and many subcommittee members _ and Mosbacher _
said the money should go to U.S. companies.
   Some of America's largest electronics concerns, and some of their
biggest foreign competitors, have filed applications for the Defense
Department seed money.
   The Pentagon said Wednesday it had received 87 proposals by its
Feb. 27 deadline. At least two foreign electronic giants submitted
funding requests _ the Sony Corp. of America, a subsidiary of the
Japanese conglomerate, and North American Philips Corp., a
subsidiary of NV Philips of the Netherlands.
   Among the other large companies requesting federal research
grants were AT&amp;T Technologies Inc.; General Electric Co.; the Harris
Corp.; Honeywell Inc.; Hughes Aircraft Co.; International Business
Machines; ITT Semiconductors; the Norden Systems subsidiary of the
United Technologies Corp.; the Tandy Corp.; Texas Instruments Inc.;
Westinghouse; and the Zenith Electronics Corp.
   Dennis E. Eckart, D-Ohio, noting Sony's proposal for Defense
Department research funds, said the government should consider
limiting the money to U.S. companies.
   ``I think this committee and the American taxpayers have to
question whether or not we want to provide U.S. taxpayers' dollars
to foreign competitors when this gentleman is not yet convinced
those foreign competitors are treating us fairly in other world
marketplaces,'' he said.
   ``It's one thing not to treat us fair,'' he said. ``It's another
thing for them to use American taxpayers' dollars to try to elbow
their way into the head of the line.''
   Another witness, State Department Ambassador Sonia Landau, said
the United States was urging adoption of one world standard for HDTV
transmission in order to protect the U.S. motion picture and TV
industries, which command 85 percent of that world market.
</TEXT>
