<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   03-09 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Gain Early; Grains Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices were slightly higher,
reflecting firmer cash prices, after a mixed opening today on the
Chicago Board of Trade, while grain futures were nearly unchanged in
early trading.
   The soybean market's modest rally defied expectations that
Wednesday's steep declines would be extended into today's session.
   Wednesday's losses were attributed to technical factors and to
nervousness about the looming Brazilian soybean harvest, which is
expected to be the most bountiful ever for the world's
second-largest soybean producer.
   But instead of follow-through selling, the soybean complex gained
support from higher cash markets and from ideas that Wednesday's
losses were overdone.
   Grain futures were very narrowly mixed, although some observers
expected forecasts for warm, dry weather in the nation's midsection
to give the wheat market a boost.
   In early trading, wheat was } cent lower to 1\ cents higher with
the contract for delivery in March at $4.31 a bushel; corn was {
cent lower to \ cent higher with March at $2.75 a bushel; oats were
1 cent lower to \ cent higher with March at $2.04 a bushel; soybeans
were \ cent to 1{ cents higher with March at $7.57 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were modestly lower
in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .02 cent lower to .20 cent higher with April at
77.10 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .25 cent lower to .20 cent
higher with March at 81.40 cents a pound; live hogs were .05 cent to
.27 cent lower with April at 44 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .02 cent to .50 cent lower with March at 38.45 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
