<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 1225EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Eastern-Congress 1stLd-Writethru   03-09 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Congress, 1st Ld-Writethru,0620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bankruptcy Petition Throws House Panel Into Confusion</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Ledes with 8 grafs with delay caused by bankruptcy proceedings;
picks up 7th graf pvs, The legislation; edits Oberstar reference in next
last graf. Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines' bankruptcy filing threw
members of Congress into confusion today, just as they were set to
work on legislation that would force a reluctant President Bush to
temporarily halt the crippling strike against the carrier.
   The House Public Works and Transportation Committee had planned
to approve the legislation today and send it for a vote to the full
House next week, where passage with the overwhelming support of the
majority Democrats would be expected.
   But the panel postponed its meeting _ at least until midafternoon
_ when lawmakers received word that the ailing airline had filed for
protection from creditors in U.S. bankruptcy court in New York.
   Rep. James Oberstar, D-Minn., chairman of the Public Works and
Transportation aviation subcommittee, and other members of the panel
said there were concerns that legislation dealing with one specific
company involved in bankruptcy proceedings might be unconstitutional.
   They said they believed that under the law, bankruptcy
legislation must be applied uniformly, not just to one company. They
also said they believed the problem could be resolved.
   ``I think we can sort this out,'' Oberstar told reporters.
   But Oberstar and Rep. Glenn Anderson, D-Calif., chairman of the
full committee, offered no specifics when asked how the bankruptcy
proceedings might cause the legislation to be changed.
   ``There may be some amendments,'' Anderson said.
   The legislation, approved Tuesday along party lines by the
aviation subcommittee, would require Bush to appoint an emergency
board to review the differences between Eastern and the
International Association of Machinists, which represents 8,500
machinists, baggage handlers and other ground workers.
   The strikers would return to work for up to 60 days while the
board studied the dispute _ which is largely over wages and benefits
_ and recommended a solution.
   The carriers' pilots and flight attendants have honored the
machinists' picket lines, forcing Eastern to terminate most of its
1,040 daily flights.
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, said Wednesday he would oppose the
legislation when it reaches the Senate, where determined procedural
maneuvering by one lawmaker can sometimes spell the end of a bill.
   ``I certainly am going to oppose any effort by Congress to force
the president to take any action that limits his prerogative,''
Gramm told a reporter.
   But even if the legislation makes it through Congress,
Transportation Secretary Samuel K. Skinner has said he will urge
Bush to veto the bill. The administration has argued that appointing
a review board will do little to solve a fight that has been waged
for 17 months, or to move the ailing airline away from the
possibility of bankruptcy.
   Democrats concede they would not have the two-thirds majority in
both chambers needed to override the veto. They have pressed the
legislation anyway, arguing that to do so prods Eastern and its
unions to settle their disputes, pressures Bush to change his
position, and at the very least would embarrass him by placing him
in the spotlight.
   ``If we took every bill up on the premise that the president
wouldn't veto it, there would be few bills that we'd take to the
House floor,'' Oberstar said Wednesday.
   The administration has said it might submit legislation that
would ban secondary boycotts against other airlines and railroad
systems, as are allowed under current law. The Democratic-controlled
Congress would be expected to reject such a proposal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
