<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 1252EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-MinimumWage 1stLd-Writethru   03-09 0686</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Minimum Wage, 1st Ld-Writethru,0707</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Clears Pay Increase; House Subcommittee to Draft Measure</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS with 8 grafs on action today; picks up 6th graf pvs, Hawkins
backs .... Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House panel today approved legislation to
gradually add $1.30 an hour to the $3.35 minimum wage and Democratic
leaders said they are willing to compromise with the Bush
administration over a reduced ``training wage'' for some workers.
   The measure approved by the labor standards subcommittee was
virtually identical to legislation the Senate Labor and Human
Resources passed Wednesday and advanced Democratic plans to take the
first hike in the minimum since 1981 to the floors of both houses
within two weeks.
   Both bills would raise the minimum in increments over three
years, to $4.65 an hour by 1991.
   Rep. Augustus Hawkins, D-Calif., chairman of the full House
Education and Labor Committee, scheduled a vote on the subcommittee
legislation for next Tuesday.
   Subcommittee Chairman Austin Murphy, D-Pa., said Democrats are
drafting their own version of a ``training wage'' and specific
requirements for education and be limited in duration.
   President Bush favors a more modest increase in the minimum wage
and wants to leave the minimum at $3.35 an hour for the first six
months' employment for all newly hired workers.
   The Democratic version of the training wage ``will be more
restrictive than the proposals we have heard from the president,''
Murphy said. ``However, our effort will show we are sincere and
prepared to address the components of this issue.''
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., chairman of the Senate labor
committee, said Wednesday that the bill is also on the ``fast
track'' in that chamber and there may be floor vote there next week.
   Hawkins backs raising the minimum to $4.65 by 1991 and last week
called the administration's more modest raise ``totally
unacceptable.''
   The minimum wage has stood at $3.35 an hour since 1981.
   The plan the Senate committee passed Wednesday would raise it 50
cents an hour when enacted and 40 cents an hour in each of the next
two years.
   President Bush said last week he wanted the minimum wage raised
to $4.25 by 1991, if a lower floor is established for the first six
months' employment at any job for workers covered by the minimum.
   Senate Democrats, after softening their opposition to a second
pay tier for new workers, called on Bush to compromise in the effort
to raise the minimum for the first time in eight years.
   ``I am hopeful that we can reach a compromise that is fairer to
the working poor and that President Bush will sign,'' Kennedy said,
later adding: ``My own hope is that the administration may still be
brought on board. But if it's the judgment that (Bush will) veto it,
we'll override it.''
   Bush has said he would veto legislation raising the minimum above
$4.25 an hour and told GOP leaders Wednesday that, as spokesman
Marlin Fitzwater put it, his proposal ``is fair and firm and his
last offer.''
   Kennedy predicted a full Senate vote on his bill next week and
said Congress may send an increase to Bush by the end of the month.
   ``One way or another, I'm convinced this is on a fast track
now,'' he said.
   The training wage, long opposed by Democrats and organized labor,
remains a key dispute.
   The administration would allow a $3.35-an-hour wage for all newly
hired workers for the first six months of their employment, saying
the lower minimum would leave employers an incentive to hire younger
and unskilled workers.
   Kennedy said Wednesday he is ``glad to listen'' to calls for a
reduced minimum for some workers, but said it would have to be
coupled with specific requirements for training and education.
   ``I'm open to listening, to having the educational components
outlined,'' he said. ``There was nothing in the administration
proposal that had an educational component.''
   He added that such a plan would also have to be limited to
first-time workers and be for a shorter duration than six months.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
