<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Retail     03-09 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Retail,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>K mart, Dayton Hudson Report Strong Earnings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Two large U.S. retailers Thursday reported sharply higher income
for the fourth quarter and 1988, due partly to vigilance in
controling inventories and a pickup in sales toward the end of the
year.
   K mart Corp., the Troy, Mich.-based discounter that does the most
retail business after Sears, Roebuck and Co., said its after-tax
income rose 22.4 percent in its fourth quarter and 16 percent for
the full year which ended Jan. 25, 1989.
   Separately, Dayton Hudson Corp. posted gains of 36.6 percent in
its fourth quarter net income and 26 percent for the entire year.
The company, based in Minneapolis and the operator of 618 stores in
37 states, said growth in its net earnings per share last year well
exceeded its target.
   Joseph E. Antonini, K mart chairman and chief executive, said
expense controls and inventory management were enhanced during the
year by linking more stores to point-of-sale systems, allowing K
mart to keep better track of companywide stock levels. At the end of
the year, 1,180 stores were hooked up to the computerized system, up
from 759 stores a year earlier.
   The company's net income came to $393.2 million, or $1.96 a
share, for the three months ended Jan. 25, up from $321.2 million,
or $1.58 a share, in the fourth quarter of the prior year.
   Sales for the quarter were up 8.5 percent to $8.42 billion, from
$7.75 billion in the year-earlier period.
   For the full year, K mart earned $802.9 million, or $4 a share,
after taxes, on sales of $27.30 billion, compared with $692.2
million, or $3.40 a share, on sales of $25.63 billion for fiscal
1987.
   The department store owner Dayton Hudson reported its net income
totaled $183 million, or $2.31 a share, in the fourth quarter ended
Jan. 28, on sales of $4.1 billion. That compared with earnings of
$134 million, or $1.54 a share, and sales of $3.68 billion a year
earlier.
   For Dayton Hudson's full financial year, after-tax income totaled
$287 million, or $3.45 a share, and sales were $12.20 billion vs.
the previous year's earnings of $228 million, or $2.41 a share, and
sales of $10.68 billion.
   ``We were committed to exceed our earnings-per-share growth
objecive of 15 percent in 1988 and we did,'' said Kenneth A. Macke,
Dayton Hudson's chairman and chief executive officer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
