<FIRST>r f AM-IBM-3M     03-09 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IBM-3M,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>IBM Selling Tucson Building With Magnetic Tape Operation to 3M</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR H. ROTSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. will
sell 3M its magnetic tape manufacturing building and equipment at
IBM's Tucson complex, the companies said Thursday.
   3M will supply tape cartridges for IBM's 3480 magnetic tape
subsystem, to be sold both under IBM and 3M brand names. The product
is used for long-term storage of data on reels of tape.
   IBM invented and developed the 3480 tape cartridge, and the drive
system that the cartridge supports was developed in Tucson, where
the sole manufacturing plant is.
   Under the agreement, 3M, which manufactures a compatible tape in
Minnesota, will supply IBM with 3480 tape cartridges to IBM
specifications, and 3M and IBM both will market the tape cartridges
under their own brand names.
   3M _ formally known as Minnesota Mining and Manufacturing Co. _
produces Scotch brand tape and numerous other products.
   Philip B. Hage, a spokesman at 3M headquarters in St. Paul,
Minn., said the company will employ about 120 people at
116,000-square-foot Building No. 10 on the IBM campus. IBM will not
reveal its employment at the building, Hage said.
   IBM is phasing out its manufacturing operation and developing the
site into a business park.
   Hage said 3M would not take actual possession of the plant or
start manufacturing for at least 30 days, because of the need for
government approval of the sale and the need for IBM to notify its
employees of the sale. The sale price was not disclosed.
</TEXT>
