<HEAD>Diamond-Star To Start Second Shift</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORMAL, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Diamond-Star Motors Corp., a joint venture
between Chrysler Corp. and Mitsubishi Motors Corp., will begin a
second shift at its plant in May, six months ahead of schedule, the
company said Thursday.
   Diamond-Star said the second shift will boost plant employment to
about 2,900 by July from about 1,900 now. The plant makes Plymouth
Laser and Mitsubishi Eclipse two-door sports cars.
   This spring, the plant will add production of a two-door,
four-wheel-drive car to be marketed by Chrysler as the Eagle Talon
and by Mitsubishi as another version of the Eclipse. Fall plans call
for the factory to begin making the Mitsubishi Mirage and Eagle
Summit, both two-wheel-drive, four-door cars.
   The plant is making about 175 cars a day and will increase that
rate to about 1,000 at full production with the addition of the
second shift, Diamond-Star spokeswoman Christine Ziehmann said.
