<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 1519EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   03-09 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Talk Of Weather, Exports, Brazilian Strike Propel Grain Futures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices advanced strongly
Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade, erasing most of the previous
session's losses amid a variety of bullish factors.
   Forecasts for continued dryness in prime winter-wheat areas
supported the wheat market, as did talk that the Soviet Union was
seeking to buy more U.S. wheat at subsidized prices.
   Soybean futures, which had fallen steeply Wednesday on jitters
linked to the impending Brazilian soybean harvest, surged back
Thursday on rumors that Brazilian dockworkers were planning to
strike next Wednesday, halting exports of newly harvested soybeans.
   ``Some of the people who sold the soybean market yesterday came
back and bought it today,'' said Steve Freed, grain-market analyst
with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   Corn futures were boosted by higher cash prices and by concerns
about lack of adequate soil moisture in the Midwest.
   At the close, wheat was 2} cents to 5} cents higher with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.35} a bushel; corn was 1} cents
to 3 cents higher with March at $2.77\ a bushel; oats were 2 cents
to 3\ cents higher with March at $2.07 a bushel; soybeans were 6}
cents to 10} cents higher with March at $7.63 a bushel.
