<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 2231EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-GoldFields     03-09 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gold Fields,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gold Fields Bid Defense Seen Forcing Higher Minorco Bid</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Huw in 7th graf is cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Securities analysts expected Minorco SA to sweeten
its hostile $5.5 billion bid for Consolidated Gold Fields PLC
Thursday after Gold Fields sent shareholders a document detailing
the company's strengths and future plans.
   However, the analysts saw little in the document, which contained
numerous valuations and forecasts for Gold Fields' various
businesses, that would cause them to change their own estimates of
what the British mining company was worth.
   South African-controlled Minorco, which already owns 29.6 percent
of Gold Fields' shares, has offered 20.50 pounds, or $35.26, in cash
and one new Minorco share for every two Gold Fields shares.
   Minorco shares traded Thursday afternoon at 804 pench each, down
9 pence on the day, meaning the offer values each Gold Fields share
at 14.27 pounds. However, Gold Fields stock closed above that level,
rising 7 pence to 14.30 pounds.
   The deal is worth a total of 3.2 billion pounds, or $5.5 billion.
   Analysts in London said Minorco, a Luxembourg-based company,
would have to sweeten its offer to between 15 pounds and 16 pounds a
share.
   ``The real story today is that this document from Gold Fields
will force Minorco to come back with a higher offer price,'' said
Huw Williams, a mining analyst at Kleinwort Grieveson Securities.
   In the document sent to shareholders, Gold Fields assigned a
value of between 8.44 pounds and 10.39 pounds per Gold Fields' share
to its U.S. gold interests. These include full ownership of Gold
Fields Mining Corp. and 49 percent of Newmont Mining Corp.
   At a later press conference, the company said its other mineral
investments worldwide are worth 5.23 pounds per Gold Fields' share.
Gold Fields owns 48 percent of Renison Goldfields Consolidated Ltd.
of Australia, 38 percent of Gold Fields of South Africa Ltd. and
other assets.
   The Gold Fields' document also detailed the results of its past
mineral exploration, and predicted, ``Considerable value will be
added in the future if recent successes are repeated.''
   The document also questioned the management ability of Minorco
executives and the value of the company's stock. Gold Fields also
noted that if it were owned by the South African company, it might
lose business in the United States because of American opposition to
South Africa's policy of apartheid.
   It was not known what further steps Gold Fields planned to take
to counter the Minorco bid.
   Joseph Perella, chairman of Wasserstein Perella &amp; Co. Inc. and a
Gold Fields adviser, said in New York that at this point, the
company had little to do besides point out the discrepancies between
the value of the Minorco bid and the underlying value of its own
assets.
   Following the release of Gold Fields' figures, London analysts
said they saw little reason to alter significantly their earlier
estimates that valued the company's total assets at somewhere
between 15 pounds and just over 20 pounds a share.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
