<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar drifted lower against other major
currencies in dull U.S. trading Thursday as dealers marked time a
day before release of February's unemployment report.
   Gold prices rose in domestic dealing after declining overseas. At
4 p.m. EST, Republic National Bank of New York quoted a bid of
$393.80 for a troy ounce of gold, up $1.90 from Wednesday's late bid.
   ``Everybody's waiting for the unemployment report,'' said Fred
Barth, chief foreign exchange trader for Prudential Bache Securities
Inc. ``Trading was lackluster at best.''
   Currency dealers elsewhere around the world reported activity
slackened as market operators awaited Friday's release of the U.S.
unemployment report by the Labor Department in Washington.
   The report will provide one of the first indications of how the
economy has responded to rising interest rates. The Federal Reserve
Board has been pursuing a restrictive monetary policy to help slow
growth and relieve inflationary pressures on the economy.
   The dollar moved moderately higher against several key currencies
in some overseas foreign exchange markets before reversing course in
the United States.
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed at 129.23 Japanese yen, up from
128.73.
   Later in London, the dollar traded at 129.10 yen. The decline
continued in U.S. trading and the dollar was quoted late in New York
at 128.80 yen, down from 129.225 late Wednesday.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.7183 late Thursday from
Wednesday's $1.7200. Sterling strengthened in U.S. trading, rising
to $1.7220 from $1.7155 on Wednesday.
   Other later dollar rates in New York, compared with Wednesday's
rates, included: 1.85625 West German marks, down from 1.86325;
1.58555 Swiss francs, down from 1.5910; 1.19925 Canadian dollars,
down from 1.20145; 6.2975 French francs, down from 6.3230; and
1,363.00 Italian lire, down from 1,366.875.
   In European trading, late rates for the dollar, compared with
Wednesday's late rates, included: 1.8600 West German marks, up from
1.8585; 1.5895 Swiss francs, up from 1.5865; 6.3125 French francs,
up from 6.3080; 2.1000 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0930; 1,366.00
Italian lire, up from 1,362.20, and 1.2000 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.2015.
   Gold bullion prices rose in U.S. trading but fell on foreign
metal markets.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery closed at $395.10 a troy ounce, up from $393.10 Wednesday.
   Overseas, prices dropped by $2 to $3 an ounce but held above the
$390 level, which dealers described as the current benchmark in
light of some renewed interest in the metal.
   In London, the late bid for gold was $391.55 a troy ounce, down
from $393.80 late Wednesday. The late bid in Zurich was $391.75,
down from $394.75. Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at a bid of
$393.51, up from $392.96.
   Late in London, silver was quoted at $5.88 a troy ounce, down
from $5.91.
   On New York's Comex, silver bullion for current delivery settled
at $6.008 a troy ounce, up from $5.865 on Wednesday.
