<SECOND>AM-Ford Retires, 1st Ld - Writethru,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford Retirement Paves Way For Fourth Generation Leadership</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds; SUBS 6th graf pvs Ford's retirement... to CORRECT to 40 years
sted 50. Picks up 7th graf, In 1951...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DT2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Clay Ford said Thursday he was retiring as
a vice chairman of Ford Motor Co., paving the way for a fourth
generation of family leadership of the automaker founded by his
grandfather, Henry Ford.
   The retirement of Ford, who will be 64 Tuesday, is effective at
the end of March and has been anticipated for months. He will remain
on the board of directors and as chairman of the board's finance and
executive committees.
   Ford's son, William Clay Ford Jr., 31, and nephew, Edsel B. Ford
II, 40, represent the fourth generation of the founding family. Both
are on the company's 21-member board of directors and the elder Ford
said in an afternoon news conference that he expects both to receive
key board assignments within a year.
   Ford said there always should be a member of the family on the
board and in leadership, but added the next generation should not be
rushed into such positions.
   ``Nature has got to take its course,'' he said.
   Ford's retirement came 40 years after he joined the company upon
graduating from Yale. He was elected to the company's board the year
before and worked on Ford's sales and advertising and industrial
relations staffs.
   In 1951, he became quality control manager for the
Lincoln-Mercury Division's jet engine defense project. Through the
decade, he stayed in the Lincoln-Mercury Division in a variety of
projects.
   Ford in 1957 was named chairman of the company's new design
committee of the policy and planning committee and still holds the
post.
   Ford was elected chairman of the board's executive committee and
became a member of the office of the chief executive in 1978. On
April 10, 1980, he was elected a vice chairman of the board. He
became chairman of its finance committee on Nov. 12, 1987.
   During the late 1970s and early 1980s, Ford took part in key
decisions that pulled the company from financial hard times to its
present profitability. As design chairman, Ford had a integral part
in developing such aerodynamic cars as the Ford Taurus that helped
turn around the company's balance sheet in the mid-1980s.
   Ford also is sole owner and president of the Detroit Lions
professional football team.
   He was the youngest of four children of Edsel B. Ford, who was
president of the automobile company from 1919 until his death in
1943.
   Ford's oldest brother, Henry Ford II, was the company's
president, chairman and chief executive officer before his death in
September 1987. His other brother, Benson Ford, was vice president
and chairman of the dealer policy board when he died in 1978.
   The roles of William Jr. and Edsel have been at the center of
speculation since Fortune magazine published a story about the
family in December.
   According to the magazine, William Jr. and Edsel have been
pushing for more power in the operations of the nation's
most-profitable automaker. But, Fortune said, Ford Chairman Donald
Petersen turned aside notions that they belonged in top management
positions simply because they were Fords.
   Early this year, Petersen said the cousins were ``now coming of
age.''
   Ford's other vice chairman, Harold Poling, also is chief
operating officer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
