<FIRST>u f AM-CommoditiesRdp     03-09 0646</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodities Rdp,0670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Silver Surges Above $6, A 6-Week High</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Silver futures prices surged in the final minutes of trading
Thursday on New York's Commodity Exchange and settled with the
spot-delivery price above $6 a troy ounce for the first time in
nearly six weeks.
   On other markets, gold futures also advanced; grains and soybeans
rebounded sharply; livestock and meat futures were lower; and energy
futures retreated.
   Silver settled 14.1 cents to 15.3 cents higher with the most
actively traded contract, for delivery in May, at $6.09 an ounce.
The spot contract for March delivery settled at the day's high of
$6.008 a troy ounce.
   Gold settled $1.40 to $1.90 higher with April at $397.30 a troy
ounce.
   Analysts said the rally was technically inspired, meaning the
buying was based on bullish interpretations of chart patterns rather
than on any change in market fundamentals.
   But the strength of silver relative to gold also suggests
speculators and investors are embracing silver and turning away from
gold, the traditional leader of the precious metals group.
   ``The white knight is finally performing,'' said Peter Cardillo,
commodity trading adviser with Josephthal &amp; Co., a New York futures
brokerage firm. ``I think we're going to see silver emerge as the
leader in the next major rally.''
   Gold is often perceived as a safe haven for investment dollars in
inflationary times, but it has responded poorly to recent government
reports of sharp rises in wholesale and consumer prices.
   Gold's sluggish reaction to the inflation signals ``suggests to
some traders that silver may outperform gold,'' said analyst Bette
Raptopoulos of Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York.
   She said the rally also reflected positioning by traders before
Friday's national unemployment report. A decline in the jobless rate
of more than 0.1 percentage point would be considered inflationary,
as would an increase in non-farm employment of 300,000 or more.
   Grain and soybean futures advanced strongly on the Chicago Board
of Trade, erasing most of the previous session's losses amid a
variety of bullish factors.
   Forecasts for continued dryness in prime winter-wheat areas
supported the wheat market, as did talk that the Soviet Union was
seeking to buy more U.S. wheat at subsidized prices.
   Soybean futures, which had fallen steeply Wednesday on jitters
linked to the impending Brazilian soybean harvest, surged back
Thursday on rumors that Brazilian dockworkers were planning to
strike next Wednesday, halting exports of newly harvested soybeans.
   Corn futures were boosted by higher cash prices and by concerns
about a lack of adequate soil moisture in the Midwest.
   Wheat settled 2} cents to 5} cents higher with March at $4.35} a
bushel; corn was 2 cents to 3 cents higher with March at $2.77} a
bushel; oats were 2 cents to 3\ cents higher with March at $2.07 a
bushel; soybeans were 6} cents to 12 cents higher with March at
$7.63{ a bushel.
   Sluggish cash markets pressured livestock and meat futures on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange. Heavy marketings of hogs also weighed
on the pork complex.
   Live cattle settled .05 cent to .10 cent lower with April at
77.07 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .40 cent to .78 cent lower
with March at 80.87 cents a pound; live hogs were .05 cent to .40
cent lower with April at 43.72 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .65 cent lower to .12 cent higher with March at 38.20 cents a
pound.
   Energy futures retreated in technically motivated trading on the
New York Mercantile Exchange, reversing the previous session's sharp
gains in heating oil.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 2 cents to 4 cents
lower with April at $18.52 a barrel; heating oil was .60 cent to .99
cent lower with April at 50.38 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was
.25 cent lower to .08 cent higher with April at 51.60 cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
