<FIRST>u f AM-MoneySupply     03-09 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Supply,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Money Supply Measures Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A broad measure of the nation's money supply fell
while a narrower measure rose in late February, the Federal Reserve
Board reported Thursday.
   The Fed said the measure known as M3 fell $1.9 billion to a
seasonally adjusted $3,942.6 billion in the week ended Feb. 27 from
a revised $3,944.5 billion the previous week. The previous week's
figure had originally been reported as $3,945.9 billion.
   A narrower measure, M2, rose $4 billion to a seasonally adjusted
$3,077.5 billion from $3,073.5 billion the previous week, revised
from $3,076.6 billion.
   The narrowest measure of the money supply, M1, held steady at a
seasonally adjusted $789.2 billion. The previous week's figure was
revised from an original report of $789.5 billion.
   M1 includes cash in circulation, deposits in checking accounts
and non-bank travelers checks. M2 is M1 plus accounts like savings
deposits and money-market mutual funds. M3 is M2 plus less-liquid
accounts, such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations
of $100,000.
   In judging its monetary policy, the Fed has indicated it is
monitoring the value of the dollar, commodity prices and the
difference between short- and long-term interest rates in addition
to the two broader money supply measures.
   The Fed in February reaffirmed a provisional target for 1989 of 3
percent to 7 percent growth in M2 and 3.5 percent to 7.5 percent
growth in M3. The Fed has not set a target for M1 growth since early
1987.
   For the latest 13 weeks, M2 averaged $3,068.9 billion, a 3.3
percent seasonally adjusted annual rate of gain from the previous 13
weeks. M3 averaged $3,925.2 billion, up 4.7 percent, while M1 rose
1.5 percent to an average of $788.0 billion.
   In other reports:
   _The Federal Reserve said bank borrowings from the Federal
Reserve System at the discount window averaged $793 million a day,
up from $308 million.
   _The Federal Reserve said net free reserves totaled $365 million
in the latest two weeks, down from $649 million in the previous two
weeks.
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis reported that the monetary
base, the seasonally adjusted total of member bank reserves held at
Federal Reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and in circulation,
was $287.5 billion in the two-week period ended Wednesday, up from
$287.4 billion two weeks earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890309-0281 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 1843EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Lorenzo     03-09 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Lorenzo,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lorenzo Says He's Not `Talk-Show Type'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines boss Frank Lorenzo, singled out
by strikers as viciously anti-union, said Thursday he is the wrong
target and the real issue in the emotion-charged walkout is the
impact of deregulation.
   Lorenzo also rejected criticism about his silence since the
strike began, saying he was too busy.
   ``We do have limited amounts of time,'' Lorenzo said in a
telephone interview following his announcement that strike-torn
Eastern had filed for protection from creditors in bankruptcy court.
``I'm not the type that travels from talk show to talk show.''
   There has been criticism in recent days of Lorenzo for not making
a public appearance since the start of the Machinists union strike
last Saturday. Pilots and flight attendants have joined the strikers
in sympathy.
   Lorenzo, who controls Miami-based Eastern through his Texas Air
Corp. holding company, earlier had told a news conference that the
animosity union leaders have expressed toward him had ``hurt my
family and me.''
   ``But I suggest that the intensive focus on a single person does
a real gross injustice to the real issues that are at stake in
airline deregulation and, indeed, in our business climate today,''
he said.
   For labor leaders, Lorenzo symbolizes union-busting and
antagonistic management. He is vilified by some as an archenemy of
working America.
   Union leaders lashed out at him Thursday as a ``robber baron.''
   ``The personalization of this has hurt me, has hurt my family a
lot,'' Lorenzo said in the interview. He added that it's difficult
when his four children, aged five to 15, ask him, ```Dad, what's
going on?'''
   But, Lorenzo said, he is ``far more troubled by the thousands of
employees whose lives have been very severely affected'' by the
Eastern strike.
   Eastern announced Monday that it was shutting down virtually all
its operations and laying off around 9,500 non-union employees. The
airline had 31,200 employees before the strike.
   ``I know the emotions; I know how difficult it is for them to
make individual decisions,'' Lorenzo said.
</TEXT>
