<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Delta     03-09 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Delta,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Delta Mum On Possibility Of Buying Eastern Property</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern Bankruptcy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delta Air Lines refused to say Thursday if it was
considering buying gates or other properties from strikebound
Eastern Airlines but acknowledged an interest in ``any new
opportunities.''
   There has been industry speculation that Delta would be among
those seeking to snap up Eastern's assets if the Miami-based airline
starts selling some or all of its property as part of its bankruptcy
reorganization.
   Eastern, virtually grounded since its Machinists union went on
strike Saturday, filed for protection from creditors in bankruptcy
court on Thursday.
   Among the company's assets are 48 domestic gates at Hartsfield
Atlanta International Airport, where Eastern has its largest hub.
   Archrival Delta has 55 of the airport's 132 domestic gates,
according to airport spokesman John Braden.
   Delta spokeswoman Jackie Pate said company and federal regulatory
policies prevented any comment on possible mergers, acquisitions or
major investments.
   Asked if the company generally would be interested in acquiring
more gates at Hartsfield Atlanta International Airport, where Delta
is the dominant carrier, Ms. Pate said, ``In the past we have
expressed interest in acquiring new gates and would be interested in
any new opportunities.''
   Systemwide, Delta has 389 jets and handles 2,265 flights a day,
Ms. Pate said. The company had earnings of $185.1 million during its
last quarter ended Dec. 31.
   Delta's major acquisition of recent years was its $860 million
merger with Western Air Lines in 1987. Western 102 airplanes to the
Delta fleet and increased the number of cities served by Delta to
153.
   Braden said Eastern's lease on its Hartsfield space runs through
2010.
   ``Those gates are valuable,'' Braden said. ``They have a
proprietary interest in them.''
   Last year, Braden said, Eastern paid a total of $23 million to
Hartsfield for gate rental, landing fees, security fees, cargo space
and other facilities.
   Delta and some of the smaller airlines operating at Hartsfield
have absorbed much of the traffic that Eastern would be handling
from Atlanta. But Ms. Pate said Delta flights are not full and
passengers should have little trouble getting tickets.
   ``We still have a lot of empty seats,'' she said. ``There are
even still some discount seats available if the passengers are
flexible (about schedules).''
   Delta spokesman Neil Monroe said the airline will be increasing
its daily flights out of Atlanta from 400 to 406 next week, but he
said that increase has been planned for several months.
</TEXT>
