<FIRST>u f AM-YugoBankruptcy     03-09 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugo Bankruptcy,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Grants Yugo Effort To Halt Sale Of Liquidator's Cars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TODD RICHISSIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yugo America Inc. on Thursday won an early
victory in the company's effort to reorganize its finances as a
bankruptcy judge barred a liquidator from selling 4,800 automobiles
below wholesale.
   Such a sale would erode consumer confidence in Yugo and would
destroy any effort by the company to emerge from Chapter 11
bankruptcy protection, which it sought in papers filed Jan. 30, the
judge and the company said.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Vincent J. Commisa told the liquidator,
Norauto Ltd. of Columbus, Ohio, it could not sell the cars.
   ``If the sales were allowed, most dealers would lose money and
never carry the Yugo car again,'' Commisa said in his ruling. ``It
in effect could completely destroy all efforts of reorganization.''
   Impex Car Corp., the U.S. agent for the car's Yugoslav maker, has
battled for control of the cars.
   Norauto insists it bought the cars last fall and should be
allowed to sell them at whatever price it wants.
   But Yugo, of Upper Saddle River, and Impex, of New York, argued
that the financial pact with Norauto was meant only to pump some
much needed cash into the financially ailing company.
   Jeremy Golton, an attorney for Norauto, declined comment on the
judge's decision, but said an appeal is likely.
   The 4,800 autos in question are among 6,000 sitting at U.S.
ports. Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co. has liens on the balance.
   Along with Yugo, parent company Global Motors Inc. and sister
company Proton America filed for bankruptcy protection. They said
more than 300 companies and individuals, led by Manufacturers
Hanover, may hold claims against them.
   Yugo touted its boxy subcompact cars as the cheapest new auto in
the United States when they went on sale in August 1985 at $3,995.
   Sales topped 39,100 in the first 10 months of 1987, but dropped
to 26,000 in the same period of 1988, according to figures released
by the company.
</TEXT>
