<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Unions 1stLd-Writethru   03-09 0860</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Unions, 1st Ld - Writethru,0883</SECOND>
<HEAD>Machinists, Others Vow To Keep Fighting</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with new union comments. Also moved on general
news wires.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking Eastern workers, initially stunned by
Thursday's announcement that the airline would seek bankruptcy
protection, quickly became angry and vowed to keep picketing and
fighting ``robber baron'' Frank Lorenzo.
   ``Hang in there! It's not over!'' Local Vice President Frank
Ortis shouted to hundreds of Eastern employees who gathered at a
Machinists union hall as news of the Chapter 11 filing began
circulating in the morning.
   The Machinists union called for a boycott of Eastern's sister
airline, Continental, and Eastern's unions said they would devise
their own plan for reorganizing the airline.
   ``Chapter 11 means there's still a patient and it's undergoing
surgery and it's coming back,'' said John Bavis, head of the Eastern
pilots. ``That's better than the continued slow dismantling of
Eastern under Texas Air.''
   Workers at the union hall temporarily put aside worries about
their futures, including the immediate problem of trying to get
paychecks due this week, to await news of the company action at the
hall across the street from corporate headquarters.
   Jammed around TV sets, workers booed and shouted epithets at
Lorenzo, chairman of Eastern parent Texas Air Corp., and Eastern
President Phil Bakes as they told reporters about the bankruptcy
filing in New York.
   There were cheers for Machinists District 100 President Charles
E. Bryan's televised news conference at the nearby district
headquarters.
   ``It certainly is a sad day for Eastern,'' said Bryan, the
combative union leader who leads 8,500 mechanics, baggage handlers
and other ground workers who went on strike Saturday after talks
broke down in their 17-month contract dispute. The strike virtually
shut down Eastern when pilots and flight attendants refused to cross
Machinists picket lines.
   The pilots union, blamed by Eastern management for forcing the
bankruptcy reorganization, planned a news conference later.
   ``We will prevail,'' said Bryan, his voice rising and his eyes
flashing. ``This is Frank Lorenzo's conspiracy. This is Frank
Lorenzo's strike.''
   Bavis said management continued calling pilots at home in hopes
some would return to work. He said the effort would fail.
   Bryan said poor management, not unions, were to blame, and he
repeated charges he has made for three years that Lorenzo intended
from the start to try to break the unions and carve up Eastern.
   Bryan said his union will fight Lorenzo in bankruptcy court and
in Washington and will picket everything touched by Texas Air,
ranging from Eastern to a fuel tanker in Corpus Christi, Texas, to
sister carrier Continental, where Lorenzo had labor contracts
abrogated during bankruptcy reorganization in 1983. The union is
urging a nationwide boycott of Continental, which Bryan says is
Lorenzo's ``war machine'' to take advantage of Eastern's shutdown by
expanding its low-cost services on Eastern routes.
   ``There's never been a more classic example of a robber baron,''
Bryan said. ``Anytime anyone buys a ticket on Continental, they're
making a contribution to treachery ... to atrocity ... to evil.''
   ``The entire labor movement learned something from the
Continental experience, and this time Lorenzo and his flunkies are
learning something about the power of union solidarity,'' United
Auto Workers President Owen Bieber said in a statement.
   Bryan urged workers not to panic. A mechanic who started at
Eastern 33 years ago and was involved in Eastern's previous strikes,
in 1958 and 1966, Bryan predicted that community businesses and
mortgage-holders would be lenient.
   His union urged workers to file for unemployment compensation,
although it was doubtful strikers would qualify. Wally Haber, a
Machinists district general chairman, said strikers were urged to
seek financial counseling and loans from the Eastern employees
credit union, which Haber said was in good shape.
   However, the company indicated that this week's paychecks for
Eastern employees, whose pay for a given work week arrives the
following week, were frozen at Thursday's announcement. Union
attorneys are likely to ask bankruptcy court to order the checks
released.
   Haber said under union rules, $100 weekly strike-fund payments
won't begin for two more weeks.
   While workers promised to keep picketing, many said they couldn't
wait for the outcome of reorganization or a possible buyout by Trans
World Airways Chairman Carl Icahn, which Bryan continued to think
was possible.
   ``Starting tomorrow, I'll be looking for another job after 12
years here,'' said Cynthia Carrasco, an officer service worker and
single mother of two.
   ``But I'll still be right out here picketing and protesting. I
want my paycheck. I've got rent, food, clothing to buy.''
   Yurbano Mayorquin, 21-year electronics technician, said he'll be
looking for a new job at age 55 but had no second thoughts about the
strike.
   ``We're all grown-up people. We knew we were taking risks,''
Mayorquin. ``But the end was coming. They were dismantling the
airline. The end was coming now or it was going to be later.''
   Company spokesman James Ashlock, a 22-year Eastern employee, said
the 1,500 remaining workers who had not joined the strike or been
laid off this week were working ``until we are told otherwise.''
</TEXT>
