<FIRST>u f AM-Texaco-Kinnear     03-09 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Texaco-Kinnear,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texaco President Says Icahn Stimulated Company; Announces Compensation
Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texaco Inc. President James W. Kinnear
reluctantly admitted Thursday that its restructuring was at least
partly due to an old adversary and the oil giant's biggest
shareholder, takeover investor Carl Icahn.
   ``You'd like to say no,'' Kinnear told a meeting of business
executives. ``But if you say that (what Icahn did) galvanized and
got the attention of the rest of the organization, I'd have to say
that's possible. I think you have to ask yourself at what cost. But
I think there's an element of that.''
   At a meeting sponsored by the Conference Board, a New York-based
business research organization, Kinnear also announced a new
incentive program for Texaco's top management.
   Kinnear said compensation would be based on several criteria,
including how well executives improve company earnings and return on
investments.
   ``In my case, about three-quarters of my compensation will vary
with how well we do ... Clearly, it's to the benefit of
shareholders,'' he said.
   Texaco in January announced the completion of a restructuring
plan which involved the sale of more than $7 billion in assets,
streamlining of management and decentralization of decision-making.
   The restructuring followed the company's emergence from Chapter
11 bankruptcy last year and was completed only after Texaco made a
deal with Icahn, a takeover speculator who acquired a big chunk of
the company's stock during and after the bankruptcy period.
   He made an unsuccessful offer for Texaco last year, an effort
that the company's management dismissed as an insincere attempt to
blackmail Texaco into buying his shares.
   The nation's third-largest oil company originally sought refuge
in bankruptcy court in April 1987, to avoid having to post a
potentially ruinous security bond of more than $10 billion as part
of a court battle with Pennzoil Co. over Texaco's acquisition of
Getty Oil Co. four years earlier.
   Since the restructuring, many industry analysts have credited
Icahn, Texaco's largest shareholder, with igniting Texaco management
into making changes that they believe it otherwise would not have
made.
   In late January, Texaco announced it had struck a deal with Icahn
under which the financier agreed not to boost his 17 percent stake
in the company for seven years or to make another takeover bid.
   Texaco in turn agreed to spend $2.4 billion in special dividend
payments to shareholders and to repurchase some of its stock in
order to boost the value of the shares. Analysts estimate that Icahn
stands to gain $300 million if the plan is approved by shareholders
at the annual meeting in May.
   On Thursday, Kinnear called for changes in public policy and tax
laws that encourage takeovers and attention to short-term gains
instead of long-term growth. One law that should be changed, he
said, allows a tax deduction for interest on loans for takeovers.
   ``Such tax reforms would encourage shareholders to view holdings
as long-term investments not simply the local roulette table,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
