<FIRST>u f AM-Alar-Apples Bjt   03-09 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Alar-Apples, Bjt,0528</SECOND>
<HEAD>Taiwan Company Cancels Orders, Reflecting Industry Trouble From Controversy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `That is ...,' to fix garble.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Taiwanese exporter said Thursday it had
canceled a large order for Washington apples because of concerns
over the health effects of the chemical Alar, the latest sign of
slowing sales due to the controversy.
   W.L.H. Group, of Seattle, this week cancelled an order for 5,000
boxes of Washington apples and may not order any more U.S. apples
the rest of the season, said Sue Lin, an employee in the Seattle
office.
   Taiwanese consumers have stopped buying U.S. apples after hearing
alarming news accounts about Alar, Ms. Lin said.
   ``Everybody is scared about that (Alar),'' Ms. Lin said in a
telephone interview. ``The market has become real bad.''
   Taiwan is the largest off-shore importer of Washington apples,
buying about 50,000 42-pound boxes per week, according to the
Northwest Horticultural Council.
   Ms. Lin said her company's weekly orders are worth about $70,000.
The current selling season extends into August, so the loss to
Washington growers could top $1.5 million.
   That is a fairly small amount compared to the $312 million the
5,000 growers in Washington state earned last year. But it is also
the most disturbing sign that the Alar controversy is hurting the
industry.
   Alar, made by Uniroyal Chemical Co., is a growth regulator that
is sprayed on trees to make the apples hang longer. That gives them
better color and firmness and allows growers extra harvest time.
   The controversy erupted last week when the private Natural
Resources Defense Council issued a report that claimed preschoolers
exposed to Alar-treated apples ran a cancer risk of about one case
for every 4,000 children exposed.
   Growers and the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency have
denounced the report as misleading and alarmist.
   Growers contend they voluntarily have cut back on Alar _ the
trade name for daminozide _ since concerns about the chemical first
were raised three years ago.
   Only about 5 percent of the total U.S. apple acreage is treated
with the chemical and it is used within allowable federal limits,
the industry contends.
   The EPA has proposed banning Alar by 1990, but its health effects
are still in dispute and the chemical is legal to use.
   The first accurate indication of how much the NRDC report has
hurt apple sales was expected Friday, when major apple-marketing
organizations in Washington state release their weekly shipping
reports.
   ``We have had a few isolated reports of sales dropping,'' said
Maureen Miklavic, spokeswoman for the International Apple Institute
in McLean, Va.
   She said the decision by the Taiwanese company was the only
international cancellation she had heard about.
   Ms. Lin said her company intends to purchase apples from Chile to
send to Taiwan.
   The 5,000-box cancellation was with the Northern Fruit Co. of
Wenatchee. Export sales manager Greg Clevenger said his impression
was that domestic sales are down, but he said ``it will turn around
once the public gets more informed.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
