<DOCNO> AP890309-0290 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 2354EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-MinimumWage 1stLd-Writethru f0223 03-09 0647</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Minimum Wage, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0223,0662</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel OKs Hike, Drawing White House Fire</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 11th graf pvs, `Hawkins said ...,' to show Senate action
now not expected before April; picks up 12th graf, `The minimum ...'; Also
moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House panel on Thursday approved legislation
to gradually add $1.30 an hour to the $3.35 minimum wage as
Democratic leaders said they're willing to compromise with the Bush
administration by adding a reduced ``training wage'' for new workers.
   The move to raise the minimum for the first time in eight years
was approved on a party-line vote by the House labor standards
subcommittee. The bill, nearly identical to one approved by the
Senate Labor and Human Resources Committee Wednesday, would raise
the minimum over three years to $4.65 by 1991.
   The administration wants to increase the minimum wage to $4.25 an
hour over three years and insists on the training wage provision
allowing the minimum to stay at $3.35 an hour for all newly hired
workers' first six months on the job.
   A spokeswoman for Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole said Thursday
the administration is sticking by its ``last offer'' and is prepared
to veto a more ambitious plan.
   ``Nothing that happened in the Congress was unexpected,'' said
spokeswoman Dale Tate. ``The entire package is the bottom line, both
the $4.25 figure and the six-month training wage at $3.35. ... We've
come more than halfway towards meeting the goal in terms of meeting
the minimum wage (increase proponents).''
   Rep. Augustus Hawkins, D-Calif., chairman of the House Education
and Labor Committee, said he expects negotiations over the
sub-minimum despite the strong Bush administration stance.
   Hawkins was asked whether he takes the veto threat seriously and
replied:
   ``No, I don't. It's the nature of a president's position to say
such things. We're not going to be threatened by a veto. We still
have to legislate.''
   House Democrats said they are prepared to include a sub-minimum
wage if strict education and training requirements are included and
committee staffers said they are considering a duration of 30 to 90
days.
   ``I can see justification in a short training period for some
minimum-wage employees,'' said subcommittee Chairman Rep. Austin
Murphy, D-Pa.
   Hawkins said the full House Education and Labor Committee will
take up the increase next Tuesday and he predicted a vote by the
full chamber the following week. A spokeswoman for Senate Majority
Leader George Mitchell said late Thursday that a vote in the Senate
is not expected until April, after the Easter recess.
   The minimum wage has stood at $3.35 an hour since 1981.
   Democrats would make the minimum $3.85 an hour this year and add
40 cents an hour in each of the next two years. Republicans want to
add 30 cents an hour annually for three years.
   Democrats and organized labor have long opposed a training wage,
but gave qualified acceptance to the idea this week, sparking hopes
that Congress would pass an increase in the minimum wage agreeable
to Bush, who has said he would veto legislation raising the minimum
above $4.25.
   ``If they want to have a training wage, we will discuss it with
them,'' Hawkins said Thursday. He said such a provision, along with
specific training, would have to be limited to first-time workers
and would have to be for a shorter duration than six months.
   ``Recent White House proposals ... are both constructive and
encouraging,'' said Murphy. ``On the question of a training wage, we
are working hard to put together a proposal to be introduced, either
in full committee or on the House floor.''
   ``Our amendment will be more restrictive than the proposals we
have heard from the president. However, our effort will show we are
sincere and prepared to address all the components of this issue,''
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890309-0291 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 2141EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>b f AM-Eastern-Bankruptcy 2ndLd-Writethru   03-09 0860</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Bankruptcy, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0887</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bankruptcy Filing Keeps Eastern Alive _ For Now</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 4th graf to list total assets and liabilities; picks up
5th graf, The filing ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Filing for bankruptcy protection gives Eastern
Airlines a chance to fly again without worrying about more than $3
billion in liabilities, but doesn't stop the strike-torn carrier
from selling assets or shutting down for good.
   Industry analysts and bankruptcy lawyers said Thursday's filing
for protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of federal bankruptcy
law does not guarantee the airline's survival.
   ``They don't have much left. I think they're a dead duck,'' said
Paul Gibson Jr., a New York attorney who was an American Airlines
vice president in the 1970s and early 1980s.
   Eastern said it had $4.5 billion in assets, $3.39 billion in
liabilities, and 15,696 creditors. It filed its petition in U.S.
Bankruptcy Court in Manhattan.
   The filing does not specify how Miami-based Eastern plans to
resurrect its crippled operations, but analysts said the sale of the
carrier _ possibly to Trans World Airlines owner Carl C. Icahn _ or
a piece-by-piece dismantling were possibilities.
   Eastern must prove to Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland that any
asset sale is crucial for raising money to stay airborne, or that
the airline can't survive at all and must be sold.
   ``If they have to raise cash to operate week-to-week or
month-to-month they can get by with the sale of a couple planes,''
said Richard Lieb, a New York bankruptcy lawyer. ``But if it's a
very significant transaction there is some real doubt whether it
could happen.''
   As such, Eastern filing throws the pending $365 million sale of
its Northeast shuttle service to New York developer Donald Trump
into the judge's hands.
   It also delays a proposed $85 million sale to USAir of Eastern
gates in Philadelphia and routes from that city to Toronto and
Montreal.
   Chapter 11 is designed to allow companies to operate normally
during reoganization, but assures nothing.
   Eastern, for instance, must find pilots to fly its planes. In
1982, Braniff Airways tried to reorganize and keep flying under
Chapter 11 but had to suspend operations before it was sold and
brought out of bankruptcy.
   Any reorganization plan must be approved by the judge and by
creditors.
   Secured creditors, who have collateral from the airline, would be
the first to get paid. Unsecured creditors, including passengers
with unused Eastern tickets, have no security in case of default and
cannot get reimbursed until the end of the case _ if at all.
   Eastern reported secured debt of $1.49 billion, while its largest
unsecured creditor, the Bank of New York, is owed $150 million.
   Some industry analysts believe bankruptcy court was a better
option for Eastern than a total sale of assets, where buyers
probably would have bid rock-bottom prices.
   ``Now because bankruptcy court is protecting the company and the
creditors, Eastern will only accept an offer that is a fair offer,''
said James Carey, vice president for research for Airline Economics
Inc.
   Eastern's major individual assets include airport gates and
landing slots, its South American routes and its Miami maintenance
facility. Wall Street estimates Eastern is worth $400 million to
$900 million as a unit.
   Eastern President Phil Bakes said in court papers the airline had
$200 million in cash left from more than $400 million on hand at the
outset of 1989. That money, needed to run daily operations, would
have run out in about 45 days and Eastern would have been forced out
of business, he said.
   Eastern has lost $1.02 billion this decade compared to industry
earnings of $2.89 billion, the papers said. The airline said it was
losing $4 million a day during the walkout by mechanics, pilots and
flight attendants, which began last Saturday.
   ``While other airlines have been able to apply revenue to
expansion projects ... Eastern has been required to apply its
revenue to primarily servicing debt obligations and meeting labor
costs,'' Bakes said.
   Eastern said its payments on total debt of $2.5 billion were
about $575 million last year. The airline says it needs more than
$200 million in labor cost savings to remain in business.
   Bakes blamed unions for forcing Eastern to seek bankruptcy
protection, saying they want to wrest control of the airline from
parent Texas Air Corp. and avenge the 1983 takeover of Continental
Airlines by Texas Air Chairman Frank Lorenzo.
   Lorenzo took Continental into bankruptcy in 1983, broke union
contracts, fired two-thirds of its workers and emerged with a
non-union airline. That led Congress to amend bankruptcy laws that
now require Lorenzo to negotiate with Eastern unions and get the
judge's approval before abrogating any pacts.
   Experts believe Lorenzo miscalculated that Eastern's 3,600 pilots
would support the Machinists walkout and probably did not envision
bankruptcy. But some also said Lorenzo's long-term intentions after
acquiring Eastern in 1986 may have been less than innocent.
   ``I think he wanted to walk along the edge and continue his
stripping down of the operations. As a wheeler-dealer, he doesn't
want a court looking over his head,'' said Gibson, the former
American executive.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
